{"title_page": "R\u00faben Neves", "text_new": "{{short description|Portuguese footballer}}\n{{Distinguish|R\u00faben Neves (footballer, born 1991)}}\n{{Portuguese name|da Silva|Neves}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = R\u00faben Neves\n| image = DK-Porto15 (4).jpg\n| image_size = \n| upright = 0.9\n| caption = Neves playing for [[FC Porto|Porto]] in 2015\n| fullname = R\u00faben Diogo da Silva Neves<ref name=SW/>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|3|13|df=y}}<ref name=SW/>\n| birth_place = [[Mozelos (Santa Maria da Feira)|Mozelos]], Portugal\n| height = {{height|m=1.83}}<ref name=FPFprofile/>\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n| clubnumber = 8\n| youthyears1 = 2005\u20132014\n| youthclubs1 = [[FC Porto|Porto]]\n| youthyears2 = 2012\u20132013\n| youthclubs2 = \u2192 [[Padroense F.C.|Padroense]] (loan)\n| years1 = 2014\u20132017\n| clubs1 = [[FC Porto|Porto]]\n| caps1 = 59\n| goals1 = 3\n| years2 = 2017\u2013\n| clubs2 = [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n| caps2 = 106\n| goals2 = 12\n| nationalyears1 = 2012\u20132013\n| nationalteam1 = [[Portugal national under-16 football team|Portugal U16]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 10\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2012\u20132014\n| nationalteam2 = [[Portugal national under-17 football team|Portugal U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 31\n| nationalgoals2 = 2\n| nationalyears3 = 2013\n| nationalteam3 = [[Portugal national under-18 football team|Portugal U18]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 2\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2014\u20132017\n| nationalteam4 = [[Portugal national under-21 football team|Portugal U21]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 23\n| nationalgoals4 = 4\n| nationalyears5 = 2016\n| nationalteam5 = [[Portugal Olympic football team|Portugal U23]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 1\n| nationalgoals5 = 1\n| nationalyears6 = 2015\u2013\n| nationalteam6 = [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]]\n| nationalcaps6 = 13\n| nationalgoals6 = 0\n| club-update = 16:19, 2 April 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 21:50, 10 September 2019 (UTC)\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{fb|POR}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[UEFA Nations League]]}}\n{{Medal|Winner|[[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals|2019 Portugal]]|}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]]|}}\n{{Medal|Runner-up|[[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2015 Czech Republic]]|}}\n}}\n'''R\u00faben Diogo da Silva Neves''' ({{IPA-pt|n\u025bv\u0283|eu}}; born 13 March 1997) is a Portuguese professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays [[On the bench]] for [[Premier League]] club [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] and the [[Portugal national football team|Portugal national team]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Porto===\nBorn in [[Mozelos (Santa Maria da Feira)]], [[Aveiro District]], Neves grew up supporting [[FC Porto]] and joined the club's youth system at the age of 8.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/sep/21/ruben-neves-diogo-jota-wolves-porto-cricket-interview|title=Wolves\u2019 R\u00faben Neves and Diogo Jota: \u2018Porto has wine, food but here it\u2019s fine\u2019|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|first=Stuart|last=James|date=21 September 2018|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=PortuGoal>{{cite web|url=https://portugoal.net/on-the-rise/356-profile-of-porto-prodigy-ruben-neves|title=Profile of Porto prodigy R\u00faben Neves|publisher=PortuGOAL|date=24 December 2015|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref> During his time with the academy, he also spent a season on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] at [[Padroense F.C.|Padroense]] which acted as the under-16 side;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2132818.html|title=The rapid rise of R\u00faben Neves|publisher=UEFA|last=Pimentel|first=Jos\u00e9 Nuno|accessdate=20 August 2014|date=17 August 2014}}</ref> on his time in the youth structures, [[FC Porto B|reserve team]] manager [[Lu\u00eds Castro (Portuguese footballer)|Lu\u00eds Castro]] described him as a player with \"extraordinary mental qualities, to go along with technical and tactical skills\".<ref name=PortuGoal/>\n\nAhead of the [[2014\u201315 Primeira Liga|2014\u201315 campaign]], Neves was earmarked to bypass Porto's under-19s and play with the reserves instead. Following an injury to teammate [[Mikel Agu]], however, he was called by [[Julen Lopetegui]] to be part of the main squad's pre-season preparations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/interior/ruben-neves-tem-um-talento-mental-extraordinario-4070889.html|title=R\u00faben Neves tem um talento mental extraordin\u00e1rio|trans-title=R\u00faben Neves has an extraordinary mental talent|newspaper=[[O Jogo]]|language=pt|date=8 August 2014|accessdate=21 August 2014}}</ref> On 15 August 2014, aged 17 years and five months, he made his [[Primeira Liga]] debut where he started and scored in a 2\u20130 home win against [[C.S. Mar\u00edtimo|Mar\u00edtimo]] \u2013 in doing so, he became the youngest player in the club's history to score a goal in the competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/liga-fc-porto-maritimo-cronica/53ee72880cf2c1dfdf15bb68.html|title=FC Porto-Mar\u00edtimo, 2\u20130 (cr\u00f3nica)|trans-title=FC Porto-Mar\u00edtimo, 2\u20130 (report)|publisher=Mais Futebol|last=Almeida|first=Germano|language=pt|date=15 August 2014|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref> He played his first match in the [[UEFA Champions League]] five days later in a 1\u20130 win over [[Lille OSC|Lille]], and broke another record (previously held by [[Cristiano Ronaldo]]) by being the youngest Portuguese to appear in the tournament.<ref name=PortuGoal/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/liga-campeoes-fc-porto-ruben-neves-cristiano-ronaldo-lille-play-off/53f4eee90cf2103fd4482b11.html|title=R\u00faben Neves o portugu\u00eas mais novo de sempre a jogar na ''Champions''|trans-title=R\u00faben Neves the youngest Portuguese ever to play in the Champions|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=pt|date=20 August 2014|accessdate=21 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 December 2014, during a [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League|Champions League group stage]] fixture against [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|Shakhtar Donetsk]], Neves suffered an injury to his right knee following a collision in midfield with [[Alex Teixeira]]. At the end of the game, the club explained that he suffered a sprain, with apparent damage to the internal lateral ligament.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/interior/ruben-neves-com-lesao-no-joelho-direito-4288722.html|title=R\u00faben Neves com les\u00e3o no joelho direito|trans-title=R\u00faben Neves with right knee injury|newspaper=O Jogo|language=pt|date=10 December 2014|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> After spending nearly a month on the sidelines, he returned to the pitch in a [[2014\u201315 Ta\u00e7a da Liga|3\u20131 home win]] over [[C.F. Uni\u00e3o|Uni\u00e3o da Madeira]] in the [[Ta\u00e7a da Liga]];<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/fc-porto/detalhe/ruben-neves-regressa-aos-convocados-924835.html|title=R\u00faben Neves regressa aos convocados|trans-title=R\u00faben Neves returns to squad|newspaper=[[Record (newspaper)|Record]]|language=pt|date=12 January 2015|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> following his injury, his role in midfield was filled by [[Casemiro]] and he spent the majority of the remainder of the season behind the Brazilian in the pecking order.<ref name=PortuGoal/>\n\nOn 20 October 2015, aged 18 years and 221 days, Neves became the youngest player to start as [[Captain (association football)|captain]] in the Champions League, helping Porto to a 2\u20130 win against [[Maccabi Tel Aviv F.C.|Maccabi Tel Aviv]] in [[2015\u201316 UEFA Champions League|the group phase]] and surpassing previous record holder [[Rafael van der Vaart]], who held it since 16 September 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2296033.html|title=Porto's R\u00faben Neves, Iker Casillas make history|publisher=UEFA|date=20 October 2015|accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref> On 5 December, in a 2\u20131 success over [[F.C. Pa\u00e7os de Ferreira|Pa\u00e7os de Ferreira]] also at the [[Est\u00e1dio do Drag\u00e3o]], he broke another record by becoming the youngest player to achieve 50 games for the club, surpassing players like [[Fernando Gomes (footballer)|Fernando Gomes]] and [[Jaime Magalh\u00e3es]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/interior/ruben-neves-e-o-mais-jovem-a-completar-50-jogos-4917762.html|title=R\u00faben Neves \u00e9 o mais jovem a completar 50 jogos|trans-title=R\u00faben Neves is the youngest to complete 50 games|newspaper=O Jogo|language=pt|date=6 December 2015|accessdate=6 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nNeves scored his second competitive goal on 3 February 2016, opening the scoreline in a 3\u20130 triumph at [[Gil Vicente F.C.|Gil Vicente]] for [[2015\u201316 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|the semi-finals]] of the [[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/interior/nunca-e-facil-mudar-de-estrategia-5014013.html|title=Nunca \u00e9 f\u00e1cil mudar de estrat\u00e9gia|trans-title=\"It is never easy to change strategy\"|newspaper=O Jogo|language=pt|date=3 February 2016|accessdate=4 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Wolverhampton Wanderers===\nOn 8 July 2017, [[EFL Championship]] side [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] announced that they had signed Neves for an undisclosed fee, thought to be in the region of \u00a315.8 million \u2013 a club and league record fee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wolves.co.uk/news/first-team/20170708-neves-arrives/|title=Neves arrives!|publisher=Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C|date=8 July 2017|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> Upon joining, he was reunited with former Porto manager [[Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo]].<ref name=Fifty>{{cite web|url=https://www.wolves.co.uk/news/first-team/20181010-50-games-of-neves-a-look-back/|title=50 games of Neves: A look back|publisher=Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C|date=10 October 2018|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref> He scored his first goal on 15 August, in a 3\u20132 away win over [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40858331|title=Hull City 2\u20133 Wolverhampton Wanderers|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=15 August 2017|accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Neves was nominated for the EFL Championship Player of the Season and Young Player of the Season awards, and was also included in the Team of the Season along with teammates [[Conor Coady]] and [[John Ruddy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43641225|title=EFL awards: Tom Cairney, Ruben Neves & Ryan Sessgenon on Championship shortlist|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 April 2018|accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> His team was ultimately [[2017\u201318 EFL Championship|promoted as champions]] with the player scoring six goals in 42 appearances, all of which were scored from outside of the box;<ref name=PR>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/everton-wolves-richarlison-ruben-neves-goals-report-a8488566.html|title=Richarlison and Ruben Neves ready to lead by example for Everton and Wolves|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|last=Nash|first=Tim|date=13 August 2018|accessdate=15 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/693584|title=FPL promotion prospects: The Wolves worth hunting|publisher=[[Premier League]]|date=27 May 2018|accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref> at the conclusion of the campaign, he claimed a hat-trick of club awards as he walked away with the Player of the Season, Player's Player of the Season and Goal of the Season accolades.<ref name=Fifty/> On 7 April 2019 it was also announced that Neves had been awarded the EFL Goal of the Year award (for 2018) for his goal against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] at [[Molineux Stadium|Molineux]] in April 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/football/wolverhampton-wanderers-fc/2019/04/08/ruben-neves-volley-earns-efl-goal-of-the-year-award/|title=Ruben Neves volley earns EFL Goal of the Year award|newspaper=[[Express & Star]]|last=Hatfield|first=Luke|date=8 April 2019|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nWolves announced that Neves had signed a new contract in July 2018, extending until 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44689010|title=Ruben Neves: Wolves midfielder signs new five-year deal|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 July 2018|accessdate=25 July 2018}}</ref> In the first match of [[2018\u201319 Premier League|the new season]], he scored his first [[Premier League]] goal and assisted [[Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez]] in the latter's competitive debut, as his team twice came from behind to draw 2\u20132 against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/aug/11/wolves-everton-premier-league-match-report|title=Wolves\u2019 Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez pegs back 10-man Everton after Richarlison's double|newspaper=The Guardian|last=Aarons|first=Ed|date=11 August 2018|accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/sg/news/wolves-2-everton-2-jimenez-header-ensures-richarlisons-brace-vain|title=Wolves 2 Everton 2: Jimenez header ensures Richarlison's brace in vain|publisher=[[FourFourTwo]]|date=11 August 2018|accessdate=11 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180811232148/https://www.fourfourtwo.com/sg/news/wolves-2-everton-2-jimenez-header-ensures-richarlisons-brace-vain|archive-date=11 August 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> His appearance in the match, alongside compatriots [[Rui Patr\u00edcio]], [[Jo\u00e3o Moutinho]], [[Diogo Jota]] and [[H\u00e9lder Costa (footballer)|H\u00e9lder Costa]] also saw the club break the league record for the most Portuguese players named in a starting line-up.<ref name=PR/>\n\nOn 6 October 2018, Neves made his 50th appearance for Wolverhampton and marked the occasion by contributing in the build-up for [[Matt Doherty (footballer, born 1992)|Matt Doherty]]'s winning goal in a 1\u20130 victory over [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref name=Fifty/> The following January, his 55th-minute winning goal against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] at [[Molineux Stadium|Molineux]] in the [[FA Cup]], \"a venomous dipping shot from {{convert|31|yards|m|abbr=out}} that beat [[Simon Mignolet]] at his near post\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46718633|title=Wolverhampton Wanderers 2\u20131 Liverpool|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Chowdhury|first=Saj|date=7 January 2019|accessdate=7 January 2019}}</ref> was voted the best of [[2018\u201319 FA Cup#Third Round Proper|the third round]] by visitors to [[BBC Sport]]'s website.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46788650|title=FA Cup: Wolves midfielder Ruben Neves wins goal of the FA Cup third round|publisher=BBC Sport|date=8 January 2019|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 September 2019, Neves was made Wolves' club captain for the first time, when he led the team in the absence of regular skipper [[Conor Coady]] as Wolves secured progression to the [[2019\u201320 EFL Cup]] Fourth Round with a penalty shoot-out victory over [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] at Molineux in the clubs' Third Round fixture.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.footballfancast.com/premier-league/wolves/wolves-ruben-neves-posts-on-twitter-after-captaining-the-club-for-the-first-time|title=Wolves\u2019 Ruben Neves posts on Twitter after captaining the club for the first time|publisher=www.footballfancast.com|date=26 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Youth===\n[[File:Ruben Neves avec la selection.jpg|thumb|upright|Neves playing for [[Portugal national under-17 football team|Portugal U17]] in 2014]]Neves represented [[Portugal national under-17 football team|Portugal]] at the [[2014 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]], helping the country reach the semi-finals as [[Captain (association football)|team captain]]. For his performances, he was named among the top ten talents of the tournament by a selection of [[UEFA]] reporters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under17/news/newsid=2106764.html|title=Ten under-17 players to keep an eye on|publisher=UEFA|date=22 May 2014|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 August 2014, still aged 17, Neves was called by coach [[Rui Jorge]] to be part of the [[Portugal national under-21 football team|under-21 side]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/seleccao/euro_sub_21/artigo/2014/08/29/portugal-sub-21-sporting-domina-convocat-ria-ruben-neves-chamado|title=Sporting domina convocat\u00f3ria, Ruben Neves chamado|trans-title=Sporting dominate list, Ruben Neves called|publisher=[[SAPO (company)|SAPO]]|language=pt|date=29 August 2014|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> He scored his first goal on 14 October, helping to a 5\u20134 home win against the [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|Netherlands]] for [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|the playoff round]] of the [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2015/matches/round=2000413/match=2015238/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Portugal through after nine-goal thriller|publisher=UEFA|date=14 October 2014|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhen the finals began in the Czech Republic, Neves broke a new record by becoming the youngest player to debut for the Portuguese under-21s in the tournament, aged 18 years and three months, playing five minutes to help beat [[England national under-21 football team|England]] 1\u20130 in the [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship#Group B|group stage]] opener.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/seleccao/portugal/artigo/2015/06/19/ruben-neves-quebra-recorde-mas-quer-mais-nao-posso-abrandar|title=R\u00faben Neves quebra recorde mas quer mais: \"N\u00e3o posso abrandar\"|trans-title=Ruben Neves breaks record but wants more: \"I can't slow down\"|publisher=SAPO|language=pt|date=19 June 2015|accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref> It was his only appearance, as the country reached [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship Final|the final]] and lost it to [[Sweden national under-21 football team|Sweden]] in a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]].<ref name=UEFA>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2015/matches/round=2000411/match=2015383/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Spot-on Sweden beat Portugal to win U21 EURO|publisher=UEFA|last=Kell|first=Tom|date=30 June 2015|accessdate=3 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Senior===\nNeves was first called up to [[Portugal national football team|the senior squad]] on 10 November 2015, ahead of [[Exhibition game|friendlies]] against [[Russia national football team|Russia]] and [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]] as an injury replacement for [[Jo\u00e3o Moutinho]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/618334/Liverpool-Chelsea-Ruben-Neves-Porto-international-debut-Portugal|title=Liverpool and Chelsea target in high demand as youngster set to make international debut|newspaper=[[Daily Express]]|last=Gray|first=James|date=10 November 2015|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref> He made his debut in the former match, featuring 17 minutes in the 0\u20131 loss in [[Krasnodar]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pt.uefa.com/uefaeuro/qualifiers/news/newsid=2304930.html|title=R\u00fassia vence Portugal em Krasnodar|trans-title=Russia beat Portugal in Krasnodar|publisher=UEFA|language=pt|date=14 November 2015|accessdate=17 November 2015}}</ref> then played the entire 2\u20130 win against the latter at the [[Stade Josy Barthel]], sharing the midfield area with Porto teammates [[Danilo Pereira (Portuguese footballer)|Danilo Pereira]] and [[Andr\u00e9 Andr\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/selecao/andre-andre/luxemburgo-portugal-2-0-cronica|title=Luxemburgo-Portugal, 0\u20132 (cr\u00f3nica)|trans-title=Luxembourg-Portugal, 0\u20132 (report)|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=pt|date=17 November 2015|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/internacional/selecao/noticias/interior/aproveitamos-o-meiocampo-do-fc-porto-4889964.html|title=Aproveitamos o meio-campo do FC Porto|trans-title=We took advantage of the FC Porto midfield|newspaper=O Jogo|language=pt|date=17 November 2015|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nNeves was selected by full side manager [[Fernando Santos (Portuguese footballer)|Fernando Santos]] to a preliminary 35-man squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/amp/news/revealed-every-world-cup-2018-squad-23-man-preliminary-lists/oa0atsduflsv1nsf6oqk576rb|title=Revealed: Every World Cup 2018 squad \u2013 23-man & preliminary lists & when will they be announced?|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|date=17 May 2018|accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref> but he did not make the final cut.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/portugal-world-cup-squad|title=Nearly half Portugal's Euro squad to miss World Cup|publisher=[[Special Broadcasting Service]]|date=17 May 2018|accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals]] on home soil, Neves played in the 3\u20131 semi-final win over [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]], but was dropped from the starting eleven for the [[2019 UEFA Nations League Final|final]] against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] for the more defensive Danilo.<ref>{{cite news |title=Danilo replaces Neves for Portugal in Nations League final |url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/06/09/danilo-replaces-neves-for-portugal-in-nations-league-final |accessdate=16 August 2019 |publisher=Euronews |date=9 June 2019}}</ref> In that match at his former club ground the ''Drag\u00e3o'', he came on in added time for [[William Carvalho]] as the Portuguese won 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite news |title=Portugal 1&ndash;0 The Netherlands |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2019/jun/09/portugal-v-netherlands-nations-league-final-live |accessdate=16 August 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nAn article on [[UEFA|UEFA.com]] described Neves as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]] who is not afraid to go forward and prompt attacks, showing great maturity combined with an accurate passing skill, great vision and an astute sense of positioning. His playing attributes also granted him comparisons to Portuguese international teammate Moutinho for his fine first touch, similar desire to press his opponents and excellent distribution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=por/news/newsid=2241045.html|title=UEFA.com's weekly wonderkid: R\u00faben Neves|publisher=UEFA|date=2 May 2015|accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nNeves also drew praise in the media for his technical, tactical and mental qualities,<ref name=PortuGoal/> as well as his intelligence and long-range shooting ability.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.calciomercato.com/en/news/the-portuguese-star-who-broke-the-records-of-ronaldo-ready-to-jo-72883|title=The Portuguese star who broke the records of Ronaldo ready to join Juventus|publisher=Calcio Mercato|last=Laurenti|first=Mirko|date=23 November 2018|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 12 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|National Cup{{efn|Includes [[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]], [[FA Cup]]}}\n!colspan=2|League Cup{{efn|Includes [[Ta\u00e7a da Liga]], [[EFL Cup]]}}\n!colspan=2|Europe\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[FC Porto|Porto]]\n|[[2014\u201315 FC Porto season|2014\u201315]]<ref name=SW/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fcporto.pt/en/futebol/fichas-de-jogo/Pages/FC-Porto-Sporting-Taca-2014-2015.aspx |title=FC Porto\u2013Sporting Portuguese Cup 3rd round |publisher=FC Porto |date=18 October 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028091019/http://www.fcporto.pt/en/futebol/fichas-de-jogo/Pages/FC-Porto-Sporting-Taca-2014-2015.aspx |archivedate=28 October 2014}}</ref>\n|rowspan=3|[[Primeira Liga]]\n|24||1||1||0||3||0||9{{efn|name=UCL|Appearances in [[UEFA Champions League]]}}||0||37||1\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 FC Porto season|2015\u201316]]<ref name=SW/>\n|22||1||6||1||2||0||8{{efn|Six appearances in UEFA Champions League, two in [[UEFA Europa League]]}}||0||38||2\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 FC Porto season|2016\u201317]]<ref name=SW>{{cite web |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/players/ruben-neves/270474/ |title=R\u00faben Neves |website=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |accessdate=5 February 2019}}</ref>\n|13||1||0||0||2||0||3{{efn|name=UCL}}||0||18||1\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!59||3||7||1||7||0||20||0||93||4\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n|[[2017\u201318 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|2017\u201318]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|77210|2017|accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref>\n|[[EFL Championship|Championship]]\n|42||6||0||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||42||6\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|77210|2018|accessdate=17 May 2019}}</ref>\n|rowspan=2|[[Premier League]]\n|35||4||5||1||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||40||5\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|2019\u201320]]<ref>{{Soccerbase season|77210|2019|accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n|29||2||2||0||1||0||11{{efn|Appearances in UEFA Europa League}}||2||43||4\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!106||12||7||1||1||0||11||2||125||15\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career total\n!165||15||14||2||8||0||31||2||218||19\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n===International===\n{{updated|29 July 2019}}<ref name=FPFprofile>{{cite web |url=https://www.fpf.pt/Jogadores/Jogador/playerId/811036 |title=Jogador: R\u00faben Neves |language=Portuguese |trans-title=Player: R\u00faben Neves |publisher=Federa\u00e7\u00e3o Portuguesa de Futebol |accessdate=29 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! National team !! Year !! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]]\n| 2015 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| 2016 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| 2017 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| 2018 || 5 || 0\n|-\n| 2019 || 3 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Total !! 12 !! 0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Wolverhampton Wanderers'''\n*[[EFL Championship]]: [[2017\u201318 EFL Championship|2017\u201318]]<ref>{{cite book|editor-first=John|editor-last=Anderson|title=Football Yearbook 2018\u20132019|year=2018|publisher=Headline Publishing Group|location=London|isbn=978-1-4722-6106-9|pages=386\u2013387}}</ref>\n\n'''Portugal'''\n*[[UEFA Nations League]]: [[2018\u201319 UEFA Nations League|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/liga-das-nacoes/artigos/portugal-regressa-ao-topo-da-europa-liga-das-nacoes-fica-em-casa|title=Portugal regressa ao topo da Europa. Liga das Na\u00e7\u00f5es fica em casa|trans-title=Portugal returns to the top of Europe. Nations League stays home|publisher=Sapo|date=9 June 2019|accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Portugal U21'''\n*[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] runner-up: [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2015]]<ref name=UEFA/>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[UEFA European Under-17 Championship]] Team of the Tournament: [[2014 UEFA European Under-17 Championship#Team of the Tournament|2014]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under17/season=2014/technical-report/tr-under17-2014.pdf|title=Technical report|publisher=UEFA|pages=21\u201322|format=PDF|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Confedera\u00e7\u00e3o do Desporto de Portugal]] Young Prospect of the Year: 2015<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/interior/ruben-neves-distinguido-como-jovem-promessa-do-ano-4881073.html|title=R\u00faben Neves distinguido como Jovem Promessa do Ano|trans-title=R\u00faben Neves distinguished as Young Prospect of the Year|newspaper=O Jogo|language=pt|date=11 November 2015|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref>\n*EFL Championship Team of the Season: 2017\u201318<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/news/2018/april/efl-awards-2018-shortlists-revealed|title=EFL Awards 2018: Shortlists revealed|publisher=[[English Football League]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref>\n*[[PFA Team of the Year]]: [[PFA Team of the Year (2010s)#Championship 9|2017\u201318 Championship]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43808543|title=PFA Championship Team of the Year: Wolves & Fulham trios named in line-up|publisher=BBC Sport|date=18 April 2018|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{ForaDeJogo}}\n*[https://www.fpf.pt/pt/Jogadores/Pesquisar-Jogadores-Internacionais/Jogador/playerId/811036/contextId/176 National team data] {{in lang|pt}}\n*{{NFT player}}\n*{{UEFA player}}\n\n{{Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Awards\n|bg=gold\n|fg=black\n|list1=\n{{2017\u201318 EFL Championship PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{Football League Goal of the Year}}\n{{Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. Player of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neves, Ruben}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Santa Maria da Feira]]\n[[Category:Portuguese footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Padroense F.C. players]]\n[[Category:FC Porto B players]]\n[[Category:FC Porto players]]\n[[Category:Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Portugal youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Portugal under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Portugal international footballers]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Portuguese footballer}}\n{{Distinguish|R\u00faben Neves (footballer, born 1991)}}\n{{Portuguese name|da Silva|Neves}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = R\u00faben Neves\n| image = DK-Porto15 (4).jpg\n| image_size = \n| upright = 0.9\n| caption = Neves playing for [[FC Porto|Porto]] in 2015\n| fullname = R\u00faben Diogo da Silva Neves<ref name=SW/>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|3|13|df=y}}<ref name=SW/>\n| birth_place = [[Mozelos (Santa Maria da Feira)|Mozelos]], Portugal\n| height = {{height|m=1.83}}<ref name=FPFprofile/>\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n| clubnumber = 8\n| youthyears1 = 2005\u20132014\n| youthclubs1 = [[FC Porto|Porto]]\n| youthyears2 = 2012\u20132013\n| youthclubs2 = \u2192 [[Padroense F.C.|Padroense]] (loan)\n| years1 = 2014\u20132017\n| clubs1 = [[FC Porto|Porto]]\n| caps1 = 59\n| goals1 = 3\n| years2 = 2017\u2013\n| clubs2 = [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n| caps2 = 106\n| goals2 = 12\n| nationalyears1 = 2012\u20132013\n| nationalteam1 = [[Portugal national under-16 football team|Portugal U16]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 10\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2012\u20132014\n| nationalteam2 = [[Portugal national under-17 football team|Portugal U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 31\n| nationalgoals2 = 2\n| nationalyears3 = 2013\n| nationalteam3 = [[Portugal national under-18 football team|Portugal U18]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 2\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2014\u20132017\n| nationalteam4 = [[Portugal national under-21 football team|Portugal U21]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 23\n| nationalgoals4 = 4\n| nationalyears5 = 2016\n| nationalteam5 = [[Portugal Olympic football team|Portugal U23]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 1\n| nationalgoals5 = 1\n| nationalyears6 = 2015\u2013\n| nationalteam6 = [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]]\n| nationalcaps6 = 13\n| nationalgoals6 = 0\n| club-update = 16:19, 2 April 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 21:50, 10 September 2019 (UTC)\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{fb|POR}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[UEFA Nations League]]}}\n{{Medal|Winner|[[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals|2019 Portugal]]|}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]]|}}\n{{Medal|Runner-up|[[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2015 Czech Republic]]|}}\n}}\n'''R\u00faben Diogo da Silva Neves''' ({{IPA-pt|n\u025bv\u0283|eu}}; born 13 March 1997) is a Portuguese professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Premier League]] club [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] and the [[Portugal national football team|Portugal national team]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Porto===\nBorn in [[Mozelos (Santa Maria da Feira)]], [[Aveiro District]], Neves grew up supporting [[FC Porto]] and joined the club's youth system at the age of 8.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/sep/21/ruben-neves-diogo-jota-wolves-porto-cricket-interview|title=Wolves\u2019 R\u00faben Neves and Diogo Jota: \u2018Porto has wine, food but here it\u2019s fine\u2019|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|first=Stuart|last=James|date=21 September 2018|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=PortuGoal>{{cite web|url=https://portugoal.net/on-the-rise/356-profile-of-porto-prodigy-ruben-neves|title=Profile of Porto prodigy R\u00faben Neves|publisher=PortuGOAL|date=24 December 2015|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref> During his time with the academy, he also spent a season on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] at [[Padroense F.C.|Padroense]] which acted as the under-16 side;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2132818.html|title=The rapid rise of R\u00faben Neves|publisher=UEFA|last=Pimentel|first=Jos\u00e9 Nuno|accessdate=20 August 2014|date=17 August 2014}}</ref> on his time in the youth structures, [[FC Porto B|reserve team]] manager [[Lu\u00eds Castro (Portuguese footballer)|Lu\u00eds Castro]] described him as a player with \"extraordinary mental qualities, to go along with technical and tactical skills\".<ref name=PortuGoal/>\n\nAhead of the [[2014\u201315 Primeira Liga|2014\u201315 campaign]], Neves was earmarked to bypass Porto's under-19s and play with the reserves instead. Following an injury to teammate [[Mikel Agu]], however, he was called by [[Julen Lopetegui]] to be part of the main squad's pre-season preparations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/interior/ruben-neves-tem-um-talento-mental-extraordinario-4070889.html|title=R\u00faben Neves tem um talento mental extraordin\u00e1rio|trans-title=R\u00faben Neves has an extraordinary mental talent|newspaper=[[O Jogo]]|language=pt|date=8 August 2014|accessdate=21 August 2014}}</ref> On 15 August 2014, aged 17 years and five months, he made his [[Primeira Liga]] debut where he started and scored in a 2\u20130 home win against [[C.S. Mar\u00edtimo|Mar\u00edtimo]] \u2013 in doing so, he became the youngest player in the club's history to score a goal in the competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/liga-fc-porto-maritimo-cronica/53ee72880cf2c1dfdf15bb68.html|title=FC Porto-Mar\u00edtimo, 2\u20130 (cr\u00f3nica)|trans-title=FC Porto-Mar\u00edtimo, 2\u20130 (report)|publisher=Mais Futebol|last=Almeida|first=Germano|language=pt|date=15 August 2014|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref> He played his first match in the [[UEFA Champions League]] five days later in a 1\u20130 win over [[Lille OSC|Lille]], and broke another record (previously held by [[Cristiano Ronaldo]]) by being the youngest Portuguese to appear in the tournament.<ref name=PortuGoal/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/liga-campeoes-fc-porto-ruben-neves-cristiano-ronaldo-lille-play-off/53f4eee90cf2103fd4482b11.html|title=R\u00faben Neves o portugu\u00eas mais novo de sempre a jogar na ''Champions''|trans-title=R\u00faben Neves the youngest Portuguese ever to play in the Champions|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=pt|date=20 August 2014|accessdate=21 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 December 2014, during a [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League|Champions League group stage]] fixture against [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|Shakhtar Donetsk]], Neves suffered an injury to his right knee following a collision in midfield with [[Alex Teixeira]]. At the end of the game, the club explained that he suffered a sprain, with apparent damage to the internal lateral ligament.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/interior/ruben-neves-com-lesao-no-joelho-direito-4288722.html|title=R\u00faben Neves com les\u00e3o no joelho direito|trans-title=R\u00faben Neves with right knee injury|newspaper=O Jogo|language=pt|date=10 December 2014|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> After spending nearly a month on the sidelines, he returned to the pitch in a [[2014\u201315 Ta\u00e7a da Liga|3\u20131 home win]] over [[C.F. Uni\u00e3o|Uni\u00e3o da Madeira]] in the [[Ta\u00e7a da Liga]];<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/fc-porto/detalhe/ruben-neves-regressa-aos-convocados-924835.html|title=R\u00faben Neves regressa aos convocados|trans-title=R\u00faben Neves returns to squad|newspaper=[[Record (newspaper)|Record]]|language=pt|date=12 January 2015|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> following his injury, his role in midfield was filled by [[Casemiro]] and he spent the majority of the remainder of the season behind the Brazilian in the pecking order.<ref name=PortuGoal/>\n\nOn 20 October 2015, aged 18 years and 221 days, Neves became the youngest player to start as [[Captain (association football)|captain]] in the Champions League, helping Porto to a 2\u20130 win against [[Maccabi Tel Aviv F.C.|Maccabi Tel Aviv]] in [[2015\u201316 UEFA Champions League|the group phase]] and surpassing previous record holder [[Rafael van der Vaart]], who held it since 16 September 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2296033.html|title=Porto's R\u00faben Neves, Iker Casillas make history|publisher=UEFA|date=20 October 2015|accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref> On 5 December, in a 2\u20131 success over [[F.C. Pa\u00e7os de Ferreira|Pa\u00e7os de Ferreira]] also at the [[Est\u00e1dio do Drag\u00e3o]], he broke another record by becoming the youngest player to achieve 50 games for the club, surpassing players like [[Fernando Gomes (footballer)|Fernando Gomes]] and [[Jaime Magalh\u00e3es]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/interior/ruben-neves-e-o-mais-jovem-a-completar-50-jogos-4917762.html|title=R\u00faben Neves \u00e9 o mais jovem a completar 50 jogos|trans-title=R\u00faben Neves is the youngest to complete 50 games|newspaper=O Jogo|language=pt|date=6 December 2015|accessdate=6 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nNeves scored his second competitive goal on 3 February 2016, opening the scoreline in a 3\u20130 triumph at [[Gil Vicente F.C.|Gil Vicente]] for [[2015\u201316 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|the semi-finals]] of the [[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/interior/nunca-e-facil-mudar-de-estrategia-5014013.html|title=Nunca \u00e9 f\u00e1cil mudar de estrat\u00e9gia|trans-title=\"It is never easy to change strategy\"|newspaper=O Jogo|language=pt|date=3 February 2016|accessdate=4 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Wolverhampton Wanderers===\nOn 8 July 2017, [[EFL Championship]] side [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] announced that they had signed Neves for an undisclosed fee, thought to be in the region of \u00a315.8 million \u2013 a club and league record fee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wolves.co.uk/news/first-team/20170708-neves-arrives/|title=Neves arrives!|publisher=Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C|date=8 July 2017|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> Upon joining, he was reunited with former Porto manager [[Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo]].<ref name=Fifty>{{cite web|url=https://www.wolves.co.uk/news/first-team/20181010-50-games-of-neves-a-look-back/|title=50 games of Neves: A look back|publisher=Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C|date=10 October 2018|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref> He scored his first goal on 15 August, in a 3\u20132 away win over [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40858331|title=Hull City 2\u20133 Wolverhampton Wanderers|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=15 August 2017|accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Neves was nominated for the EFL Championship Player of the Season and Young Player of the Season awards, and was also included in the Team of the Season along with teammates [[Conor Coady]] and [[John Ruddy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43641225|title=EFL awards: Tom Cairney, Ruben Neves & Ryan Sessgenon on Championship shortlist|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 April 2018|accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> His team was ultimately [[2017\u201318 EFL Championship|promoted as champions]] with the player scoring six goals in 42 appearances, all of which were scored from outside of the box;<ref name=PR>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/everton-wolves-richarlison-ruben-neves-goals-report-a8488566.html|title=Richarlison and Ruben Neves ready to lead by example for Everton and Wolves|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|last=Nash|first=Tim|date=13 August 2018|accessdate=15 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/693584|title=FPL promotion prospects: The Wolves worth hunting|publisher=[[Premier League]]|date=27 May 2018|accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref> at the conclusion of the campaign, he claimed a hat-trick of club awards as he walked away with the Player of the Season, Player's Player of the Season and Goal of the Season accolades.<ref name=Fifty/> On 7 April 2019 it was also announced that Neves had been awarded the EFL Goal of the Year award (for 2018) for his goal against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] at [[Molineux Stadium|Molineux]] in April 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/football/wolverhampton-wanderers-fc/2019/04/08/ruben-neves-volley-earns-efl-goal-of-the-year-award/|title=Ruben Neves volley earns EFL Goal of the Year award|newspaper=[[Express & Star]]|last=Hatfield|first=Luke|date=8 April 2019|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nWolves announced that Neves had signed a new contract in July 2018, extending until 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44689010|title=Ruben Neves: Wolves midfielder signs new five-year deal|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 July 2018|accessdate=25 July 2018}}</ref> In the first match of [[2018\u201319 Premier League|the new season]], he scored his first [[Premier League]] goal and assisted [[Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez]] in the latter's competitive debut, as his team twice came from behind to draw 2\u20132 against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/aug/11/wolves-everton-premier-league-match-report|title=Wolves\u2019 Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez pegs back 10-man Everton after Richarlison's double|newspaper=The Guardian|last=Aarons|first=Ed|date=11 August 2018|accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/sg/news/wolves-2-everton-2-jimenez-header-ensures-richarlisons-brace-vain|title=Wolves 2 Everton 2: Jimenez header ensures Richarlison's brace in vain|publisher=[[FourFourTwo]]|date=11 August 2018|accessdate=11 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180811232148/https://www.fourfourtwo.com/sg/news/wolves-2-everton-2-jimenez-header-ensures-richarlisons-brace-vain|archive-date=11 August 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> His appearance in the match, alongside compatriots [[Rui Patr\u00edcio]], [[Jo\u00e3o Moutinho]], [[Diogo Jota]] and [[H\u00e9lder Costa (footballer)|H\u00e9lder Costa]] also saw the club break the league record for the most Portuguese players named in a starting line-up.<ref name=PR/>\n\nOn 6 October 2018, Neves made his 50th appearance for Wolverhampton and marked the occasion by contributing in the build-up for [[Matt Doherty (footballer, born 1992)|Matt Doherty]]'s winning goal in a 1\u20130 victory over [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref name=Fifty/> The following January, his 55th-minute winning goal against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] at [[Molineux Stadium|Molineux]] in the [[FA Cup]], \"a venomous dipping shot from {{convert|31|yards|m|abbr=out}} that beat [[Simon Mignolet]] at his near post\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46718633|title=Wolverhampton Wanderers 2\u20131 Liverpool|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Chowdhury|first=Saj|date=7 January 2019|accessdate=7 January 2019}}</ref> was voted the best of [[2018\u201319 FA Cup#Third Round Proper|the third round]] by visitors to [[BBC Sport]]'s website.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46788650|title=FA Cup: Wolves midfielder Ruben Neves wins goal of the FA Cup third round|publisher=BBC Sport|date=8 January 2019|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 September 2019, Neves was made Wolves' club captain for the first time, when he led the team in the absence of regular skipper [[Conor Coady]] as Wolves secured progression to the [[2019\u201320 EFL Cup]] Fourth Round with a penalty shoot-out victory over [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] at Molineux in the clubs' Third Round fixture.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.footballfancast.com/premier-league/wolves/wolves-ruben-neves-posts-on-twitter-after-captaining-the-club-for-the-first-time|title=Wolves\u2019 Ruben Neves posts on Twitter after captaining the club for the first time|publisher=www.footballfancast.com|date=26 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Youth===\n[[File:Ruben Neves avec la selection.jpg|thumb|upright|Neves playing for [[Portugal national under-17 football team|Portugal U17]] in 2014]]Neves represented [[Portugal national under-17 football team|Portugal]] at the [[2014 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]], helping the country reach the semi-finals as [[Captain (association football)|team captain]]. For his performances, he was named among the top ten talents of the tournament by a selection of [[UEFA]] reporters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under17/news/newsid=2106764.html|title=Ten under-17 players to keep an eye on|publisher=UEFA|date=22 May 2014|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 August 2014, still aged 17, Neves was called by coach [[Rui Jorge]] to be part of the [[Portugal national under-21 football team|under-21 side]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/seleccao/euro_sub_21/artigo/2014/08/29/portugal-sub-21-sporting-domina-convocat-ria-ruben-neves-chamado|title=Sporting domina convocat\u00f3ria, Ruben Neves chamado|trans-title=Sporting dominate list, Ruben Neves called|publisher=[[SAPO (company)|SAPO]]|language=pt|date=29 August 2014|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> He scored his first goal on 14 October, helping to a 5\u20134 home win against the [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|Netherlands]] for [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|the playoff round]] of the [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2015/matches/round=2000413/match=2015238/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Portugal through after nine-goal thriller|publisher=UEFA|date=14 October 2014|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhen the finals began in the Czech Republic, Neves broke a new record by becoming the youngest player to debut for the Portuguese under-21s in the tournament, aged 18 years and three months, playing five minutes to help beat [[England national under-21 football team|England]] 1\u20130 in the [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship#Group B|group stage]] opener.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/seleccao/portugal/artigo/2015/06/19/ruben-neves-quebra-recorde-mas-quer-mais-nao-posso-abrandar|title=R\u00faben Neves quebra recorde mas quer mais: \"N\u00e3o posso abrandar\"|trans-title=Ruben Neves breaks record but wants more: \"I can't slow down\"|publisher=SAPO|language=pt|date=19 June 2015|accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref> It was his only appearance, as the country reached [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship Final|the final]] and lost it to [[Sweden national under-21 football team|Sweden]] in a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]].<ref name=UEFA>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2015/matches/round=2000411/match=2015383/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Spot-on Sweden beat Portugal to win U21 EURO|publisher=UEFA|last=Kell|first=Tom|date=30 June 2015|accessdate=3 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Senior===\nNeves was first called up to [[Portugal national football team|the senior squad]] on 10 November 2015, ahead of [[Exhibition game|friendlies]] against [[Russia national football team|Russia]] and [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]] as an injury replacement for [[Jo\u00e3o Moutinho]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/618334/Liverpool-Chelsea-Ruben-Neves-Porto-international-debut-Portugal|title=Liverpool and Chelsea target in high demand as youngster set to make international debut|newspaper=[[Daily Express]]|last=Gray|first=James|date=10 November 2015|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref> He made his debut in the former match, featuring 17 minutes in the 0\u20131 loss in [[Krasnodar]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pt.uefa.com/uefaeuro/qualifiers/news/newsid=2304930.html|title=R\u00fassia vence Portugal em Krasnodar|trans-title=Russia beat Portugal in Krasnodar|publisher=UEFA|language=pt|date=14 November 2015|accessdate=17 November 2015}}</ref> then played the entire 2\u20130 win against the latter at the [[Stade Josy Barthel]], sharing the midfield area with Porto teammates [[Danilo Pereira (Portuguese footballer)|Danilo Pereira]] and [[Andr\u00e9 Andr\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/selecao/andre-andre/luxemburgo-portugal-2-0-cronica|title=Luxemburgo-Portugal, 0\u20132 (cr\u00f3nica)|trans-title=Luxembourg-Portugal, 0\u20132 (report)|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=pt|date=17 November 2015|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/internacional/selecao/noticias/interior/aproveitamos-o-meiocampo-do-fc-porto-4889964.html|title=Aproveitamos o meio-campo do FC Porto|trans-title=We took advantage of the FC Porto midfield|newspaper=O Jogo|language=pt|date=17 November 2015|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nNeves was selected by full side manager [[Fernando Santos (Portuguese footballer)|Fernando Santos]] to a preliminary 35-man squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/amp/news/revealed-every-world-cup-2018-squad-23-man-preliminary-lists/oa0atsduflsv1nsf6oqk576rb|title=Revealed: Every World Cup 2018 squad \u2013 23-man & preliminary lists & when will they be announced?|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|date=17 May 2018|accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref> but he did not make the final cut.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/portugal-world-cup-squad|title=Nearly half Portugal's Euro squad to miss World Cup|publisher=[[Special Broadcasting Service]]|date=17 May 2018|accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals]] on home soil, Neves played in the 3\u20131 semi-final win over [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]], but was dropped from the starting eleven for the [[2019 UEFA Nations League Final|final]] against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] for the more defensive Danilo.<ref>{{cite news |title=Danilo replaces Neves for Portugal in Nations League final |url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/06/09/danilo-replaces-neves-for-portugal-in-nations-league-final |accessdate=16 August 2019 |publisher=Euronews |date=9 June 2019}}</ref> In that match at his former club ground the ''Drag\u00e3o'', he came on in added time for [[William Carvalho]] as the Portuguese won 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite news |title=Portugal 1&ndash;0 The Netherlands |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2019/jun/09/portugal-v-netherlands-nations-league-final-live |accessdate=16 August 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nAn article on [[UEFA|UEFA.com]] described Neves as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]] who is not afraid to go forward and prompt attacks, showing great maturity combined with an accurate passing skill, great vision and an astute sense of positioning. His playing attributes also granted him comparisons to Portuguese international teammate Moutinho for his fine first touch, similar desire to press his opponents and excellent distribution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=por/news/newsid=2241045.html|title=UEFA.com's weekly wonderkid: R\u00faben Neves|publisher=UEFA|date=2 May 2015|accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nNeves also drew praise in the media for his technical, tactical and mental qualities,<ref name=PortuGoal/> as well as his intelligence and long-range shooting ability.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.calciomercato.com/en/news/the-portuguese-star-who-broke-the-records-of-ronaldo-ready-to-jo-72883|title=The Portuguese star who broke the records of Ronaldo ready to join Juventus|publisher=Calcio Mercato|last=Laurenti|first=Mirko|date=23 November 2018|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 12 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|National Cup{{efn|Includes [[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]], [[FA Cup]]}}\n!colspan=2|League Cup{{efn|Includes [[Ta\u00e7a da Liga]], [[EFL Cup]]}}\n!colspan=2|Europe\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[FC Porto|Porto]]\n|[[2014\u201315 FC Porto season|2014\u201315]]<ref name=SW/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fcporto.pt/en/futebol/fichas-de-jogo/Pages/FC-Porto-Sporting-Taca-2014-2015.aspx |title=FC Porto\u2013Sporting Portuguese Cup 3rd round |publisher=FC Porto |date=18 October 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028091019/http://www.fcporto.pt/en/futebol/fichas-de-jogo/Pages/FC-Porto-Sporting-Taca-2014-2015.aspx |archivedate=28 October 2014}}</ref>\n|rowspan=3|[[Primeira Liga]]\n|24||1||1||0||3||0||9{{efn|name=UCL|Appearances in [[UEFA Champions League]]}}||0||37||1\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 FC Porto season|2015\u201316]]<ref name=SW/>\n|22||1||6||1||2||0||8{{efn|Six appearances in UEFA Champions League, two in [[UEFA Europa League]]}}||0||38||2\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 FC Porto season|2016\u201317]]<ref name=SW>{{cite web |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/players/ruben-neves/270474/ |title=R\u00faben Neves |website=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |accessdate=5 February 2019}}</ref>\n|13||1||0||0||2||0||3{{efn|name=UCL}}||0||18||1\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!59||3||7||1||7||0||20||0||93||4\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n|[[2017\u201318 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|2017\u201318]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|77210|2017|accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref>\n|[[EFL Championship|Championship]]\n|42||6||0||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||42||6\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|77210|2018|accessdate=17 May 2019}}</ref>\n|rowspan=2|[[Premier League]]\n|35||4||5||1||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||40||5\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|2019\u201320]]<ref>{{Soccerbase season|77210|2019|accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n|29||2||2||0||1||0||11{{efn|Appearances in UEFA Europa League}}||2||43||4\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!106||12||7||1||1||0||11||2||125||15\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career total\n!165||15||14||2||8||0||31||2||218||19\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n===International===\n{{updated|29 July 2019}}<ref name=FPFprofile>{{cite web |url=https://www.fpf.pt/Jogadores/Jogador/playerId/811036 |title=Jogador: R\u00faben Neves |language=Portuguese |trans-title=Player: R\u00faben Neves |publisher=Federa\u00e7\u00e3o Portuguesa de Futebol |accessdate=29 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! National team !! Year !! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]]\n| 2015 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| 2016 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| 2017 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| 2018 || 5 || 0\n|-\n| 2019 || 3 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Total !! 12 !! 0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Wolverhampton Wanderers'''\n*[[EFL Championship]]: [[2017\u201318 EFL Championship|2017\u201318]]<ref>{{cite book|editor-first=John|editor-last=Anderson|title=Football Yearbook 2018\u20132019|year=2018|publisher=Headline Publishing Group|location=London|isbn=978-1-4722-6106-9|pages=386\u2013387}}</ref>\n\n'''Portugal'''\n*[[UEFA Nations League]]: [[2018\u201319 UEFA Nations League|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/liga-das-nacoes/artigos/portugal-regressa-ao-topo-da-europa-liga-das-nacoes-fica-em-casa|title=Portugal regressa ao topo da Europa. Liga das Na\u00e7\u00f5es fica em casa|trans-title=Portugal returns to the top of Europe. Nations League stays home|publisher=Sapo|date=9 June 2019|accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Portugal U21'''\n*[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] runner-up: [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2015]]<ref name=UEFA/>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[UEFA European Under-17 Championship]] Team of the Tournament: [[2014 UEFA European Under-17 Championship#Team of the Tournament|2014]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under17/season=2014/technical-report/tr-under17-2014.pdf|title=Technical report|publisher=UEFA|pages=21\u201322|format=PDF|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Confedera\u00e7\u00e3o do Desporto de Portugal]] Young Prospect of the Year: 2015<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/interior/ruben-neves-distinguido-como-jovem-promessa-do-ano-4881073.html|title=R\u00faben Neves distinguido como Jovem Promessa do Ano|trans-title=R\u00faben Neves distinguished as Young Prospect of the Year|newspaper=O Jogo|language=pt|date=11 November 2015|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref>\n*EFL Championship Team of the Season: 2017\u201318<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/news/2018/april/efl-awards-2018-shortlists-revealed|title=EFL Awards 2018: Shortlists revealed|publisher=[[English Football League]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref>\n*[[PFA Team of the Year]]: [[PFA Team of the Year (2010s)#Championship 9|2017\u201318 Championship]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43808543|title=PFA Championship Team of the Year: Wolves & Fulham trios named in line-up|publisher=BBC Sport|date=18 April 2018|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{ForaDeJogo}}\n*[https://www.fpf.pt/pt/Jogadores/Pesquisar-Jogadores-Internacionais/Jogador/playerId/811036/contextId/176 National team data] {{in lang|pt}}\n*{{NFT player}}\n*{{UEFA player}}\n\n{{Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Awards\n|bg=gold\n|fg=black\n|list1=\n{{2017\u201318 EFL Championship PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{Football League Goal of the Year}}\n{{Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. Player of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neves, Ruben}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Santa Maria da Feira]]\n[[Category:Portuguese footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Padroense F.C. players]]\n[[Category:FC Porto B players]]\n[[Category:FC Porto players]]\n[[Category:Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Portugal youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Portugal under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Portugal international footballers]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n", "name_user": "92.234.145.230", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Position change)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R%C3%BAben_Neves"}
{"title_page": "Thomas McCarthy (footballer)", "text_new": "{{for|other people with the same name|Thomas McCarthy (disambiguation){{!}}Thomas McCarthy}}\n{{short description|Welsh footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = Thomas McCarthy\n|image          =\n| image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|fullname       =\n|birth_date     = 1868\n|birth_place    = Wales\n|death_date     = <!--{{death date and age|||||||df=yes}}-->\n|death_place    =\n|height         =\n|position       =\n|youthyears1    =\n|youthclubs1    =\n|years1         = 1888\u20131889\n|clubs1         = [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]]\n|caps1          =\n|goals1         =\n|years2         =\n|clubs2         =\n|caps2          =\n|goals2         =\n|totalcaps      =\n|totalgoals     =\n|nationalyears1 = 1889\n|nationalteam1  = [[Wales national football team|Wales]]\n|nationalcaps1  = 1\n|nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1  =\n| managerclubs1  =\n| medaltemplates =\n}}\n'''Thomas McCarthy ''' (1868 in Wales \u2013 ) was a [[Welsh people|Welsh]] international [[association football|footballer]]. He was part of the [[Wales national football team]], playing 1 match on 27 April 1889 against Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eu-football.info/_players.php?id=218|title=Wales player database 1872 to 2013|publisher=eu-football.info|accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt club level, he played for [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] in the 1880s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/thomas-mccarthy/ |title=Thomas McCarthy |publisher=worldfootball.net |accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Wales international footballers (alphabetical)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCarthy, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1868 births]]\n[[Category:Welsh footballers]]\n[[Category:Wales international footballers]]\n[[Category:Wrexham A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n\n\n{{Wales-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Welsh footballer}}\n{{for|other people with the same name|Thomas McCarthy (disambiguation){{!}}Thomas McCarthy}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = Thomas McCarthy\n|image          =\n| image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|fullname       =\n|birth_date     = 1868\n|birth_place    = Wales\n|death_date     = <!--{{death date and age|||||||df=yes}}-->\n|death_place    =\n|height         =\n|position       =\n|youthyears1    =\n|youthclubs1    =\n|years1         = 1888\u20131889\n|clubs1         = [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]]\n|caps1          =\n|goals1         =\n|years2         =\n|clubs2         =\n|caps2          =\n|goals2         =\n|totalcaps      =\n|totalgoals     =\n|nationalyears1 = 1889\n|nationalteam1  = [[Wales national football team|Wales]]\n|nationalcaps1  = 1\n|nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1  =\n| managerclubs1  =\n| medaltemplates =\n}}\n'''Thomas McCarthy ''' (1868 in Wales \u2013 ) was a [[Welsh people|Welsh]] international [[association football|footballer]]. He was part of the [[Wales national football team]], playing 1 match on 27 April 1889 against Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eu-football.info/_players.php?id=218|title=Wales player database 1872 to 2013|publisher=eu-football.info|accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt club level, he played for [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] in the 1880s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/thomas-mccarthy/ |title=Thomas McCarthy |publisher=worldfootball.net |accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Wales international footballers (alphabetical)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCarthy, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1868 births]]\n[[Category:Welsh footballers]]\n[[Category:Wales international footballers]]\n[[Category:Wrexham A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n\n\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n{{Wales-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_McCarthy_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Bill Hall Trail", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=November 2009}}\n\n{{Infobox hiking trail\n |name=Bill Hall trail\n |photo=\n |caption=\n |length=\n |location=[[Grand Canyon National Park]], [[Arizona]], [[United States]]\n |trailheads=[[Colorado River]]\n |use=[[Hiking]]\n |elev_change=\n |highest=\n |lowest=\n |difficulty=\n |season=\n |sights=[[Grand Canyon]]\n |hazards=[[Severe weather|Severe Weather]]<br>[[Fatigue (physical)|Overexertion]]<br>[[Dehydration]]<br>[[Flash flood|Flash Flood]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Bill Hall Trail''' is a [[hiking]] [[trail]] in [[Grand Canyon National Park]], located in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Arizona]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Grand Canyon and the American Southwest: Trekking in the Grand Canyon, Zion and Bryce Canyon National Parks|first1=Constance |last1=Roos|first2= Bob |last2=Gibbons|first3= Sian |last3=Pritchard-Jones |edition=2|publisher =Cicerone Press Limited|year= 2008 |ISBN =1-85284-453-1|pages=88}}</ref>\n\n==Access==\nThe trail begins at ''Monument Point'' along the north rim of the canyon on the boundary of the National Park, about {{Convert|20|mi|km|0}} west of the park services at North Rim, Arizona.  Access to the trailhead is over {{Convert|35|mi|km|0}} of forest roads made of graded dirt, and a [[four-wheel drive]] vehicle is recommended for travel in the area. When roads are dry the trailhead can be accessed by a passenger car.\n\n==Description==\nFrom the dirt parking lot at the trailhead, the trail heads west and dips below the rim into the park.  The trail makes several short, steep switchbacks during its descent through the upper canyon rock layers.  In the Coconino Sandstone, the trail is at its steepest.  There are numerous boulders, some very large, that require care to detour around or climb over.  Some portions of this descent may require lowering of backpacks prior to downclimbing.\n\nAfter {{Convert|2|mi|km|0}} of steep descent, the trail levels off along the Esplanade Sandstone until the junction with the [[Thunder River Trail]].  This junction marks the lower terminus of the trail.\n\nThe trail is named for Bill Hall who was a seasonal park ranger on the North Rim who was killed in the line of duty (automobile accident) in \n1979.\n\n==See also==\n* [[The Grand Canyon]]\n* [[List of trails in Grand Canyon National Park]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nps.gov/grca/ Grand Canyon National Park, Official site]\n* http://www.xmission.com/~mbmiles/p165.htm Bill Hall, Thunder River and Deer Creek trails][[dead link]]\n{{Coord|36.43461|-112.42933|type:landmark_region:US_scale:50000|display=title}}\n\n{{Grand Canyon trails}}\n\n[[Category:Hiking trails in Grand Canyon National Park]]\n[[Category:Grand Canyon, North Rim]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=November 2009}}\n\n{{Infobox hiking trail\n |name=Bill Hall trail\n |photo=\n |caption=\n |length=\n |location=[[Grand Canyon National Park]], [[Arizona]], [[United States]]\n |trailheads=[[Colorado River]]\n |use=[[Hiking]]\n |elev_change=\n |highest=\n |lowest=\n |difficulty=\n |season=\n |sights=[[Grand Canyon]]\n |hazards=[[Severe weather|Severe Weather]]<br>[[Fatigue (physical)|Overexertion]]<br>[[Dehydration]]<br>[[Flash flood|Flash Flood]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Bill Hall Trail''' is a [[hiking]] [[trail]] in [[Grand Canyon National Park]], located in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Arizona]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Grand Canyon and the American Southwest: Trekking in the Grand Canyon, Zion and Bryce Canyon National Parks|first1=Constance |last1=Roos|first2= Bob |last2=Gibbons|first3= Sian |last3=Pritchard-Jones |edition=2|publisher =Cicerone Press Limited|year= 2008 |ISBN =1-85284-453-1|pages=88}}</ref>\n\n==Access==\nThe trail begins at ''Monument Point'' along the north rim of the canyon on the boundary of the National Park, about {{Convert|20|mi|km|0}} west of the park services at North Rim, Arizona.  Access to the trailhead is over {{Convert|35|mi|km|0}} of forest roads made of graded dirt, and a [[four-wheel drive]] vehicle is recommended for travel in the area. When roads are dry the trailhead can be accessed by a passenger car.\n\n==Description==\nFrom the dirt parking lot at the trailhead, the trail heads west and dips below the rim into the park.  The trail makes several short, steep switchbacks during its descent through the upper canyon rock layers.  In the Coconino Sandstone, the trail is at its steepest.  There are numerous boulders, some very large, that require care to detour around or climb over.  Some portions of this descent may require lowering of backpacks prior to downclimbing.\n\nAfter {{Convert|2|mi|km|0}} of steep descent, the trail levels off along the Esplanade Sandstone until the junction with the [[Thunder River Trail]].  This junction marks the lower terminus of the trail.\n\nThe trail is named for Bill Hall who was a seasonal park ranger on the North Rim who was killed in the line of duty (automobile accident) in \n1979.\n\n==See also==\n* [[The Grand Canyon]]\n* [[List of trails in Grand Canyon National Park]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nps.gov/grca/ Grand Canyon National Park, Official site]\n* [https://archive.is/20060312033238/http://www.xmission.com/~mbmiles/p165.htm Bill Hall, Thunder River and Deer Creek trails][[dead link]]\n{{Coord|36.43461|-112.42933|type:landmark_region:US_scale:50000|display=title}}\n\n{{Grand Canyon trails}}\n\n[[Category:Hiking trails in Grand Canyon National Park]]\n[[Category:Grand Canyon, North Rim]]\n", "name_user": "Nipunadk123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bill_Hall_Trail"}
{"title_page": "Robert Southwell (died 1598)", "text_new": "{{short description|English politician}}\n[[File:Southwell OfWoodrisingNorfolk Arms.svg|thumb|Arms of Southwell of Woodrising, Norfolk: ''Argent, three cinquefoils gules each charged with six annulets or'']]\n'''Sir Robert Southwell''' (1563\u20131598), of [[Woodrising, Norfolk|Woodrising]], [[Norfolk]], was an English politician.\n\nRobert was the son of Sir Thomas Southwell and his second wife Mary, daughter of Sir [[Rice Mansel]]. Thomas's third wife was Nazaret or [[Nazareth Newton]].\n\nHe was [[High Sheriff of Norfolk]] for 1589\u201390 and [[Vice-Admiral of Norfolk]] from 1585 to 1598. He was a [[Member of Parliament|Member]] (MP) of the [[Parliament of England]] for [[Guildford (UK Parliament constituency)|Guildford]] in 1597.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1558-1603/member/southwell-sir-robert-1563-98|title=SOUTHWELL,   Sir Robert (1563-98),  of Wood Rising, Norf. - History of Parliament Online|website=www.historyofparliamentonline.org}}</ref>\n\nRobert was an admiral in 1588 in the battle with the [[Spanish Armada]], in command of the ''[[English ship Elizabeth Jonas (1559)|Elizabeth Jonas]]''.\n\n==Family==\nOn 27 April 1583 he married [[Elizabeth Howard, Countess of Carrick|Elizabeth Howard]], eldest daughter of [[Charles Howard, 1st Earl of Nottingham]], and a lady in waiting to [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth]]. They had four sons and four daughters, including:\n* Robert Southwell, died 23 September 1586.\n* Thomas Southwell (1598-1643) was his heir.\n* Charles Southwell (2 February 1588 - 23 April 1588), buried at [[Reigate]] where the Howard family lived at Reigate Priory.<ref>Mill Stephenson, 'A list of Monumental Brasses in Surrey', ''Surrey Archaeological Collections'', vol. 32 (1919), p. 70.</ref>\n* Elizabeth Southwell (1584-1631), maid of honour to Queen Elizabeth from 1 January 1600.<ref>''Letters of Rowland Whyte'' (Philadelphia, 2013), pp. 377, 398.</ref> She danced in the masque at the marriage of [[Henry Somerset, 1st Marquess of Worcester]] in June 1600.<ref>Michael Brennan, Noel Kinnamon, Margaret Hannay, ''The Letters of Rowland Whyte'' (Philadelphia, 2013), pp. 498, 501: Arthur Collins, ''Letters and Memorials of State'', vol. 2 (London, 1746), p. 201: Roy Strong, ''The Cult of Elizabeth'' (London, 1977), pp. 28-43.</ref> She was also maid of honour to [[Anne of Denmark]], and third wife of [[Robert Dudley (explorer)|Robert Dudley]]. She wrote an account of the death of Queen Elizabeth.<ref>Catherine Loomis, ''The Death of Elizabeth I: Remembering and Reconstructing the Virgin Queen'' (New York, 2010), pp. 83-5.</ref> She was buried in [[San Pancrazio, Florence]] where there was formerly a Latin inscription including her age, 37 years. Her portrait is drawn in an Italian armorial.<ref>John Temple Leader, ''Life of Sir Robert Dudley'' (Florence, 1895), pp. 9-10, 146.</ref>\n* Frances Southwell, gentlewoman of the privy chamber to Anne of Denmark, married [[Edward Rodney|Sir Edward Rodney]] of [[Rodney Stoke]], Somerset, at [[Somerset House|Denmark House]] in 1614.<ref>Norman Egbert McClure, ''Letters of John Chamberlain'', vol. 1 (Philadelphia, 1939), p. 512.</ref> The [[Francis Manners, 6th Earl of Rutland|Earl of Rutland]] gave a wedding present of a gilt bowl and cover worth \u00a321.<ref>''HMC Rutland'' vol. 4 (London, 1905), p. 500.</ref>\n* Katherine Southwell, gentlewoman of the Privy Chamber to Anne of Denmark, who married [[Greville Verney, 7th Baron Willoughby de Broke]] in 1618.\n\nRobert's half-sister, the daughter of Nazaret Newton, Elizabeth Southwell, was a Maid of Honour to Queen Elizabeth. She was a mistress of [[Robert Devereux, 2nd Earl of Essex]] and the mother of [[Walter Devereux (died 1641)|Walter Devereux]].<ref>Johanna Rickman, ''Love, Lust, and License in Early Modern England: Illicit Sex and the Nobility'' (Ashgate, 2008), pp. 30-32.</ref> She married Sir Barentine Moleyns or Molyns of Clapcot.<ref>[https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1604-1629/member/molyns-michael-1601-1662 Alan Davidson, 'MOLYNS, Michael (c.1601-at least 1662), of Clapcot', ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1604-1629'', ed. Andrew Thrush and John P. Ferris, 2010.]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Southwell, Robert}}\n[[Category:1563 births]]\n[[Category:1598 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Breckland District]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1597\u20131598]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Norfolk]]\n[[Category:Members of Parliament for Guildford]]\n\n\n{{England-pre1707-MP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English politician}}\n[[File:Southwell OfWoodrisingNorfolk Arms.svg|thumb|Arms of Southwell of Woodrising, Norfolk: ''Argent, three cinquefoils gules each charged with six annulets or'']]\n'''Sir Robert Southwell''' (1563\u20131598), of [[Woodrising, Norfolk|Woodrising]], [[Norfolk]], was an English politician.\n\nRobert was the son of Sir Thomas Southwell and his second wife Mary, daughter of Sir [[Rice Mansel]]. Thomas's third wife was Nazaret or [[Nazareth Newton]].\n\nHe was [[High Sheriff of Norfolk]] for 1589\u201390 and [[Vice-Admiral of Norfolk]] from 1585 to 1598. He was a [[Member of Parliament|Member]] (MP) of the [[Parliament of England]] for [[Guildford (UK Parliament constituency)|Guildford]] in 1597.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1558-1603/member/southwell-sir-robert-1563-98|title=SOUTHWELL,   Sir Robert (1563-98),  of Wood Rising, Norf. - History of Parliament Online|website=www.historyofparliamentonline.org}}</ref>\n\nRobert was an admiral in 1588 in the battle with the [[Spanish Armada]], in command of the ''[[English ship Elizabeth Jonas (1559)|Elizabeth Jonas]]''.\n\n==Family==\nOn 27 April 1583 he married [[Elizabeth Howard, Countess of Carrick|Elizabeth Howard]], eldest daughter of [[Charles Howard, 1st Earl of Nottingham]], and a lady in waiting to [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth]]. They had four sons and four daughters, including:\n* Robert Southwell, died 23 September 1586.\n* Thomas Southwell (1598-1643) was his heir.\n* Charles Southwell (2 February 1588 - 23 April 1588), buried at [[Reigate]] where the Howard family lived at Reigate Priory.<ref>Mill Stephenson, 'A list of Monumental Brasses in Surrey', ''Surrey Archaeological Collections'', vol. 32 (1919), p. 70.</ref>\n* Elizabeth Southwell (1584-1631), maid of honour to Queen Elizabeth from 1 January 1600.</ref>''Letters of Rowland Whyte'' (Philadelphia, 2013), pp. 377, 398.</ref> She danced in the masque at the marriage of [[Henry Somerset, 1st Marquess of Worcester]] in June 1600.<ref>Michael Brennan, Noel Kinnamon, Margaret Hannay, ''The Letters of Rowland Whyte'' (Philadelphia, 2013), pp. 498, 501: Arthur Collins, ''Letters and Memorials of State'', vol. 2 (London, 1746), p. 201: Roy Strong, ''The Cult of Elizabeth'' (London, 1977), pp. 28-43.</ref> She was also maid of honour to [[Anne of Denmark]], and third wife of [[Robert Dudley (explorer)|Robert Dudley]]. She wrote an account of the death of Queen Elizabeth.<ref>Catherine Loomis, ''The Death of Elizabeth I: Remembering and Reconstructing the Virgin Queen'' (New York, 2010), pp. 83-5.</ref> She was buried in [[San Pancrazio, Florence]] where there was formerly a Latin inscription including her age, 37 years. Her portrait is drawn in an Italian armorial.<ref>John Temple Leader, ''Life of Sir Robert Dudley'' (Florence, 1895), pp. 9-10, 146.</ref>\n* Frances Southwell, gentlewoman of the privy chamber to Anne of Denmark, married [[Edward Rodney|Sir Edward Rodney]] of [[Rodney Stoke]], Somerset, at [[Somerset House|Denmark House]] in 1614.<ref>Norman Egbert McClure, ''Letters of John Chamberlain'', vol. 1 (Philadelphia, 1939), p. 512.</ref> The [[Francis Manners, 6th Earl of Rutland|Earl of Rutland]] gave a wedding present of a gilt bowl and cover worth \u00a321.<ref>''HMC Rutland'' vol. 4 (London, 1905), p. 500.</ref>\n* Katherine Southwell, gentlewoman of the Privy Chamber to Anne of Denmark, who married [[Greville Verney, 7th Baron Willoughby de Broke]] in 1618.\n\nRobert's half-sister, the daughter of Nazaret Newton, Elizabeth Southwell, was a Maid of Honour to Queen Elizabeth. She was a mistress of [[Robert Devereux, 2nd Earl of Essex]] and the mother of [[Walter Devereux (died 1641)|Walter Devereux]].<ref>Johanna Rickman, ''Love, Lust, and License in Early Modern England: Illicit Sex and the Nobility'' (Ashgate, 2008), pp. 30-32.</ref> She married Sir Barentine Moleyns or Molyns of Clapcot.<ref>[https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1604-1629/member/molyns-michael-1601-1662 Alan Davidson, 'MOLYNS, Michael (c.1601-at least 1662), of Clapcot', ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1604-1629'', ed. Andrew Thrush and John P. Ferris, 2010.]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Southwell, Robert}}\n[[Category:1563 births]]\n[[Category:1598 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Breckland District]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1597\u20131598]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Norfolk]]\n[[Category:Members of Parliament for Guildford]]\n\n\n{{England-pre1707-MP-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFamily:ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Southwell_(died_1598)"}
{"title_page": "64 BC Syria earthquake", "text_new": "The '''64 BC Syria earthquake''' is mentioned in catalogues of historical earthquakes. It affected the region of [[Syria (region)|Syria]] and may have caused structural damage in the city of [[Jerusalem]].<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\n==Sources==\nThe earthquake is mentioned in an [[epitome]] of ''Liber Historiarum Philippicarum'', written by the historian [[Justin (historian)|Justin]] (2nd century).<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref> Justin reported that a devastating earthquake affected Syria, dating the earthquake to the end of the reign of [[Tigranes the Great]] (reigned 95\u201355 BC) in Syria. The earthquake reportedly caused widespread destruction, and caused the deaths of 170,000 people.<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\nThere are disdagreements over when Tigranes stopped reigning over Syria, and when the earthquake took place. Other suggested dates for the earthquake give the year as 65 BC or 69 BC. While Justin used the historian [[Gnaeus Pompeius Trogus]] as his main source, his surviving works indicate that Justin misunderstood this source. Resulting in a confusion over the dates of events, and the identities of the characters mentioned.<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\nAnother mention of this earthquake is found in ''Historiarum Adversum Paganos'', written by the historian [[Orosius]] (5th century).<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref> The narrative mentions that when the earthquake took place, [[Mithridates VI of Pontus]] was attending a festival of the goddess [[Ceres (mythology)|Ceres]] in the [[Bosporus]]. The text is though to describe a visir of Mithridates to the Cimmerian Bosporus (modern [[Kerch Strait]]), located at the [[Sea of Azov]] and the peninmsula of [[Crimea]].<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref> The text does not clarify whether Mithridates himself experienced the earthquake, or merely heard news about it.<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\n''Chronographia'' by [[John Malalas]] briefly mentions the eartquake. He reports that it caused the [[Bouleuterion]] of [[Antioch]] to fall down. The destroyed building was eventually rebuilt by [[Pompey]].<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref> Modern sources have extrapolated that Antioch suffered extensive structural damage or that the entire city was destroyed by the earthquake. However, Malalas states nothing about such an event.<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\n==Possible Jewish sources==\nThe same earthquake is supposed in modern sources to have affected [[Jerusalem]], which is located {{convert|550|km|abbr=on}} south of Antioch. The earthquake supposedly caused structural damage to Jerusalem's city walls, and to the [[Second Temple]]'s compound.<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\nThe primary source for such an event is the [[Babylonian Talmud]]. The narrative speaks of a struggle for power between the sons of Queen regnant [[Salome Alexandra]] (reigned 76-67 BC). Her two sons were [[Hyrcanus II]] and [[Aristobulus II]], who were the last kings of the [[Hasmonean dynasty]].<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\nHyrcanus II allied himself with the [[Nabataeans]], and they helped him in a [[Siege of Jerusalem (64 BC)|siege of Jerusalem]]. According to the Talmud, the two opposing sides reached an agreement to allow the supply of sacrificial animals to the Second Temple, which was needed for the year's celebration of the [[Passover]]. The defenders of the city would lower a \"big basket\" filled with golden coins over the city walls, which the attackers were required to fill. The attackers broke the agreement, and took the gold without fullfilling their end of the bargain. Instead of sending sacrificial animals, they send a pig. The pig struck its claws to the city walls, and suddenly an earthquake struck the [[Land of Israel]]. According to the Talmud, the earthquake shocked areas at a distance of 400 [[parasang]]s by 400 parasangs. The parasang is a Persian unit of distance, about 4000 yards long.<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\n[[Josephus]] account of the siege mentions neither an earthquake, nor a pig. In his narrative, the Passover services were both prevented and mocked during the siege. [[Divine punishment]] struck in the form of a \"storm of wind\", that destroyed [[Judea]]'s fruits. According to Josephus, prices rose due to the destruction. A modius of wheat cost 11 [[Greek drachma|drachmae]].<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\n[[Cassius Dio]] also mentions the war between the two brothers, without mentioning an earthquake. The Talmud's earthquake may have originated in a story of figurative shock over the \"ungodly breach of agreement\", and the consequent disruption services.<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref> This idea seems to be corroborated by the [[Jerusalem Talmud]]'s narrative.<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\n==Historical context==\nIn chronological accounts, the 64 BC siege and the earthquake are place after the death of [[Salome Alexandra]] (d. 67 BC), and before [[Pompey]]'\ns [[Siege of Jerusalem (63 BC)|Siege of Jerusalem]] (63 BC).<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref> Pompey's siege is nnown to have taken place shortly after the death of [[Mithridates VI of Pontus]].<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\nPompey and [[Tigranes the Great]] were rivals in war until 66 BC, and then Pompey fought against [[Kingdom of Pontus]]. Pompey's subordinate commander [[Marcus Aemilius Scaurus (praetor 56 BC)|Marcus Aemilius Scaurus]] is credited with ending the Nabatean siege of Jerusalem. Scaurus was send from [[Damascus]] to Judea, where he offered bribes to both sides of the conflict. The siege was lifted, and Scaurus offered his support to [[Aristobulus II]].<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\nThe Passover associated with the siege and earthquake took place in 65 or 64 BC. In narratives of the earthquake, the Passover took place at the same time as a festival of [[Ceres (mythology)|Ceres]]. This would place the earthquake in [[Spring (season)|springtime]], as both these festivities teaditionally took place in spring.<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\nThe \"fanciful\" Talmudic narrative reports on an earthquake, but does not support the idea that Jerusalem's city walls and the Second Temple suffered extensive damage. [[Josephus]]' narrative does not mention such a disaster either.<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref> Both Josephus and [[Strabo]] mention that Jerusalem's city walls were still robust during Pompey's siege, and that Pompey faced difficulties in capturing the city.<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\n==Modern perspectives==\nA group of 8 sediment deformation horizons (mixed layers) have been identified among the [[Holocene]] sediments found in the [[Tze'elim Stream]] (Nahal Tze'elim) of the [[Dead Sea]] region. The deformations are believed to have a seismic event origin, with each deformation corresponding to a seismic event. The earliest sediment deformation in the group has been dated through [[radiometry]] to a range of dates between 200 BC and 40 BC. One theory associates the sentiment with the 64 BC earthquake.<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\nIn this view, the epicenter of the earthquake was in the Dead Sea. The earthquake would be strong enough to cause structural damage in both Jerusalem and Antioch.<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref> Doubts on this view point to the questionable historicity of the Talmudic sources, and the insufficient data from other primary sources.<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite LSA |last=Karcz |first=Iaakov |year=2004 |title=Implications of some early Jewish sources for estimates of earthquake hazard in the Holy Land |url=http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.393.3596&rep=rep1&type=pdf |journal=[[Annals of Geophysics]] |volume=47 |pages=759\u2013792 |accessdate=2020-04-02}}\n\n[[Category:64 BC]]\n[[Category:1st-century BC earthquakes]]\n[[Category:Ancient Antioch]]\n[[Category:Ancient history of Jerusalem]]\n", "text_old": "The '''64 BC Syria earthquake''' is mentioned in catalogues of historical earthquakes. It affected the region of [[Syria (region)|Syria]] and may have caused structural damage in the city of [[Jerusalem]]. <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\n==Sources==\nThe earthquake is mentioned in an [[epitome]] of ''Liber Historiarum Philippicarum'', written by the historian [[Justin (historian)|Justin]] (2nd century). <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref> Justin reported that a devastating earthquake affected Syria, dating the earthquake to the end of the reign of [[Tigranes the Great]] (reigned 95\u201355 BC) in Syria. The earthquake reportedly caused widespread destruction, and caused the deaths of 170,000 people.<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref> \n\nThere are disdagreements over when Tigranes stopped reigning over Syria, and when the earthquake took place. Other suggested dates for the earthquake give the year as 65 BC or 69 BC. While Justin used the historian [[Gnaeus Pompeius Trogus]] as his main source, his surviving works indicate that Justin misunderstood this source. Resulting in a confusion over the dates of events, and the identities of the characters mentioned. <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\nAnother mention of this earthquake is found in ''Historiarum Adversum Paganos'', written by the historian [[Orosius]] (5th century). <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref> The narrative mentions that when the earthquake took place, [[Mithridates VI of Pontus]] was attending a festival of the goddess [[Ceres (mythology)|Ceres]] in the [[Bosporus]]. The text is though to describe a visir of Mithridates to the Cimmerian Bosporus (modern [[Kerch Strait]]), located at the [[Sea of Azov]] and the peninmsula of [[Crimea]]. <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref> The text does not clarify whether Mithridates himself experienced the earthquake, or merely heard news about it. <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\n''Chronographia'' by [[John Malalas]] briefly mentions the eartquake. He reports that it caused the [[Bouleuterion]] of [[Antioch]] to fall down. The destroyed building was eventually rebuilt by [[Pompey]]. <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref> Modern sources have extrapolated that Antioch suffered extensive structural damage or that the entire city was destroyed by the earthquake. However, Malalas states nothing about such an event. <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\n==Possible Jewish sources==\nThe same earthquake is supposed in modern sources to have affected [[Jerusalem]], which is located {{convert|550|km|abbr=on}} south of Antioch. The earthquake supposedly caused structural damage to Jerusalem's city walls, and to the [[Second Temple]]'s compound. <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\nThe primary source for such an event is the [[Babylonian Talmud]]. The narrative speaks of a struggle for power between the sons of Queen regnant [[Salome Alexandra]] (reigned 76-67 BC). Her two sons were [[Hyrcanus II]] and [[Aristobulus II]], who were the last kings of the [[Hasmonean dynasty]]. <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\nHyrcanus II allied himself with the [[Nabataeans]], and they helped him in a [[Siege of Jerusalem (64 BC)|siege of Jerusalem]]. According to the Talmud, the two opposing sides reached an agreement to allow the supply of sacrificial animals to the Second Temple, which was needed for the year's celebration of the [[Passover]]. The defenders of the city would lower a \"big basket\" filled with golden coins over the city walls, which the attackers were required to fill. The attackers broke the agreement, and took the gold without fullfilling their end of the bargain. Instead of sending sacrificial animals, they send a pig. The pig struck its claws to the city walls, and suddenly an earthquake struck the [[Land of Israel]]. According to the Talmud, the earthquake shocked areas at a distance of 400 [[parasang]]s by 400 parasangs. The parasang is a Persian unit of distance, about 4000 yards long. <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\n[[Josephus]] account of the siege mentions neither an earthquake, nor a pig. In his narrative, the Passover services were both prevented and mocked during the siege. [[Divine punishment]] struck in the form of a \"storm of wind\", that destroyed [[Judea]]'s fruits. According to Josephus, prices rose due to the destruction. A modius of wheat cost 11 [[Greek drachma|drachmae]]. <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\n[[Cassius Dio]] also mentions the war between the two brothers, without mentioning an earthquake. The Talmud's earthquake may have originated in a story of figurative shock over the \"ungodly breach of agreement\", and the consequent disruption services. <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref> This idea seems to be corroborated by the [[Jerusalem Talmud]]'s narrative. <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\n==Historical context==\nIn chronological accounts, the 64 BC siege and the earthquake are place after the death of [[Salome Alexandra]] (d. 67 BC), and before [[Pompey]]'\ns [[Siege of Jerusalem (63 BC)|Siege of Jerusalem]] (63 BC). <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref> Pompey's siege is nnown to have taken place shortly after the death of [[Mithridates VI of Pontus]].<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\nPompey and [[Tigranes the Great]] were rivals in war until 66 BC, and then Pompey fought against [[Kingdom of Pontus]]. Pompey's subordinate commander [[Marcus Aemilius Scaurus (praetor 56 BC)|Marcus Aemilius Scaurus]] is credited with ending the Nabatean siege of Jerusalem. Scaurus was send from [[Damascus]] to Judea, where he offered bribes to both sides of the conflict. The siege was lifted, and Scaurus offered his support to [[Aristobulus II]].<ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\nThe Passover associated with the siege and earthquake took place in 65 or 64 BC. In narratives of the earthquake, the Passover took place at the same time as a festival of [[Ceres (mythology)|Ceres]]. This would place the earthquake in [[Spring (season)|springtime]], as both these festivities teaditionally took place in spring. <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\nThe \"fanciful\" Talmudic narrative reports on an earthquake, but does not support the idea that Jerusalem's city walls and the Second Temple suffered extensive damage. [[Josephus]]' narrative does not mention such a disaster either. <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref> Both Josephus and [[Strabo]] mention that Jerusalem's city walls were still robust during Pompey's siege, and that Pompey faced difficulties in capturing the city. <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\n==Modern perspectives==\nA group of 8 sediment deformation horizons (mixed layers) have been identified among the [[Holocene]] sediments found in the [[Tze'elim Stream]] (Nahal Tze'elim) of the [[Dead Sea]] region. The deformations are believed to have a seismic event origin, with each deformation corresponding to a seismic event. The earliest sediment deformation in the group has been dated through [[radiometry]] to a range of dates between 200 BC and 40 BC. One theory associates the sentiment with the 64 BC earthquake. <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\nIn this view, the epicenter of the earthquake was in the Dead Sea. The earthquake would be strong enough to cause structural damage in both Jerusalem and Antioch. <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref> Doubts on this view point to the questionable historicity of the Talmudic sources, and the insufficient data from other primary sources. <ref name=\"Karcz\">Karcz, 2004, p. 770-773</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite LSA |last=Karcz |first=Iaakov |year=2004 |title=Implications of some early Jewish sources for estimates of earthquake hazard in the Holy Land |url=http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.393.3596&rep=rep1&type=pdf |journal=[[Annals of Geophysics]] |volume=47 |pages=759\u2013792 |accessdate=2020-04-02}}\n\n[[Category:64 BC]]\n[[Category:1st-century BC earthquakes]]\n[[Category:Ancient Antioch]]\n[[Category:Ancient history of Jerusalem]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/64_BC_Syria_earthquake"}
{"title_page": "Thomas McBride (footballer)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Thomas McBride\n| image             =\n| caption           =\n| fullname          = Thomas McBride\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1992|5|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Derry]], Northern Ireland\n| clubnumber        = \n| currentclub       = \t[[Newbuildings United F.C.|Newbuildings United]]\n| height            = \n| position          = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1       = | youthclubs1 = Maiden City Academy\n| years1 = 2008\u20132010  | clubs1 = [[Northampton Town]]             | caps1 =   | goals1 = \n| years2 = 2010\u20132011  | clubs2 = [[Derry City F.C.|Derry City]]   | caps2 = 25 | goals2 = 3\n| years3 = 2011\u20132012  | clubs3 = [[Institute F.C.|Institute]]     | caps3 = 11 | goals3 = 4\n| years4 = 2012\u20132013  | clubs4 = [[Finn Harps F.C.|Finn Harps]]   | caps4 = 28 | goals4 = 6\n| years5 = 2014\u20132015      | clubs5 = [[Institute F.C.|Institute]]     | caps5 = 7  | goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 2015\u20132016      | clubs6= [[Crewe United F.C.|Crewe United]] | caps6 =  | goals6 = \n| years7 = 2016       | clubs7= [[Dergview F.C.|Dergview]] | caps7 =  | goals7 = \n| years8 = 2017\u20132019     | clubs8= [[Finn Harps F.C.|Finn Harps]] | caps8 = 25 | goals8 = 1\n| years9 = 2019    | clubs9= [[Institute F.C.|Institute]] | caps9 = 14  | goals9 = 0\n| years10 = 2019\u2013     | clubs10= [[Newbuildings United F.C.|Newbuildings United]] | caps10 = 0  | goals10 = 0\n| nationalyears1 =    | nationalteam1  = [[Republic of Ireland national under-19 football team|Republic of Ireland U-19]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 5  | nationalgoals1 = 0 }}\n\n'''Thomas McBride''' is a footballer from [[Derry]], Northern Ireland who plays for [[Northern Ireland Intermediate League]] club [[Newbuildings United F.C.|Newbuildings United]].\n\nHe previously played with [[Derry City F.C.|Derry City]], had 2 stints at [[Finn Harps F.C.|Finn Harps]] and was a youth player for [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]]. McBride was also selected for the [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland Under-18]] Schoolboys in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://www.irishfa.com/the-ifa/news/5420/u18-schools-squad-named/\n|title=U18 SCHOOLS SQUAD NAMED\n|accessdate=13 March 2010\n|date=19 January 2010\n|publisher=irishfa.com}}</ref> However, he went on to represent the [[Republic of Ireland national under-19 football team|Republic of Ireland at under 19 level]].<ref>[http://www.fai.ie/international/under-19/100816-mccaffrey-names-starting-team-for-u19-friendly.html McCaffrey names starting team for U19 friendly] Retrieved 23.01.12</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Northampton===\nMcBride was scouted and signed as a youth to [[Northampton Town F.C.]] but after a short spell at the club with no first team appearances, he left by mutual consent, and returned to Northern Ireland.\n\n===Derry City===\nMcBride signed for local team [[Derry City F.C.|Derry City]] on trial in 2010 and after several friendlies was signed up on a one-year contract. He regularly featured on the subs bench at the start of the new First Division season but soon won a place in the starting team. He also won Northern Irish u18 player of the year after netting 3 goals within 3 appearances{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}. Following Derry's promotion to the Premier Division and the addition of [[Ruaidhri Higgins]] to the midfield McBride lost his place in the team and was dropped to the bench. It was announced in August 2011 that he had left the club after requesting that his contract be terminated as to complete a move to Institute.\n\n===Institute===\nImmediately after leaving Derry he signed for neighbouring club [[Institute F.C.|Institute]]. He left the club after his contract expired in order to sign for [[League of Ireland]] side Finn Harps.\n\n===Finn Harps===\nHe signed for [[Finn Harps F.C.|Finn Harps]] in February 2012. He left in May 2013, again by mutual consent.\n\n===Return to Institute===\nHe rejoined the Drumahoe club in June 2014, for the start of his second stint with them, also marking his return to senior football (in the [[NIFL Premiership]]).\nHis debut was a 2\u20132 away draw with [[Dungannon Swifts F.C.|Dungannon Swifts]] on the first day of the 2014-15 [[NIFL Premiership]] season. His first competitive goal since rejoining the club came in late August, in a 2\u20130 home league cup win over [[Dollingstown F.C.|Dollingstown]]. His only league goal of the season came in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Glentoran F.C.|Glentoran]] at the [[YMCA Grounds|Riverside Stadium]].\n\n===Return to Finn Harps===\n\nIn the summer of 2017, McBride returned to Finn Harps as the club looked to remain in the [[League of Ireland Premier Division]], following the departure of [[Barry Molloy]]. Despite becoming a mainstay in the side, Harps were relegated, finishing 11th place in the table.\n\nMcBride subsequently agreed a new one-year contract for the 2018 First Division season.\n\n===Third stint at Institute===\nMcBride signed for Institute for his third spell with the club in January 2019.\n\n===Newbuildings United===\nIn October 2019,McBride left Institute for intermediate club [[Newbuildings United F.C.|Newbuildings United]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McBride, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Derry City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Northampton Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Institute F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Finn Harps F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:League of Ireland players]]\n[[Category:NIFL Premiership players]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland association footballers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Derry (city)]]\n[[Category:A Championship players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Thomas McBride\n| image             =\n| caption           =\n| fullname          = Thomas McBride\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1992|5|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Derry]], [[Northern Ireland]]\n| clubnumber        = \n| currentclub       = \t[[Newbuildings United F.C.|Newbuildings United]]\n| height            = {{convert|1.75|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position          = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1       = | youthclubs1 = Maiden City Academy\n| years1 = 2008\u20132010  | clubs1 = [[Northampton Town]]             | caps1 =   | goals1 = \n| years2 = 2010\u20132011  | clubs2 = [[Derry City F.C.|Derry City]]   | caps2 = 25 | goals2 = 3\n| years3 = 2011\u20132012  | clubs3 = [[Institute F.C.|Institute]]     | caps3 = 11 | goals3 = 4\n| years4 = 2012\u20132013  | clubs4 = [[Finn Harps F.C.|Finn Harps]]   | caps4 = 28 | goals4 = 6\n| years5 = 2014\u20132015      | clubs5 = [[Institute F.C.|Institute]]     | caps5 = 7  | goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 2015\u20132016      | clubs6= [[Crewe United F.C.|Crewe United]] | caps6 =  | goals6 = \n| years7 = 2016       | clubs7= [[Dergview F.C.|Dergview]] | caps7 =  | goals7 = \n| years8 = 2017\u20132019     | clubs8= [[Finn Harps F.C.|Finn Harps]] | caps8 = 25 | goals8 = 1\n| years9 = 2019    | clubs9= [[Institute F.C.|Institute]] | caps9 = 14  | goals9 = 0\n| years10 = 2019\u2013     | clubs10= [[Newbuildings United F.C.|Newbuildings United]] | caps10 = 0  | goals10 = 0\n| nationalyears1 =    | nationalteam1  = [[Republic of Ireland national under-19 football team|Republic of Ireland U-19]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 5  | nationalgoals1 = 0 }}\n\n'''Thomas McBride''' is a footballer from [[Derry]], [[Northern Ireland]] who plays for [[Northern Ireland Intermediate League]] club [[Newbuildings United F.C.|Newbuildings United]].\n\nHe previously played with [[Derry City F.C.|Derry City]], had 2 stints at [[Finn Harps F.C.|Finn Harps]] and was a youth player for [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]]. McBride was also selected for the [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland Under-18]] Schoolboys in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://www.irishfa.com/the-ifa/news/5420/u18-schools-squad-named/\n|title=U18 SCHOOLS SQUAD NAMED\n|accessdate=13 March 2010\n|date=19 January 2010\n|publisher=irishfa.com}}</ref> However, he went on to represent the [[Republic of Ireland national under-19 football team|Republic of Ireland at under 19 level]].<ref>[http://www.fai.ie/international/under-19/100816-mccaffrey-names-starting-team-for-u19-friendly.html McCaffrey names starting team for U19 friendly] Retrieved 23.01.12</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Northampton===\nMcBride was scouted and signed as a youth to [[Northampton Town F.C.]] but after a short spell at the club with no first team appearances, he left by mutual consent, and returned to Northern Ireland.\n\n===Derry City===\nMcBride signed for local team [[Derry City F.C.|Derry City]] on trial in 2010 and after several friendlies was signed up on a one-year contract. He regularly featured on the subs bench at the start of the new First Division season but soon won a place in the starting team. He also won Northern Irish u18 player of the year after netting 3 goals within 3 appearances{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}. Following Derry's promotion to the Premier Division and the addition of [[Ruaidhri Higgins]] to the midfield McBride lost his place in the team and was dropped to the bench. It was announced in August 2011 that he had left the club after requesting that his contract be terminated as to complete a move to Institute.\n\n===Institute===\nImmediately after leaving Derry he signed for neighbouring club [[Institute F.C.|Institute]]. He left the club after his contract expired in order to sign for [[League of Ireland]] side Finn Harps.\n\n===Finn Harps===\nHe signed for [[Finn Harps F.C.|Finn Harps]] in February 2012. He left in May 2013, again by mutual consent.\n\n===Return to Institute===\nHe rejoined the Drumahoe club in June 2014, for the start of his second stint with them, also marking his return to senior football (in the [[NIFL Premiership]]).\nHis debut was a 2-2 away draw with [[Dungannon Swifts F.C.|Dungannon Swifts]] on the first day of the 2014-15 [[NIFL Premiership]] season. His first competitive goal since rejoining the club came in late August, in a 2-0 home league cup win over [[Dollingstown F.C.|Dollingstown]]. His only league goal of the season came in a 1-1 draw with [[Glentoran F.C.|Glentoran]] at the [[YMCA Grounds|Riverside Stadium]].\n\n===Return to Finn Harps===\n\nIn the summer of 2017, McBride returned to Finn Harps as the club looked to remain in the [[League of Ireland Premier Division]], following the departure of [[Barry Molloy]]. Despite becoming a mainstay in the side, Harps were relegated, finishing 11th place in the table.\n\nMcBride subsequently agreed a new one-year contract for the 2018 First Division season.\n\n===Third stint at Institute===\nMcBride signed for Institute for his third spell with the club in January 2019.\n\n===Newbuildings United===\nIn October 2019,McBride left Institute for intermediate club [[Newbuildings United F.C.|Newbuildings United]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McBride, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Derry City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Northampton Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Institute F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Finn Harps F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:League of Ireland players]]\n[[Category:NIFL Premiership players]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland association footballers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Derry (city)]]\n[[Category:A Championship players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, remove unref height,typo(s) fixed: 2-2 \u2192 2\u20132 (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_McBride_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Lars Jungnickel", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| image               = Lars Jungnickel.png\n| image_size          = 200px\n| caption             = Lars Jungnickel in July 2008\n| fullname            =\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1981|8|31|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Dohna]], [[East Germany]]\n| height              = 1.79 m\n| position            = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub         = \n| clubnumber          = \n| youthyears1         = {{0|0000}}\u20131987\n| youthclubs1         = [[VfB Zittau]]\n| youthyears2         = 1987\u20131999\n| youthclubs2         = [[Dynamo Dresden]]\n| years1              = 1999\u20132001\n| clubs1              = [[Dynamo Dresden]]\n| caps1               = 52\n| goals1              = 13\n| years2              = 2001\u20132007\n| clubs2              = [[FC Energie Cottbus|Energie Cottbus]]\n| caps2               = 80\n| goals2              = 7\n| years3              = 2007\u20132012\n| clubs3              = [[Dynamo Dresden]]\n| caps3               = 95\n| goals3              = 3\n| years4              = 2009\u20132014\n| clubs4              = [[Dynamo Dresden II]]\n| caps4               = 29\n| goals4              = 2\n| years5              = 2014\u20132015\n| clubs5              = [[Dynamo Dresden II]]\n| caps5               = 15\n| goals5              = 0\n| totalcaps           = 271\n| totalgoals          = 25\n| nationalyears1      = 2002\n| nationalteam1       = [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany U-21]]\n| nationalcaps1       = 4\n| nationalgoals1      = 1\n| medaltemplates      =\n| manageryears1 = 2013\u20132015\n| managerclubs1 = [[Dynamo Dresden II]] (Player/Assistant Manager)<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bild.de/regional/dresden/dynamo-dresden/lars-jungnickel-wird-spieler-trainer-30921426.bild.html | title = Lars Jungnickel wird Spieler-Trainer | language = German | publisher = bild.de | date = 20 June 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Lars Jungnickel''' (born 31 August 1981) is a German former professional [[Association football|footballer]]. Early in his career, he played as a [[forward (football)|forward]] and later as a [[midfielder]], most notably for [[Dynamo Dresden]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/3liga/vereine/3-liga/2011-12/dynamo-dresden-65/23676/spieler_lars-jungnickel.html | title = Jungnickel, Lars | language = German | publisher = kicker.de | accessdate = 19 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nJungnickel was born in [[Dohna]], [[East Germany]]. He had two spells with Dynamo Dresden. He first joined the club as a child in 1987, and made his debut in the [[Regionalliga Nordost]] twelve years later. He spent two seasons in Dynamo's first-team, playing as a [[Forward (association football)|striker]], and despite the club's relegation to, and subsequent failure to get promoted from, the [[NOFV-Oberliga]], he showed promise, and in July 2001 he earned a move to [[FC Energie Cottbus|Energie Cottbus]] of the [[Bundesliga]], along with teammate [[Silvio Schr\u00f6ter]].\n\nJungnickel only made three appearances in his first season with Cottbus \u2013 his debut came in March 2003 when he replaced [[Thomas Reichenberger]] in a 2\u20130 win over [[Schalke 04]] \u2013 but made 23 appearances, mostly as a substitute, the next year, as the team finished bottom of the league. He missed much of the following season, but featured more regularly in the next two [[2. Bundesliga]] seasons, the latter of which saw the club promoted in third place. Back in the Bundesliga, Jungnickel only saw 20 minutes of action all season, and was released by Cottbus in July 2007.\n\nJungnickel then returned to Dynamo Dresden, now in the [[Regionalliga Nord]], and helped the club qualify for the [[3. Liga]] in his first season back. He has been a regular first-team player at the club ever since, usually employed as a [[defensive midfielder]]. He helped Dynamo earn promotion to the 2. Bundesliga in 2011, but missed most of the following season, due to injury. He retired at the end of the 2012\u201313 season, in which he had not made any first-team appearances.\n\nJungnickel was named in [[Germany national under-20 football team|Germany's squad]] for the [[2001 FIFA World Youth Championship]], and won four caps for the [[Germany national under-20 football team|under-21 team]] in 2002, scoring one goal.\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|9 February 2013.}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!Colspan=\"3\"|Club performance!!Colspan=\"2\"|League!!Colspan=\"2\"|Cup!!Colspan=\"2\"|Other!!Colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Club!!League!!Season!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n!Colspan=\"3\"|Germany!!Colspan=\"2\"|League!!Colspan=\"2\"|[[DFB-Pokal]]!!Colspan=\"2\"|Other!!Colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n|Rowspan=\"6\"|[[FC Energie Cottbus|Energie Cottbus]]||Rowspan=\"2\"|[[Bundesliga]]||[[2001\u201302 Bundesliga|2001\u201302]]||3||0||0||0||rowspan=\"7\" colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||3||0\n|-\n|[[2002\u201303 Bundesliga|2002\u201303]]||23||2||1||0||24||2\n|-\n|Rowspan=\"3\"|[[2. Bundesliga]]||[[2003\u201304 2. Bundesliga|2003\u201304]]||3||0||0||0||3||0\n|-\n|[[2004\u201305 2. Bundesliga|2004\u201305]]||24||1||1||0||25||1\n|-\n|[[2005\u201306 2. Bundesliga|2005\u201306]]||26||4||2||0||28||4\n|-\n|[[Bundesliga]]||[[2006\u201307 Bundesliga|2006\u201307]]||1||0||0||0||1||0\n|-\n|Rowspan=\"6\"|[[Dynamo Dresden]]||[[Regionalliga Nord]]||[[2007\u201308 Regionalliga|2007\u201308]]||17||1||1||0||18||1\n|-\n|Rowspan=\"3\"|[[3. Liga]]||[[2008\u201309 3. Liga|2008\u201309]]||24||0||Colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||Colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||24||0\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 3. Liga|2009\u201310]]||16||1||0||0||Colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||16||1\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 3. Liga|2010\u201311]]||36||1||Colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||2||0||38||1\n|-\n|Rowspan=\"2\"|[[2. Bundesliga]]||[[2011\u201312 2. Bundesliga|2011\u201312]]||2||0||0||0||Colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||2||0\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 2. 