           = 95\n| goals3              = 3\n| years4              = 2009\u20132014\n| clubs4              = [[Dynamo Dresden II]]\n| caps4               = 29\n| goals4              = 2\n| years5              = 2014\u20132015\n| clubs5              = [[Dynamo Dresden II]]\n| caps5               = 15\n| goals5              = 0\n| totalcaps           = \n| totalgoals          = \n| nationalyears1      = 2002\n| nationalteam1       = [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany U-21]]\n| nationalcaps1       = 4\n| nationalgoals1      = 1\n| medaltemplates      =\n| manageryears1 = 2013\u20132015\n| managerclubs1 = [[Dynamo Dresden II]] (Player/Assistant Manager)<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bild.de/regional/dresden/dynamo-dresden/lars-jungnickel-wird-spieler-trainer-30921426.bild.html | title = Lars Jungnickel wird Spieler-Trainer | language = German | publisher = bild.de | date = 20 June 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Lars Jungnickel''' (born 31 August 1981 in [[Dohna]]) is a former German [[Association football|footballer]]. Early in his career, he played as a [[forward (football)|forward]] and later as a [[midfielder]], most notably for [[Dynamo Dresden]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/3liga/vereine/3-liga/2011-12/dynamo-dresden-65/23676/spieler_lars-jungnickel.html | title = Jungnickel, Lars | language = German | publisher = kicker.de | accessdate = 19 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nJungnickel had two spells with Dynamo Dresden. He first joined the club as a child in 1987, and made his debut in the [[Regionalliga Nordost]] twelve years later. He spent two seasons in Dynamo's first-team, playing as a [[Forward (association football)|striker]], and despite the club's relegation to, and subsequent failure to get promoted from, the [[NOFV-Oberliga]], he showed promise, and in July 2001 he earned a move to [[FC Energie Cottbus|Energie Cottbus]] of the [[Bundesliga]], along with teammate [[Silvio Schr\u00f6ter]].\n\nJungnickel only made three appearances in his first season with Cottbus \u2013 his debut didn't come until March 2003 when he replaced [[Thomas Reichenberger]] in a 2\u20130 win over [[Schalke 04]] \u2013 but made 23 appearances, mostly as a substitute, the next year, as the team finished bottom of the league. He missed much of the following season, but featured more regularly in the next two [[2. Bundesliga]] seasons, the latter of which saw the club promoted in third place. Back in the Bundesliga, Jungnickel only saw 20 minutes of action all season, and was released by Cottbus in July 2007.\n\nJungnickel then returned to Dynamo Dresden, now in the [[Regionalliga Nord]], and helped the club qualify for the [[3. Liga]] in his first season back. He has been a regular first-team player at the club ever since, usually employed as a [[defensive midfielder]]. He helped Dynamo earn promotion to the 2. Bundesliga in 2011, but missed most of the following season, due to injury. He retired at the end of the 2012\u201313 season, in which he had not made any first-team appearances.\n\nJungnickel was named in [[Germany national under-20 football team|Germany's squad]] for the [[2001 FIFA World Youth Championship]], and won four caps for the [[Germany national under-20 football team|under-21 team]] in 2002, scoring one goal.\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|9 February 2013.}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!Colspan=\"3\"|Club performance!!Colspan=\"2\"|League!!Colspan=\"2\"|Cup!!Colspan=\"2\"|Other!!Colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Club!!League!!Season!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n!Colspan=\"3\"|Germany!!Colspan=\"2\"|League!!Colspan=\"2\"|[[DFB-Pokal]]!!Colspan=\"2\"|Other!!Colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n|Rowspan=\"6\"|[[FC Energie Cottbus|Energie Cottbus]]||Rowspan=\"2\"|[[Bundesliga]]||[[2001\u201302 Bundesliga|2001\u201302]]||3||0||0||0||rowspan=\"7\" colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||3||0\n|-\n|[[2002\u201303 Bundesliga|2002\u201303]]||23||2||1||0||24||2\n|-\