{"title_page": "Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic", "text_new": "{{short description|Medical material and other goods shortages that are a major issue}}\n<!-- {{multiple issues|{{short description|Impact of COVID-19}}\n}} -->\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Current COVID|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Clinicians in Intensive Care Unit.jpg|thumb|400px|upright=1.4|A patient and clinicians in an [[intensive care unit]]. In the context of the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], an ICU bed is a [[hospital bed]] equipped with [[mechanical ventilation]]. A lack of mechanical ventilation increases the probability that a COVID-19 patient will die.]]\nMedical material and other goods shortages caused by the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] are a major issue of the ongoing [[pandemic]]. The matter of pandemic-related shortage has been studied in the past and has been documented in recent events. On the medical side, shortages of [[personal protective equipment]] such as [[Surgical mask|medical masks]], [[Medical glove|gloves]], [[face shield]]s, gear,<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|last=Tiefenth\u00e4ler|first=Ainara|url=https://www.nytimes.com/video/world/europe/100000007051789/coronavirus-ppe-shortage-health-care-workers.html|title='Health Care Kamikazes': How Spain's Workers Are Battling Coronavirus, Unprotected|work=The New York Times|access-date=31 March 2020|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331010547/https://www.nytimes.com/video/world/europe/100000007051789/coronavirus-ppe-shortage-health-care-workers.html|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Sanitizer|sanitizing products]], is also joined by potential shortage of more advanced devices such as [[hospital bed]]s, [[Intensive care unit|ICU beds]], [[oxygen therapy]], [[mechanical ventilation]]<nowiki/>s and [[Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation|ECMO]] devices. Human resources, especially in term of medical staff, may be drained by the overwhelming extent of the epidemic and associated workload, together with losses by contamination, isolation, sickness<ref name=\":14\" /> or mortality among health care workers. While preparing for the Epidemic apex, New York governor [[Andrew Cuomo]], cited as main components for [[Health system|health care system]] to support the apex load to be [[Intensive care unit|ICU]] [[Hospital bed]]s, supplies ([[Personal protective equipment|PPE]]) and equipment, together with relevant-skills [[Health professional|health care workers]], whom are at risk from the virus but also to physical and emotional exhaustion.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AC360/status/1245891038864121862|title=New York Gov. Andrew Cuomo: \"This state had purchased 17,000 ventilators, more than any other state in the nation, and they never got delivered. Because they were all coming from China, and 50 states are competing. ... We can't get any more.\" #CNNTownHall <nowiki>https://cnn.it/2R42aQn\u00a0pic.twitter.com/vFrbIaqMKJ</nowiki>|last=Cooper 360\u00b0|first=Anderson|date=2 April 2020|website=@AC360|access-date=3 April 2020}}{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}</ref> Territories are differently equipped to face the pandemic. Various emergency measures have been taken to ramp up equipment levels such as purchases, while calls for donations, local 3D makers,<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=20200331com/2020/03/31/science/coronavirus-masks-equipment-crowdsource>{{Cite news|last=Petri|first=Alexandra E.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/science/coronavirus-masks-equipment-crowdsource.html|title=D.I.Y. Coronavirus Solutions Are Gaining Steam|date=31 March 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=31 March 2020|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331141002/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/science/coronavirus-masks-equipment-crowdsource.html|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> volunteer staffing, mandatory draft or seizure of stocks and factory lines have also occurred. Inter-countries and inter-States bidding wars over these items are reported to be a major issue<ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":17\" />, with price increase<ref name=\":16\" />, orders seized by local government or cancelled by selling company to be redirected to higher bidder<ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":17\" />. In some cases, medical workers have been ordered to not speak about these resources shortages.<ref name=co9433171>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-nhs-uk-doctors-gagged-england-a9433171.html|title=Doctors claim they have been gagged over protective equipment shortages|date=30 March 2020|website=The Independent|access-date=31 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331050400/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-nhs-uk-doctors-gagged-england-a9433171.html|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Tests==\nTesting shortage is a key element preventing authorities from measuring the true extend of current epidemic spread.<ref name=20200402com/2020/04/02/us/politics/cia-coronavirus-china>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/02/us/politics/cia-coronavirus-china.html|title=C.I.A. Hunts for Authentic Virus Totals in China, Dismissing Government Tallies|first=Julian E.|last=Barnes|date=2 April 2020|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n===Diagnostic tests===\n\n====Reagents====\nIn Ireland and the UK, in late March and early April, reagent shortages limited the number of tests.<ref name=20200401reuters>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-ireland-reagent-idUSL8N2BP2DQ|title=Ireland says reagent shortage to slow COVID-19 tests rollout for 7\u201310 days|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref> By March, insufficient amounts of [[reagent]] has become a [[Bottleneck (production)|bottleneck]] for mass testing in the EU and UK<ref name=20200325eu/sites/default/files/documents/RRA-seventh-update-Outbreak-of-coronavirus-disease-COVID-19>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) pandemic: increased transmission in the EU/EEA and the UK \u2013seventh update |url=https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/sites/default/files/documents/RRA-seventh-update-Outbreak-of-coronavirus-disease-COVID-19.pdf |publisher=[[European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control]] |accessdate=29 March 2020 |pages=15\u201316 |date=25 March 2020 |quote=the current shortages of laboratory consumables and reagents affect diagnostic capacity and hamper the epidemic response at the national and local levels. The laboratories have experienced delayed or missing deliveries of swabbing material, plastic consumables, RNA extraction and RT-PCR reagents, and PPE. This is affecting laboratories in all EU/EEA countries. |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326192834/https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/sites/default/files/documents/RRA-seventh-update-Outbreak-of-coronavirus-disease-COVID-19.pdf |archive-date=26 March 2020 }}</ref> and the US.<ref name=20200324newyorker>{{cite web |last1=Baird |first1=Robert P. |title=Why Widespread Coronavirus Testing Isn't Coming Anytime Soon |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/why-widespread-coronavirus-testing-isnt-coming-anytime-soon |website=[[The New Yorker]] |accessdate=29 March 2020 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200328133105/https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/why-widespread-coronavirus-testing-isnt-coming-anytime-soon |archivedate=28 March 2020  |date=24 March 2020 |quote=South Dakota, said that her state\u2019s public-health laboratory\u2014the only lab doing COVID-19 testing in the state\u2014had so much trouble securing reagents that it was forced to temporarily stop testing altogether. also noted critical shortages of extraction kits, reagents, and test kits |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=qz1822596>{{cite web |last1=Ossola |first1=Alexandra |title=Here are the coronavirus testing materials that are in short supply in the US |url=https://qz.com/1822596/all-the-coronavirus-test-materials-in-short-supply-in-the-us/ |website=Quartz |accessdate=29 March 2020 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200326174135/https://qz.com/1822596/all-the-coronavirus-test-materials-in-short-supply-in-the-us/ |archivedate=26 March 2020  |date=25 March 2020 |quote=extract the virus\u2019s genetic material\u2014in this case, RNA\u2014using a set of chemicals that usually come in pre-assembled kits. \u201cThe big shortage is extraction kits\u201d There are no easy replacements here: \u201cThese reagents that are used in extraction are fairly complex chemicals. They have to be very pure, and they have to be in pure solution\u201d |url-status=live}}</ref> This has led some authors to explore sample preparation protocols that involve heating samples at {{cvt|98|C|F}} for 5 minutes to release [[RNA genome]]s for further testing.<ref name=ssi-boil>{{cite web |last1=Fomsgaard |first1=Anders |title=Statens Serum Institut (SSI) solves essential COVID-19 testing deficiency problem |url=https://en.ssi.dk/news/news/2020/03-ssi--solves-essential-covid19-testing-deficiency-problem |website=en.ssi.dk |publisher=[[Statens Serum Institut]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200329085152/https://en.ssi.dk/news/news/2020/03-ssi--solves-essential-covid19-testing-deficiency-problem |archivedate=29 March 2020  |date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live |quote=several countries are in lack of the chemical reagents necessary to test their citizens for the disease. }}</ref><ref name=cphpost112522>{{cite web |title=Danish researchers behind simple&nbsp;coronavirus test method |work=[[The Copenhagen Post]]|url=http://cphpost.dk/?p=112522 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328130357/http://cphpost.dk/?p=112522 |archivedate=28 March 2020 |date=28 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn UK, on 1 April the government confirmed that a total of 2,000 NHS staff had been tested for coronavirus since the outbreak began, but Cabinet Office Minister Michael Gove said a shortage of chemicals needed for the test meant it was not possible to screen the NHS's 1.2&nbsp;million workforce.<ref name=\"BBC52122761\"/> Gove's statement was contradicted by the [[Chemical Industries Association]], which said there was not a shortage of the relevant chemicals and that at a meeting with a business minister the week before the government had not tried to find out about potential supply problems.<ref name=20200331itv>{{cite news |last1=Preston |first1=Robert |authorlink1=Robert Peston |title=Robert Peston: Is Michael Gove right that there is a shortage of coronavirus test kit ingredients? |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-31/robert-peston-is-gove-right-that-there-is-a-shortage-of-test-kit-ingredients/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[ITV News]] |date=31 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401160117/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-31/robert-peston-is-gove-right-that-there-is-a-shortage-of-test-kit-ingredients/ |archivedate=1 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====Swabs====\nA feared shortage of swabs in [[Iceland]] was averted when stocks were found to bridge the gap until more arrived from China.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.icelandreview.com/news/plenty-of-swabs-for-covid-19-testing/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=3 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331023517/https://www.icelandreview.com/news/plenty-of-swabs-for-covid-19-testing/ |archive-date=31 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Shortages arose in the US, though one manufacturer increased production to 1 million swabs per day.<ref name=npr825499508>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/01/825499508/one-of-the-few-manufacturers-of-the-special-swab-for-coronavirus-tests-speaks|title=Swab Manufacturer Works To Meet 'Overwhelming' Demand|publisher=NPR}}</ref> Shortages also arose in the UK, but were resolve by 2 April.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2020-04-02/uk-has-fixed-swab-shortage-problem-for-coronavirus-testing-minister-says</ref>\n\n===Antibody tests===\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Personal protective equipment ==\nMasks, gloves, closes, and sanitising products have been in shortage. A survey of medical personnel pointed out at the lack of proper equipment as the main issue in their current efforts, with 90% claiming they went to work without the proper equipment.<ref name=20200325com/2020/03/25/business/media/coronavirus-nurses-stories-anonymous>{{Cite news|last=Lee|first=Edmund|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/business/media/coronavirus-nurses-stories-anonymous.html|title=Nurses Share Coronavirus Stories Anonymously in an Online Document|date=25 March 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=25 March 2020|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325205951/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/business/media/coronavirus-nurses-stories-anonymous.html|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGiven that the global supply of [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE) is insufficient, the [[World Health Organization]] recommends minimising the need for PPE through [[telemedicine]], physical barriers such as clear windows, allowing only those involved in direct care to enter a room with a COVID-19 patient, using only the PPE necessary for the specific task, continuing use of the same respirator without removing it while caring for multiple patients with the same diagnosis, monitoring and coordinating the PPE supply chain, and discouraging the use of masks for asymptomatic individuals.<ref name=\":32\">{{cite web|url=https://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/331215/WHO-2019-nCov-IPCPPE_use-2020.1-eng.pdf|title=Rational use of personal protective equipment for coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19)|date=27 February 2020|website=World Health Organization|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303000654/https://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/331215/WHO-2019-nCov-IPCPPE_use-2020.1-eng.pdf|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Sanitising products ===\n[[Hand sanitizer|Hand sanitiser]] was largely out of stocks in many areas, causing price gouging.<ref name=20200316com/2020/03/16/learning/is-it-immoral-to-increase-the-price-of-goods-during-a-crisis>{{Cite news|last=Doyne|first=Shannon|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/learning/is-it-immoral-to-increase-the-price-of-goods-during-a-crisis.html|title=Is It Immoral to Increase the Price of Goods During a Crisis?|date=16 March 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=26 March 2020|last2=Gonchar|first2=Michael|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326130830/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/learning/is-it-immoral-to-increase-the-price-of-goods-during-a-crisis.html|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Protective gear ===\nIn the United States, some nurses at one New York City hospital have been reported as wearing garbage bags as an alternative to unavailable protective clothing.<ref name=20200325nypost>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/25/worker-at-nyc-hospital-where-nurses-wear-trash-bags-as-protection-dies-from-coronavirus/|title=Worker at NYC hospital where nurses wear trash bags as protection dies from coronavirus|last=Bowden|first=Ebony|last2=Campanile|first2=Carl|date=25 March 2020|website=New York Post|access-date=26 March 2020|last3=Golding|first3=Bruce|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326131114/https://nypost.com/2020/03/25/worker-at-nyc-hospital-where-nurses-wear-trash-bags-as-protection-dies-from-coronavirus/|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Facial masks ===\n==== Early epidemic in China ====\n[[File:Citizens of Wuhan lining up outside of a drug store to buy masks during the Wuhan coronavirus outbreak.jpg|thumb|People in Wuhan lining up in front of a drug store to buy [[surgical masks]]]]\n[[File:Surgical mask and 84 disinfectant liquid purchase limit notice at a CSF Market (20200202155633).jpg|thumb|A notice at a supermarket in Beijing, which says each person can only buy one pack of surgical masks and one bottle of 84 disinfectant liquid a day]]\n\nAs the epidemic accelerated, the mainland market saw a shortage of [[Surgical mask|face masks]] due to the increased need from the public.<ref name=sohu161795>{{cite news|author=\u8c22\u658c \u5f20\u7eaf|url=http://www.sohu.com/a/368299105_161795|title=\u4e00\u7f69\u96be\u6c42\uff1a\u5357\u90fd\u6c11\u8c03\u5b9e\u6d4b\u8d70\u8bbf\u53d1\u73b0\uff0c\u7ebf\u4e0a\u7ebf\u4e0b\u53e3\u7f69\u57fa\u672c\u5356\u8131\u9500|date=21 January 2020|accessdate=21 January 2020|agency=\u5357\u65b9\u90fd\u5e02\u62a5}}</ref> It was reported that Shanghai customers had to queue for nearly an hour to buy a pack of face masks which was sold out in another half an hour.<ref name=udn4304194>{{cite news|author1=\u5f90\u6986\u6db5|url=https://money.udn.com/money/story/5648/4304194|title=\u5168\u7403\u5404\u5730\u760b\u6436\u53e3\u7f69 \u5c08\u5bb6\uff1a\u4e0d\u5fc5\u8cb7N95|date=23 January 2020|accessdate=25 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125103023/https://money.udn.com/money/story/5648/4304194|archive-date=25 January 2020|publisher=\u806f\u5408\u5831|url-status=live}}</ref> Some stores are hoarding, driving up prices and other acts, so the market regulator said it will crack down on such acts.<ref name=southcn190111854>{{cite news|author=\u5218\u704f|url=http://economy.southcn.com/e/2020-01/21/content_190111854.htm|title=\u5e7f\u4e1c\u5e02\u573a\u76d1\u7ba1\u90e8\u95e8\uff1a\u5c06\u575a\u51b3\u6253\u51fb\u56e4\u79ef\u5c45\u5947\u3001\u54c4\u62ac\u4ef7\u683c\u7b49\u884c\u4e3a|date=21 January 2020|accessdate=21 January 2020|agency=\u5357\u65b9\u7f51}}</ref><ref name=gov1620613>{{cite web|url=http://scjgj.beijing.gov.cn/zwxx/ttgg/202001/t20200122_1620613.html|title=\u5e02\u573a\u4ef7\u683c\u884c\u4e3a\u63d0\u9192\u4e66|date=n.d.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127080911/http://scjgj.beijing.gov.cn/zwxx/ttgg/202001/t20200122_1620613.html|archive-date=27 January 2020|accessdate=|url-status=live}}</ref> The shortage will not be relieved until late February when most workers return from the New Year vacation according to Lei Limin, an expert in the industry.<ref name=chinanews9074410>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinanews.com/sh/2020/01-31/9074410.shtml|title=\u4e13\u5bb6\uff1a\u53e3\u7f69\u77ed\u7f3a2\u6708\u5e95\u6216\u7f13\u89e3|last=Liu|first=Yuying|date=31 January 2020|website=\u4e2d\u65b0\u7f51|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202154104/http://www.chinanews.com/sh/2020/01-31/9074410.shtml|archive-date=2 February 2020|access-date=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 January 2020, [[Taobao]], China's largest e-commerce platform owned by [[Alibaba Group]], said that all face masks on [[Taobao]] and [[Tmall]] would not be allowed to increase in price. Special subsidies would be provided to the retailers. Also, Alibaba Health's \"urgent drug delivery\" service would not be closed during the Spring Festival.<ref name=ycwb30486944>{{cite news|author=\u9648\u6cfd\u4e91|url=http://news.ycwb.com/2020-01/22/content_30486944.htm|title=\u53e3\u7f69\u4e70\u4e0d\u5230\u600e\u4e48\u529e\uff1f\u8fd9\u4e9b\u836f\u5e97\u5e73\u53f0\u6625\u8282\u671f\u95f4\u6301\u7eed\u4f9b\u5e94|date=22 January 2020|accessdate=22 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122102833/http://news.ycwb.com/2020-01/22/content_30486944.htm|archive-date=22 January 2020|agency=\u91d1\u7f8a\u7f51|url-status=live}}</ref> [[JD.com|JD]], another leading Chinese e-commerce platform, said, \"We are actively working to ensure supply and price stability from sources, storage and distribution, platform control and so on\" and \"while fully ensuring price stability for JD's own commodities, JD.com has also exercised strict control over the commodities on JD's platform. Third-party vendors selling face masks are prohibited from raising prices. Once it is confirmed that the prices of third-party vendors have increased abnormally, JD will immediately remove the offending commodities from shelves and deal with the offending vendors accordingly.\"<ref name=bjnews677805>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjnews.com.cn/finance/2020/01/22/677805.html|title=\u4eac\u4e1c\uff1a\u7981\u6b62\u7b2c\u4e09\u65b9\u5546\u5bb6\u53e3\u7f69\u6da8\u4ef7|author=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5|date=22 January 2020|website=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127082917/http://www.bjnews.com.cn/finance/2020/01/22/677805.html|archive-date=27 January 2020|access-date=22 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Other major e-commerce platforms including Sunning.com and [[Pinduoduo]] also promised to keep the prices of health products stable.<ref name=bjnews677744>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjnews.com.cn/finance/2020/01/22/677744.html|title=\u62fc\u591a\u591a\uff1a\u5bf9\u53e3\u7f69\u7b49\u4ea7\u54c1\u8fdb\u884c\u76d1\u6d4b\uff0c\u6076\u610f\u6da8\u4ef7\u8005\u5c06\u4e0b\u67b6|author=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5|date=22 January 2020|website=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122023043/http://www.bjnews.com.cn/finance/2020/01/22/677744.html|archive-date=22 January 2020|access-date=22 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=bjnews677740>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjnews.com.cn/finance/2020/01/22/677740.html|title=\u82cf\u5b81\u6613\u8d2d\uff1a\u53e3\u7f69\u7b49\u5065\u5eb7\u7c7b\u5546\u54c1\u7981\u6da8\u4ef7\uff0c\u5e76\u5f00\u5c55\u767e\u4ebf\u8865\u8d34|author=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5|date=22 January 2020|website=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122023040/http://www.bjnews.com.cn/finance/2020/01/22/677740.html|archive-date=22 January 2020|access-date=22 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFigures from China Customs show that some 2.46&nbsp;billion pieces of epidemic prevention and control materials had been imported between 24 January and 29 February, including 2.02&nbsp;billion masks and 25.38&nbsp;million items of protective clothing valued at 8.2&nbsp;billion yuan ($1&nbsp;billion). Press reported that the [[China Poly Group]], together with other Chinese companies and state-owned enterprises, had an important role in scouring markets abroad to procure essential medical supplies and equipment for China.<ref name=smh20200402>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/billions-of-face-masks-sent-to-china-during-australian-bushfire-crisis-20200402-p54gjh.html|title=Billions of face masks sent to China during bushfire crisis|first=Kate McClymont, Royce|last=Millar|date=2 April 2020|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> [[Risland]] (formerly Country Garden)  sourced 82 tonnes of supplies, which were subsequently airlifted to Wuhan.<ref name=20200326smh>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/second-developer-flies-82-tonnes-of-medical-supplies-to-china-20200326-p54e8n.html  |title=Second developer flew 82 tonnes of medical supplies to China |author=McClymont, Kate|date=27 March 2020|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Rest of the world ====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"float:right; font-size:0.9em;\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"7\" | Can facial masks be disinfected for re-use?<ref name=\":7\" />\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Cleaning method\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" | Meltblown fiber filtration media\n! colspan=\"2\" | Static-charged cotton\n! rowspan=\"2\" | ''E. Coli.''\nDisinfection\n|-\n!Min.\n!Filtration (%)\n!Pressure drop (Pa)\n!Filtration (%)\n!Pressure drop (Pa)\n|-\n|Masks before treatment\n|(null)\n|style=\"background:#60ff60aa;\"| 96.76\n|style=\"background:#60ff60aa;\"| 8.33\n|style=\"background:#60ff60aa;\"| 78.01\n|style=\"background:#60ff60aa;\"| 5.33\n|style=\"background:#60ff60aa;\"| (no E.Coli.)\n|-\n|70&nbsp;\u00b0C hot air in oven\n|30\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 96.60\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 8.00\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 70.16\n|4.67\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| >99%\n|-\n|Ultraviolet light\n|30\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 95.50\n|7.00\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 77.72\n|6.00\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| >99%\n|-\n| 5% alcohol soaking, drying\n|n.a.\n|style=\"background:#ff606088;\"| 56.33\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 7.67\n|style=\"background:#ff606088;\"| 29.24\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 5.33\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| >99%\n|-\n|Chlorine-based\n|5\n|style=\"background:#ff606088;\"| 73.11\n|9.00\n|style=\"background:#ff606088;\"| 57.33\n|7.00\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| >99%\n|-\n|Vapor from boiling water\n|10\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 94.74\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 8.00\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 77.65\n|7.00\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| >99%\n|}\n\nShortage in single-use medical mask and field reports of reuse lead to the question of which process could properly sanitise these PPE without altering their filtering capacity.<ref name=\":7\" /> In 2006, 156 million masks were added to the US [[Strategic National Stockpile]] in prevision of a flu pandemic.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|last=Manjoo|first=Farhad|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/opinion/coronavirus-face-mask.html|title=Opinion {{!}} How the World's Richest Country Ran Out of a 75-Cent Face Mask|date=25 March 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=25 March 2020|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325205952/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/opinion/coronavirus-face-mask.html|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> After they were used against the [[2009 flu pandemic]], neither the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] nor the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump administration]] renewed the stocks.<ref name=\":8\"/>\n\n[[FFP2]] masks can be sanitised by 70&nbsp;\u00b0C vapor allowing reuses.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://stanfordmedicine.app.box.com/v/covid19-PPE-1-1|title=Addressing COVID-19 Face Mask Shortages [v1.1] : Can Facial Masks be Disinfected for Re-use?|last1=Price|first1=Amy|last2=Chu|first2=Larry|date=22 March 2020|website=stanfordmedicine.app.box.com|publisher=[[Stanford University]] Anesthesia Informatics and Media Lab, [[COVID-19]] Evidence Service Report|page=5|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323234628/https://stanfordmedicine.app.box.com/v/covid19-PPE-1-1|archive-date=23 March 2020|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> Use of alcohol is discouraged since it alters [[N95 mask]] microfibers' static charge which helps filtration.<ref name=\":7\" /> Chlorine is also discouraged since its fumes may be harmful.<ref name=\":7\" /> Authors are warning against reuses by non-professionals, pointing out that even the best scored methods can degrade the mask if not performed properly.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=sciencesetavenir142836>{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencesetavenir.fr/sante/covid-19-des-medecins-decontaminent-leur-masque-ffp2-en-les-passant-au-four_142836|title=Covid-19: des chercheurs tentent de d\u00e9contaminer les masques \u2013 Sciences et Avenir|date=27 March 2020|website=sciencesetavenir.fr|language=fr|access-date=28 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328045554/https://www.sciencesetavenir.fr/sante/covid-19-des-medecins-decontaminent-leur-masque-ffp2-en-les-passant-au-four_142836|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing [[N95 masks]] shortages, volunteers created 3D printed \"NanoHack\" alternative.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/societe/coronavirus-quand-les-inventeurs-viennent-a-la-rescousse-des-hopitaux-23-03-2020-8286186.php|title=Coronavirus : quand les inventeurs viennent \u00e0 la rescousse des h\u00f4pitaux|last=Opoczynski|first=David|date=23 March 2020|website=Le Parisien|language=fr-FR|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324220615/http://www.leparisien.fr/societe/coronavirus-quand-les-inventeurs-viennent-a-la-rescousse-des-hopitaux-23-03-2020-8286186.php|archive-date=24 March 2020|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> This printed mask allows to use hand-cut [[surgical mask]] as fine-particle filters.<ref name=\":4\" /> Vacuum bags can be sewn into masks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/kevin-drum/2020/03/how-to-make-a-homemade-mask-if-you-absolutely-have-to/|title=How to make a homemade mask if you absolutely have to|last=Drum|first=Kevin|website=Mother Jones|access-date=26 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326004750/https://www.motherjones.com/kevin-drum/2020/03/how-to-make-a-homemade-mask-if-you-absolutely-have-to/|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA Singaporean study found no contamination on mask after brief care to COVID19 patients, suggesting masks could be reuse for multiple patients cares.<ref name=cambridge900526>{{cite journal |author=Institution login |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/infection-control-and-hospital-epidemiology/article/absence-of-contamination-of-personal-protective-equipment-ppe-by-severe-acute-respiratory-syndrome-coronavirus-2-sarscov2/EA37207FECDD23BE900526CEE5BA9430 |title=Absence of contamination of personal protective equipment (PPE) by Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) &#124; Infection Control & Hospital Epidemiology &#124; Cambridge Core |journal=Infection Control & Hospital Epidemiology |doi=10.1017/ice.2020.91 |publisher=Cambridge.org |date=26 March 2020 |pages=1\u20136 |pmid=32213231 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328233703/https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/infection-control-and-hospital-epidemiology/article/absence-of-contamination-of-personal-protective-equipment-ppe-by-severe-acute-respiratory-syndrome-coronavirus-2-sarscov2/EA37207FECDD23BE900526CEE5BA9430 |archive-date=28 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April, US's [[Strategic National Stockpile]] was nearly emptied.<ref name=washingtonpost7148009252>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/coronavirus-protective-gear-stockpile-depleted/2020/04/01/44d6592a-741f-11ea-ae50-7148009252e3_story.html|title=Protective gear in national stockpile is nearly depleted, DHS officials say|last=enforcement|first=Nick Miroff closeNick MiroffReporter covering immigration|last2=Homel|first2=the Department of|website=The Washington Post|access-date=1 April 2020|last3=SecurityEmailEmailBioBioFollowFollow|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401225900/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/coronavirus-protective-gear-stockpile-depleted/2020/04/01/44d6592a-741f-11ea-ae50-7148009252e3_story.html|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>{{clarify|date=April 2020}} French regional representative complained that the United States, in their aggressive search for stocks, had been making tarmac bids for stocks of masks ordered, paying 3 times the price.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfmtv.com/mediaplayer/video/valerie-pecresse-sur-les-masques-nous-avons-ete-confrontes-a-cette-situation-ou-des-americains-ont-surencheri-1235950.html|title=Val\u00e9rie P\u00e9cresse sur les masques: \u00ab Des Am\u00e9ricains ont surench\u00e9ri \u00bb|via=bfmtv.com}}</ref>\n\nIn late-March/early-April 2020, as Western countries were in turn dependent on China for supplies of masks and other equipment, China was seen as making soft-power play to influence world opinion.<ref name=bbc52092395/><ref name=20200402businessinsider/> However, some of the supplies sent to Spain, Turkey and the Netherlands was reportedly rejected as being sub-standard. Dutch health ministry issued a recall of 600,000 face masks from a Chinese supplier on 21 March did not fit properly and whose filters did not work as intended despite them having a quality certificate;<ref name=bbc52092395>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-52092395|title=Countries reject Chinese-made equipment|date=30 March 2020|via=bbc.com}}</ref><ref name=\"20200402businessinsider\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.fr/us/china-face-mask-defective-double-check-instructions-2020-4|title=Chinese government rejects allegations that its face masks were defective, tells countries to 'double check' instructions|first=David|last=Choi|date=2 April 2020|website=Business Insider France}}</ref><ref name=\"20200402businessinsider\"/> The Spanish government alleged that 60,000 out of 340,000 test kits from a Chinese manufacturer did not accurately test for COVID-19.<ref name=20200402businessinsider/> The Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs responded that the customer should \"double-check the instructions to make sure that you ordered, paid for and distributed the right ones. Do not use non-surgical masks for surgical purposes\".<ref name=20200402businessinsider/>\n\n====Do it yourself masks====\nGiven the scarecity of masks and ambiguity on their efficiency, individuals and volunteers have started to produce masks for themselves or for others.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite news|last=Sindya|first=Bhanoo|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/wellness/masks-diy-coronavirus/2020/04/01/20830f5e-7420-11ea-85cb-8670579b863d_story.html|title=Which DIY mask pattern should you use? Even experts can't pick one to recommend.|date=1 April 2020|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401220027/https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/wellness/masks-diy-coronavirus/2020/04/01/20830f5e-7420-11ea-85cb-8670579b863d_story.html|archive-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> Various designs are shared online to ease creation.<ref name=\":15\" />{{Explain|reason=|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== Medical face shield ===\n[[File:Visor frame v10.stl|thumb|right|A 3d printable face shield frame.]]\nReacting to shortage of face shield, volunteers from the [[Maker culture|maker community]] with [[3D printing]] abilities initiated an effort to produce face-shields for hospitals' staff.<ref name=\":4\" /> On 24 March, while the epidemic was expanding, popular French 3D maker and YouTuber Heliox announced her willingness to produce face-shields for free building upon another maker's design.<ref name=\":13\">{{cite web|url=https://www.lci.fr/high-tech/l-imprimante-3d-au-secours-des-hopitaux-pour-lutter-contre-le-coronavirus-2149112.html|title=L'imprimante 3D au secours des h\u00f4pitaux pour lutter contre le coronavirus|website=LCI|language=fr|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329153244/https://www.lci.fr/high-tech/l-imprimante-3d-au-secours-des-hopitaux-pour-lutter-contre-le-coronavirus-2149112.html|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She was quickly contacted by local hospitals, health centres and other medical professionals asking for rapid delivery of face shield.<ref name=\":13\" /> The visible popularity of her initiative caused other 3D makers to join the effort and offer their help in other regions to connect health facilities with nearby makers.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nOn 30 March, the [[The New York Times]] published a video on COVID-19-related shortages and healthcare workers' DIY solutions.<ref name=\":14\" />{{Clarify|reason=|date=March 2020}}\n\n'''3D printed [[Face shield#Medical|medical face shield]] created in response to COVID19's medical shortage'''\n<gallery>\nFile:3D-printed visor-Heliox Lab-01.jpg\nFile:3D-printed visor-Heliox Lab-02.jpg\nFile:3D-printed visor-Heliox Lab-03.jpg\nFile:3D-printed visor-Heliox Lab-04.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n== Medical care devices ==\nThe availability of critical care beds or ICU beds,<ref name=20200316theguardian>{{cite news|last=Srivastava|first=Ranjana|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/mar/17/now-more-than-ever-we-have-to-be-honest-about-intensive-care-beds|title=Now more than ever, we have to be honest about intensive care beds|date=16 March 2020|work=The Guardian|accessdate=17 March 2020|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323151959/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/mar/17/now-more-than-ever-we-have-to-be-honest-about-intensive-care-beds|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[mechanical ventilation]]<ref name=20200318com/2020/03/18/business/ventilator-shortage-coronavirus>{{Cite news|last=Kliff|first=Sarah|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/business/ventilator-shortage-coronavirus.html|title=There Aren't Enough Ventilators to Cope With the Coronavirus|date=18 March 2020|work=The New York Times|accessdate=18 March 2020|last2=Satariano|first2=Adam|issn=0362-4331|last3=Silver-Greenberg|first3=Jessica|last4=Kulish|first4=Nicholas|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318190318/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/business/ventilator-shortage-coronavirus.html|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Daugherty Biddison 848\u2013854\">{{Cite journal|last=Daugherty Biddison|first=E. Lee|last2=Faden|first2=Ruth|last3=Gwon|first3=Howard S.|last4=Mareiniss|first4=Darren P.|last5=Regenberg|first5=Alan C.|last6=Schoch-Spana|first6=Monica|last7=Schwartz|first7=Jack|last8=Toner|first8=Eric S.|date=1 April 2019|title=Too Many Patients\u2026A Framework to Guide Statewide Allocation of Scarce Mechanical Ventilation During Disasters|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0012369218325650|journal=Chest|volume=155|issue=4|pages=848\u2013854|doi=10.1016/j.chest.2018.09.025|pmid=30316913|issn=0012-3692}}</ref> and [[Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation|ECMO]] devices<ref name=\"Ronco 240\u2013241\">{{Cite journal|last=Ronco|first=Claudio|last2=Navalesi|first2=Paolo|last3=Vincent|first3=Jean Louis|date=1 March 2020|title=Coronavirus epidemic: preparing for extracorporeal organ support in intensive care|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lanres/article/PIIS2213-2600(20)30060-6/abstract|journal=The Lancet Respiratory Medicine|volume=8|issue=3|pages=240\u2013241|doi=10.1016/S2213-2600(20)30060-6|issn=2213-2600|pmid=32035509}}</ref> generally closely associated with [[List of countries by hospital beds|hospital beds]] has been described as a critical bottleneck in responding to the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. The lack of such devices dramatically raises the mortality rate of COVID-19.\n\n=== Oxygenation mask ===\n[[File:Decathlon_Easybreath_snorkel_mask.jpg|thumb|Common snorkeling masks have been adapted into oxygenation masks via minor changes and 3D-printed adapters.]]\nPopular [[Snorkeling]] masks have been adapted into oxygen dispensing emergency respiratory masks via the usage of 3D printed adapters and minimal modifications to the original mask.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w4Csqdxkrfw|title=Video: Emergency mask for hospital ventilators|date=n.d.|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325193405/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w4Csqdxkrfw|archive-date=25 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.isinnova.it/easy-covid19-eng/|title=Easy \u2013 Covid19 : Emergency mask for hospital ventilators|last=Isinnova|date=n.d.|website=Isinnova|language=it-IT|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324231946/https://www.isinnova.it/easy-covid19-eng/|archive-date=24 March 2020|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> According to Italian laws relative to medical cares where the project has occurs, usage by the patient requires a signed declaration of acceptance of use of an uncertified biomedical device.<ref name=\":5\" /> The project provides the 3D files for free, as well as 2 forms to register hospitals in need and 3D makers willing to produces adapters.<ref name=\":5\" />\nFrance main sportwear and snorkeling masks producer [[Decathlon]] has locked down is mask sales to redirect them toward medical staff, patients and 3D makers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uZ5Vtf69cAA |title=Pourquoi ne pas distribuer des masques de plong\u00e9e D\u00e9cathlon? BFMTV r\u00e9pond \u00e0 vos questions |via=YouTube |date=n.d.|accessdate=1 April 2020|language=French}}</ref>\n\n=== Intensive care beds ===\n{{See also|List of countries by hospital beds}}\nBoth rich countries and [[developing countries]] have or will face [[intensive care beds]] shortages, but the situation is expected to be more intense in developing countries due to lower equipment levels.<ref name=scmp3077552>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/opinion/article/3077552/why-coronavirus-lockdowns-will-not-be-easy-developing-countries |title=Why coronavirus lockdowns will not be easy for developing countries, and what they can learn |work=South China Morning Post |date=n.d.|accessdate=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330120606/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/opinion/article/3077552/why-coronavirus-lockdowns-will-not-be-easy-developing-countries |archive-date=30 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn early March, the UK government supported a strategy to develop natural [[herd immunity]], drawing sharp criticism from medical personnel and researchers.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/u-k-realized-its-coronavirus-plan-could-kill-over-100-000.html|title=U.K. Only Grasped in the 'Last Few Days' It Had the Exact Wrong Coronavirus Plan|last=Stieb|first=Matt|date=16 March 2020|website=Intelligencer|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317215047/https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/u-k-realized-its-coronavirus-plan-could-kill-over-100-000.html|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Various forecasts by [[Imperial College COVID-19 Response Team]], made public on 16 March, suggested that the peak number of cases in the UK would require between 100 and 225 CCBs / 100,000 inhabitants,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-COVID19-NPI-modelling-16-03-2020.pdf|title=Impact of non-pharmaceutical interventions (NPIs) to reduce COVID19 mortality and healthcare demand|last=Imperial College COVID-19 Response Team|date=16 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316223332/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-COVID19-NPI-modelling-16-03-2020.pdf|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> if proper mitigation or no mitigation strategies are put into force, respectively. These requirements would both exceed the UK's current capacities of 6.6<ref name=\"Rhodes2012a2\">{{cite journal|last=Rhodes|first=A.|last2=Ferdinande|first2=P.|last3=Flaatten|first3=H.|last4=Guidet|first4=B.|last5=Metnitz|first5=P. G.|last6=Moreno|first6=R. P.|date=1 October 2012|title=The variability of critical care bed numbers in Europe|journal=Intensive Care Medicine|volume=38|issue=10|pages=1647\u20131653|doi=10.1007/s00134-012-2627-8|pmid=22777516|issn=1432-1238}}</ref>\u201314<ref name=\":0\" /> CCB / 100,000 inhabitants. In the best case scenario, the peak caseload would require 7.5 times the current number of available ICU beds.<ref name=20200315co>{{Cite news|last=Batchelor|first=George|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/hospitals-could-need-75-times-number-critical-care-beds-treat/|title=Hospitals could need 7.5 times the number of critical care beds to treat virus patients|date=15 March 2020|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=17 March 2020|issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323151959/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/hospitals-could-need-75-times-number-critical-care-beds-treat/|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Around 16 March, the UK government changed trajectory toward a more standard mitigation/suppression strategy.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|France]], around 15 March, the [[Grand Est]] region was the first to express the scarcity of CCB limiting its handling of the crisis.<ref name=europe13955371>{{cite web|url=https://www.europe1.fr/sante/coronavirus-dans-le-grand-est-pratiquement-tous-les-lits-de-reanimation-sont-occupes-3955371|title=Coronavirus : dans le Grand Est, \"pratiquement tous les lits de r\u00e9animation sont occup\u00e9s\"|website=Europe 1|access-date=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317174350/https://www.europe1.fr/sante/coronavirus-dans-le-grand-est-pratiquement-tous-les-lits-de-reanimation-sont-occupes-3955371|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Assistance Publique \u2013 H\u00f4pitaux de Paris|Assistance-publique H\u00f4pitaux de Paris]] (AP-HP), which manages most hospitals in the French capital area (~10&nbsp;million inhabitants), reported the need for 3,000\u20134,000 ICUs.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2020/03/17/covid-19-des-milliers-de-lits-de-reanimation-necessaires-dans-les-hopitaux-parisiens_6033380_3244.html|title=Covid-19 : l'AP-HP s'attend \u00e0 faire face \u00e0 une vague d'hospitalisation bien plus haute que pr\u00e9vu|date=17 March 2020|work=Le Monde.fr|accessdate=17 March 2020|language=fr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323151957/https://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2020/03/17/covid-19-des-milliers-de-lits-de-reanimation-necessaires-dans-les-hopitaux-parisiens_6033380_3244.html|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Current capacity is reported to be between 1500<ref name=\":1\" /> and 350,<ref>See [[:fr:Assistance Publique \u2013 H\u00f4pitaux de Paris|Assistance Publique \u2013 H\u00f4pitaux de Paris]].</ref> depending on the source.\n\nIn France, given shortages of ICU hospital beds in [[Grand Est]] and [[Ile-de-France]] regions, severe but stable patients with ARS and breathing assistance have been moved toward other regional medical centers within France, Germany, Austria, Luxembourg or Switzerland.<ref name=bfmtv1235967>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfmtv.com/mediaplayer/video/les-transferts-de-malades-du-coronavirus-se-poursuivent-pour-desengorger-les-regions-saturees-1235967.html|title=Les transferts de malades du coronavirus se poursuivent pour d\u00e9sengorger les r\u00e9gions satur\u00e9es|via=bfmtv.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Mechanical ventilation ===\n[[Mechanical ventilation]] have been called ''\"the device that becomes the decider between life and death\"''<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90477940/these-good-samaritans-with-a-3d-printer-are-saving-lives-by-making-new-respirator-valves-for-free|title=These Good Samaritans with a 3D printer are saving lives by making new respirator valves for free|last=Toussaint|first=Kristin|date=16 March 2020|publisher=Fast Company|access-date=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326042513/https://www.fastcompany.com/90477940/these-good-samaritans-with-a-3d-printer-are-saving-lives-by-making-new-respirator-valves-for-free|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> for COVID-19 patients, due to COVID19 being a respiratory disease sending all about 5% of detected cases to rely on the device now in shortage.<ref name=\":6\" /> Ventilators shortage is endemic in the [[Developing country|developing world]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Krishnamoorthy|first=Vijay|last2=Vavilala|first2=Monica S.|last3=Mock|first3=Charles N.|year=2014|title=The need for ventilators in the developing world: An opportunity to improve care and save lives|journal=Journal of Global Health|volume=4|issue=1|page=010303|doi=10.7189/jogh.04.010303|issn=2047-2978|pmc=4073242|pmid=24976958}}</ref> In case of shortage, some triage strategies have been previously discussed. One strategy is to grade the patient on dimensions such as : prospects for short-term survival ; prospects for long-term survival ; stage of life-related considerations ; pregnancy and fair chance.<ref name=\"Daugherty Biddison 848\u2013854\" /> The frequent 15 to 20 days duration of the intubation to recover is an important factor in the ventilator's shortage.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Facing Covid-19 in Italy \u2013 Ethics, Logistics, and Therapeutics on the Epidemic's Front Line|first=Lisa|last=Rosenbaum|date=18 March 2020|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=0|doi=10.1056/NEJMp2005492|pmid = 32187459}}</ref>\n\nAn important way of reducing demand for ventilators is the use of CPAP devices as a first resort.  For this reason CPAP devices themselves have become a scarce item.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==== Officials assessments ====\nIn the 2000s, the US CDC estimated a shortage of 40~70,000 ventilators in case of pandemic influenza.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|last=Kulish|first=Nicholas|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/29/business/coronavirus-us-ventilator-shortage.html|title=The U.S. Tried to Build a New Fleet of Ventilators. The Mission Failed.|date=29 March 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=29 March 2020|last2=Kliff|first2=Sarah|issn=0362-4331|last3=Silver-Greenberg|first3=Jessica|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329151242/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/29/business/coronavirus-us-ventilator-shortage.html|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> From this assessment resulted ''Project Aura'', a public-private initiative to design a frugal, 3,000 US$ mechanical ventilator, simple to mass-produce, and able to supply the [[Strategic National Stockpile]].<ref name=\":12\" /> [[Newport Medical Instruments]] was granted the contract, designing and prototyping (2011) the frugal ventilators to CDC officials, and expecting to later profit from the product by moving into the private market were other competing devices were sold for 10,000US$.<ref name=\":12\" /> On April 2012, [[United States Department of Health and Human Services|US Health and Human Services]] officials confirmed to the [[United States Congress|US Congress]] that the project was on schedule to file for market approval in late 2013, after which the device would go into mass-production.<ref name=\":12\" /> In May 2012, US$12&nbsp;billion-worth medical conglomerate [[Covidien]], a top actor of the mechanical ventilation market, acquired Newport for 100 million US$.<ref name=\":12\" /> Covidien soon asked to cancel the ''Project Aura'' contract since it wasn't profitable enough.<ref name=\":12\" /> Former Newport executives, government officials and executives at rival ventilator companies suspect Covidien acquired Newport to prevent the frugal 3,000 ventilator design from disturbing its profitable ventilation operation.<ref name=\":12\" /> Covidien has merged in 2015 into [[Medtronic]].<ref name=\":12\" />  ''Project Aura'' looked for and then signed a new contract with [[Philips healthcare]]. In July 2019, the [[Food and Drug Administration|FDA]] signed for 10,000 units of their [[Trilogy Evo]] portable ventilator, to be delivered to the SNS by mid-2020.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nOn 25 March, Andrew Cuomo made a detailed 1-hour COVID-19 press conference,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pscp.tv/NYGovCuomo/1DXxyeovOoYxM|title=Andrew Cuomo @NYGovCuomo|last=Inc|first=Twitter|website=Periscope|access-date=26 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327001048/https://www.pscp.tv/NYGovCuomo/1DXxyeovOoYxM|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=20200325youtube>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wjGq1SsuPwU|title=New York Gov. Cuomo holds briefing on the coronavirus pandemic|date=25 March 2020|website=|publisher=CNBC|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331205742/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wjGq1SsuPwU|archive-date=31 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref> emphasising an expectation of a severe shortage of ventilators, and their importance in sustaining life in severe COVID-19 cases.<ref name=\":11\">{{cite web|url=https://www.governor.ny.gov/news/video-audio-photos-rush-transcript-amid-ongoing-covid-19-pandemic-governor-cuomo-announces-2|title=Video, Audio, Photos & Rush Transcript: Amid Ongoing COVID-19 Pandemic, Governor Cuomo Announces 40,000 Health Professionals Have Signed Up to Volunteer as Part of The State's Surge Healthcare Force|date=25 March 2020|website=Governor Andrew M. Cuomo|access-date=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327001059/https://www.governor.ny.gov/news/video-audio-photos-rush-transcript-amid-ongoing-covid-19-pandemic-governor-cuomo-announces-2|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Cuomo said New York state would ultimately need about 30,000 ventilators to handle the influx, while having only 4,000 as of 25 March; on the 27th, President Trump expressed doubt about the need, saying \"I don't believe you need 40,000 or 30,000 ventilators,\" and resisting calls to force businesses to produce them.<ref name=20200327theguardian>{{Cite news|last=Evelyn|first=Kenya|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/27/trump-ventilators-coronavirus-cuomo-new-york|title=Trump on urgent requests for ventilators: 'I don't believe you need 30,000'|date=27 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=28 March 2020|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328152527/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/27/trump-ventilators-coronavirus-cuomo-new-york|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":11\" /> Later on the 27th, the President acceded to calls to assist states in ventilator procurement, using the [[Defense Production Act of 1950|Defense Production Act]]; fears remain that procurement will not happen in time to prevent severe shortages.<ref name=20200327com/2020/03/27/us/politics/coronavirus-trump-ventilators-gm-ventec>{{Cite news|last=Sanger|first=David E.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/27/us/politics/coronavirus-trump-ventilators-gm-ventec.html|title=Under Intense Criticism, Trump Says Government Will Buy More Ventilators|date=27 March 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=28 March 2020|last2=Haberman|first2=Maggie|issn=0362-4331|last3=Karni|first3=Annie|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328151652/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/27/us/politics/coronavirus-trump-ventilators-gm-ventec.html|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Industrial suppliers ====\nIn Europe, the company [[L\u00f6wenstein Medical]] producing 1500 ICU-level ventilators and 20,000 home-level ventilator per year for France alone, pointed out of the current high demand and production shortage.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/replay-radio/l-interview-eco/coronavirus-la-demande-en-ventilateurs-et-respirateurs-artificiels-est-devenue-colossale-explique-un-specialiste-dans-le-materiel-medical_3849549.html|title=Coronavirus : la demande en ventilateurs et respirateurs artificiels est devenue \"colossale\", explique un sp\u00e9cialiste dans le mat\u00e9riel m\u00e9dical|date=17 March 2020|website=Franceinfo|language=fr|access-date=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319185356/https://www.francetvinfo.fr/replay-radio/l-interview-eco/coronavirus-la-demande-en-ventilateurs-et-respirateurs-artificiels-est-devenue-colossale-explique-un-specialiste-dans-le-materiel-medical_3849549.html|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Based in Europe, all their components are European and not relying on Chinese's supply chain.<ref name=\":3\" /> As for production ramp up, it was suggested to increase the production of home-level ventilators, more basic and which can be assembled in half an hour yet able to support patients through [[acute respiratory distress syndrome]].<ref name=\":3\" /> The current bottleneck is mainly a question of qualified human resources.<ref name=\":3\" /> In business as usual, ICU-level ventilators are to be renewed every 10 to 15 years.<ref name=\":3\" /> Due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], Germany and other European countries have started to take control over the company's supply.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn China, local manufacturers are racing to answer the demand.<ref name=scmp3076657>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/business/companies/article/3076657/chinas-factories-work-24/7-build-medical-ventilators-milan-new|title=China's factories work 24/7 to build ventilators for Milan, New York|date=24 March 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=25 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325225951/https://www.scmp.com/business/companies/article/3076657/chinas-factories-work-24/7-build-medical-ventilators-milan-new|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Medtronic]] made ventilator design specifications publicly available.<ref>{{cite news |title=Medtronic is sharing its portable ventilator design specifications and code for free to all |url=https://techcrunch.com/2020/03/30/medtronic-is-sharing-its-portable-ventilator-design-specifications-and-code-for-free-to-all/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=TechCrunch |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401182148/https://techcrunch.com/2020/03/30/medtronic-is-sharing-its-portable-ventilator-design-specifications-and-code-for-free-to-all/ |archive-date=1 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== Hackers ====\n{{See also|Open-source ventilator}}\n[[File:Open_source_ventilator-OpenLung-01-design.png|thumb|500px|The Open Source Ventilator's OpenLung project, an open source, low resource, quick deployment [[:en:mechanical ventilator|mechanical ventilator]] design uses a [[:bag valve mask|bag valve mask]] (BVM or Ambu-bag) as a core component.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gitlab.com/open-source-ventilator/OpenLung|title=Open Source Ventilator / OpenLung BVM Ventilator|website=GitLab|access-date=28 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327173607/https://gitlab.com/open-source-ventilator/OpenLung|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>]]\n3D makers have been working on various low-cost alternative ventilation devices or adaptations.\n\nAnaesthetist Dr. Alan Gauthier from [[Ontario]], Canada, turned one single-patient ventilator into a nine-patient device thanks to a 2006 YouTube video by 2 doctors from Detroit.<ref name=\":4\" /> The method uses T-shaped tubes to split airflow and multiply the number of patients provided with respiratory support.\n\nIn Ireland, volunteers started the ''Open Source Ventilator Project'' in collaboration with medical staff.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn Italy, local journalist and journal director Nunzia Vallini of the ''[[Giornale di Brescia]] (Brescia Daily)'' was informed that nearby [[Chiari, Lombardy|Chiani]] hospital was running out of valves which mix oxygen with air and are therefore a critical part of reanimation devices.<ref name=\":6\" /> The valves supplier was itself out of stock leading to patient deaths.<ref name=\":6\" /> Vallini contacted [[Fab lab|FabLab]] founder Massimo Temporelli, which invited Michele Faini, an expert in 3D print manufacturing and a research and development designer at Lonati SpA to join a 3D printing effort.<ref name=\":6\" /> When the supplier didn't wish to share the design's specifics, they reverse-engineered the valves and produced a limited not-for-profit series for local hospitals.<ref name=\":6\" /> To satisfy biomedical requirements that can withstand periodic sanitation, Lonati SpA used their SLS 3D printers to print about 100 valves in [[Nylon 12|Nylon PA12]].<ref name=\":6\" /> Faini and Temporelli still acknowledge the limitations of their production: 3D printing not being able to reach the quality and sterilised context of the original valves and manufacturing process.<ref name=\":6\" /> Contrary to rumors online, the valves don't cost {{usd|10,000}} each and the original manufacturer did not threaten to sue the 3D printers team.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nHackers of the ''Ventilator Project'' have brainstormed to propose to re-purposing [[CPAP machine]]s (sleep-apnea masks) as ventilators, hacking single ventilators to split air-flow and treat multiple patients, and using grounded airplanes as treatment facilities to leverage their one-oxygen-mask-per-seat infrastructure.<ref name=\"nyMCGuyvers\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/04/06/the-macgyvers-taking-on-the-ventilator-shortage|title=The MacGyvers Taking on the Ventilator Shortage|first=Tyler|last=Foggatt|website=The New Yorker|access-date=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327203202/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/04/06/the-macgyvers-taking-on-the-ventilator-shortage|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Engineers familiar with devices design and production, medical professionals familiar existing respiratory devices and lawyers able to navigate FDA regulations if the needs arise are key participants among the 350 volunteers involved.<ref name=\"nyMCGuyvers\" /> The central avenue of exploration is to ditch away the most advances features of modern mechanical ventilation, which includes layers of electronics and patients monitoring systems, to focus solely on assisted respiration by pressured airflow. The group is, by example, looking for an old [[Harry Diamond Labs]] \"emergency army respirator\" model to study.<ref name=\"nyMCGuyvers\" /> While hopeful they will be able to submit viable and mass-producible design, several questions linger at this later levels: mass production line, FDA approval, personnel training, personnel availability, and eventually actual needs on the battlegrounds to come.<ref name=\"nyMCGuyvers\" />\n\nAn MIT team has designed an emergency ventilator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.mit.edu/2020/ventilator-covid-deployment-open-source-low-cost-0326|title=MIT-based team works on rapid deployment of open-source, low-cost ventilator|website=MIT News|access-date=28 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328084324/http://news.mit.edu/2020/ventilator-covid-deployment-open-source-low-cost-0326|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== ECMOs ===\n[[Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation]] are devices able to replace both the lungs and the patient's heart. As of 6 February 2020, the medical community was encouraged to set up criteria for ECMO patients triage.<ref name=\"Ronco 240\u2013241\"/>\n\n== Facilities ==\nAs Wuhan's situation worsened and to assist the overwhelmed [[Central Hospital of Wuhan]] and [[Dabie Mountain Regional Medical Centre]], China built two emergency field hospital within a few days: the [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] and [[Leishenshan Hospital]]. The hospitals were progressively phased out in March 2020.<ref name=channelnewsasia12490222>{{cite web |title=Wuhan closes makeshift hospital as new COVID-19 cases in China drop sharply |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/coronavirus-wuhan-closes-makeshift-hospital-china-cases-drop-12490222 |website=CNA |accessdate=3 March 2020 |date=2 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"aisachanews\">{{cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/coronavirus-china-wuhan-hubei-makeshift-hospitals-closed-12517390 |title=China closes makeshift hospitals as COVID-19 cases plunge |website=CNA  |access-date=27 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327122456/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/coronavirus-china-wuhan-hubei-makeshift-hospitals-closed-12517390 |archive-date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, Lieutenant General [[Todd T. Semonite]], Chief of the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]], signaled an ongoing effort to lease existing facilities such as hostels, [[College dormitory|college dormitories]], and a larger hall to temporarily convert them into medical facilities.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 16 March, French President [[Emmanuel Macron]] announced a military hospital would be set up in the Grand-Est region, to provide up to 30 ICU beds.<ref name=liberation1782133>{{cite news|url=https://www.liberation.fr/france/2020/03/17/aide-de-l-armee-la-france-dans-les-bras-de-morphee_1782133|title=Aide de l'arm\u00e9e : la France dans les bras de \"Morph\u00e9e\"|date=17 March 2020|work=Lib\u00e9ration|access-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live|language=French|trans-title=Aid from the Army: France in the arms of \"Morpheus\"|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324094601/https://www.liberation.fr/france/2020/03/17/aide-de-l-armee-la-france-dans-les-bras-de-morphee_1782133|archive-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> The hospital was being tested 7 days later.<ref name=lemonde6034110>{{cite news|last=S\u00e9bastien|first=Bozon|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2020/03/23/coronavirus-voici-a-quoi-ressemble-l-hopital-militaire-installe-a-mulhouse_6034110_3244.html|title=Coronavirus : voici \u00e0 quoi ressemble l'h\u00f4pital militaire install\u00e9 \u00e0 Mulhouse|date=23 March 2020|work=Le Monde|access-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live|language=French|trans-title=Coronavirus: this is what the military hospital in Mulhouse looks like|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323203541/https://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2020/03/23/coronavirus-voici-a-quoi-ressemble-l-hopital-militaire-installe-a-mulhouse_6034110_3244.html|archive-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy 8 March, [[Lombardy]] had created 482 new I.C.U beds answers to the initial shortage.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|last=Marcolini|first=Barbara|url=https://www.nytimes.com/video/world/europe/100000007045579/coronavirus-italy-doctors-lombardy-hospitals-video.html|title='Brace Yourself': How Doctors in Italy Responded to Coronavirus|date=23 March 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live|last2=Stein|first2=Robin|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326121523/https://www.nytimes.com/video/world/europe/100000007045579/coronavirus-italy-doctors-lombardy-hospitals-video.html|archive-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> [[Lodi, Lombardy|Lodi]]'s ICU director reported that every single square metre, every single aisle of the hospital had been repurposed for severe COVID-19 patients, increasing ICU beds from 7 to 24.<ref name=\":9\" /> In [[Monza]], 3 new wards of 50 beds each were opened on 17 March.<ref name=\":9\" /> In [[Bergamo]], gastrology, internal medicine, neurology services have been repurposed.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nIn the UK almost the entire private health stock of beds was requisitioned, providing an additional 8,000 beds.<ref name=co7027196>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/policy-and-regulation/nhs-block-books-almost-all-private-hospital-sector-capacity-to-fight-covid-19/7027196.article|title=NHS block books almost all private hospital sector capacity to fight covid-19|first=James|last=Illman|website=Health Service Journal|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> Three [[NHS Nightingale Hospitals|Nightingale hospitals]] were created by [[NHS England]], with the military, to provide an additional 10\u201311,000 critical care beds, another 1,000 bed hospital created in Scotland, and a 3,000 bed hospital at the [[Principality Stadium]] in Cardiff.  Temporary wards were constructed in hospital car parks, and existing wards re-organised to free up 33,000 beds in England and 3,000 in Scotland for COVID-19 patients.<ref name=\"Look inside\"/> A hanger at [[Birmingham International Airport]] was converted into a 12,000 body mortuary.<ref name=\"Look inside\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2020/03/look-inside-london-nightingale-temporary-hospitals-coronavirus/|title=Take a look inside NHS Nightingale, London's new coronavirus hospital|website=World Economic Forum|accessdate=2 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403004905/https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2020/03/look-inside-london-nightingale-temporary-hospitals-coronavirus/|archive-date=3 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Health workers ==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\nThe factors in health worker shortage are several.  First, the excess demand due to the pandemic.  Second, the specialised nature of care of the critically ill and the time taken to train for new methods of working to prevent cross-contamination, in some cases with new types of protective equipment (PPE).  The third factor is the loss of staff to the pandemic, mostly because they are self-isolating with symptoms (which may be unrelated) or because a household member has symptoms, but also because of long term effects of the disease, or death.  This last case applies across the health system and makes it harder to draw staff from non-COVID health workers.\n\nMitigations being used include recruiting military and sports medics, final-year doctors in training, private sector staff, and re-recruiting retired staff and those who have moved from the medical sector.\n\nFor non-medical roles staff have been recruited from other sectors.\n\n=== Patients overload===\nMayor De Blasio made a call for medical staffs.<ref name=20200403com/2020/04/03/opinion/coronavirus-deblasio-nyc>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/03/opinion/coronavirus-deblasio-nyc.html|title=Opinion: We Need All Medical Workers on the Front Lines|first=Bill|last=de Blasio|date=3 April 2020|work=The New York Times}}</ref>{{explain|date=March 2020}}\n\n=== Isolation and trauma ===\n{{See also|Mental health during the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n====China====\nAs for China, medical staff are self isolating from families and under high emotional pressure.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nPsychological trauma is expected among medical professionals.<ref name=\"nytSick0329\">{{cite news |author=Jennifer Senior |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/29/opinion/coronavirus-ventilators-rationing-triage.html |title=Opinion &#124; Doctors Must Ration Ventilators as Coronavirus Rages. The Decisions Are Painful. |work=The New York Times |date=n.d.|accessdate=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330133854/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/29/opinion/coronavirus-ventilators-rationing-triage.html |archive-date=30 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{clarify|date=March 2020}}\n\n=== Sickness and death ===\nAt least 50 Chinese doctors died.<ref name=20200324com/2020/03/30/nyregion/ny-coronavirus-doctors-sick>{{cite news |author=Michael Schwirtz |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/nyregion/ny-coronavirus-doctors-sick.html |title=Nurses Die, Doctors Fall Sick and Panic Rises on Virus Front Lines|work=The New York Times |date=24 March 2020 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330101607/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/nyregion/ny-coronavirus-doctors-sick.html |archive-date=30 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn [[Lombardy]], Italy, with the mid-March 2020 outbreak, medical staff reported high level of sick staff.<ref name=\":9\" /> In Lodi, doctors from other services have been called to attend Covid patients.<ref name=\":9\" /> In [[Cremona]], the number of patients entries was three times the usual while services were running with 50% of their staff.<ref name=\":9\" /> On 12 March 8% of Italy's 13,382 cases were health workers.<ref name=\":9\" /> It was also reported that between 5 and 10% of deaths were medical staff.<ref name=\":9\" /> On 17 March, one of the largest hospital of the [[Bergamo]] region ran out of [[Intensive care unit|ICU beds]], patients were flown to other regions by helicopter.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nAbout 14% of Spanish cases are medical staff.<ref name=\"nytSick0329\" />\n\n== Groceries ==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:2020-03-14 Desabastiment a Consum Rafelbunyol per compra compulsiva pel COVID-19 02.jpg|thumb|Almost empty shelves in a [[Consum supermarkets|Consum]] supermarket on 14 March, though plenty of produce can be seen in the next bay an in the background.]]\nSome daily goods have seen shortages, mainly due to [[panic buying]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n<!-- Vitamin C also if citation can be found -->\n\n===Soap===\n\n\n===Hand sanitiser===\n\n\n===Toilet paper===\n\n\n===Paracetemol===\n\n\n===Pasta===\n\n\n===Condoms===\nThe shortage of condoms is possible.<ref name=20200327theguardian2>{{cite web |author=Reuters in Kuala Lumpur |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/27/global-condom-shortage-coronavirus-shuts-down-production |title=Global condom shortage looms as coronavirus shuts down production  |work=The Guardian |date=n.d.|accessdate=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327180211/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/27/global-condom-shortage-coronavirus-shuts-down-production |archive-date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Others ==\nIn France, due to closed borders and the impossibility for foreign seasonal worker to come over,<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bfmtv.com/economie/coronavirus-la-cueillette-des-fraises-menacee-par-le-manque-de-main-d-oeuvre-et-de-debouches-1881783.html|title=Coronavirus: la cueillette des fraises menac\u00e9e par le manque de main d'oeuvre et de d\u00e9bouch\u00e9s|last=BFMTV|publisher=BFMTV|language=fr|access-date=26 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326150948/https://www.bfmtv.com/economie/coronavirus-la-cueillette-des-fraises-menacee-par-le-manque-de-main-d-oeuvre-et-de-debouches-1881783.html|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the government's [[Didier Guillaume|Minister of Agriculture]] called for jobless volunteers to contact [[Strawberry|strawberries farms]] and help collect the harvest for the usual [[Minimum wage|minimal wage]].<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nLaboratory mice are being culled, and some strains are at risk of shortage due to lockdowns.<ref name=20200323sciencemag>{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/it-s-heartbreaking-labs-are-euthanizing-thousands-mice-response-coronavirus-pandemic|title='It's heartbreaking.' Labs are euthanizing thousands of mice in response to coronavirus pandemic|last=Grimm |first=David|date=23 March 2020|website=Science {{!}} AAAS|access-date=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328234927/https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/it-s-heartbreaking-labs-are-euthanizing-thousands-mice-response-coronavirus-pandemic|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{annotated link|Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation}}\n* {{annotated link|List of countries by hospital beds}}\n* {{annotated link|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{clear}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|data}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Socio-economic impact of the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Shortages]]\n[[Category:2020 in international relations]]\n[[Category:Market (economics)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Medical material and other goods shortages that are a major issue}}\n<!-- {{multiple issues|{{short description|Impact of COVID-19}}\n}} -->\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Current COVID|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Clinicians in Intensive Care Unit.jpg|thumb|400px|upright=1.4|A patient and clinicians in an [[intensive care unit]]. In the context of the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], an ICU bed is a [[hospital bed]] equipped with [[mechanical ventilation]]. A lack of mechanical ventilation increases the probability that a COVID-19 patient will die.]]\n'''Medical material and other goods shortages caused by the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]''' are a major issue of the ongoing [[pandemic]]. The matter of pandemic-related shortage has been studied in the past and has been documented in recent events. On the medical side, shortages of [[personal protective equipment]] such as [[Surgical mask|medical masks]], [[Medical glove|gloves]], [[face shield]]s, gear,<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|last=Tiefenth\u00e4ler|first=Ainara|url=https://www.nytimes.com/video/world/europe/100000007051789/coronavirus-ppe-shortage-health-care-workers.html|title='Health Care Kamikazes': How Spain's Workers Are Battling Coronavirus, Unprotected|work=The New York Times|access-date=31 March 2020|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331010547/https://www.nytimes.com/video/world/europe/100000007051789/coronavirus-ppe-shortage-health-care-workers.html|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Sanitizer|sanitizing products]], is also joined by potential shortage of more advanced devices such as [[hospital bed]]s, [[Intensive care unit|ICU beds]], [[oxygen therapy]], [[mechanical ventilation]]<nowiki/>s and [[Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation|ECMO]] devices. Human resources, especially in term of medical staff, may be drained by the overwhelming extent of the epidemic and associated workload, together with losses by contamination, isolation, sickness<ref name=\":14\" /> or mortality among health care workers. While preparing for the Epidemic apex, New York governor [[Andrew Cuomo]], cited as main components for [[Health system|health care system]] to support the apex load to be [[Intensive care unit|ICU]] [[Hospital bed]]s, supplies ([[Personal protective equipment|PPE]]) and equipment, together with relevant-skills [[Health professional|health care workers]], whom are at risk from the virus but also to physical and emotional exhaustion.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AC360/status/1245891038864121862|title=New York Gov. Andrew Cuomo: \"This state had purchased 17,000 ventilators, more than any other state in the nation, and they never got delivered. Because they were all coming from China, and 50 states are competing. ... We can't get any more.\" #CNNTownHall <nowiki>https://cnn.it/2R42aQn\u00a0pic.twitter.com/vFrbIaqMKJ</nowiki>|last=Cooper 360\u00b0|first=Anderson|date=2 April 2020|website=@AC360|access-date=3 April 2020}}{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}</ref> Territories are differently equipped to face the pandemic. Various emergency measures have been taken to ramp up equipment levels such as purchases, while calls for donations, local 3D makers,<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=20200331com/2020/03/31/science/coronavirus-masks-equipment-crowdsource>{{Cite news|last=Petri|first=Alexandra E.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/science/coronavirus-masks-equipment-crowdsource.html|title=D.I.Y. Coronavirus Solutions Are Gaining Steam|date=31 March 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=31 March 2020|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331141002/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/science/coronavirus-masks-equipment-crowdsource.html|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> volunteer staffing, mandatory draft or seizure of stocks and factory lines have also occurred. Inter-countries and inter-States bidding wars over these items are reported to be a major issue<ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":17\" />, with price increase<ref name=\":16\" />, orders seized by local government or cancelled by selling company to be redirected to higher bidder<ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":17\" />. In some cases, medical workers have been ordered to not speak about these resources shortages.<ref name=co9433171>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-nhs-uk-doctors-gagged-england-a9433171.html|title=Doctors claim they have been gagged over protective equipment shortages|date=30 March 2020|website=The Independent|access-date=31 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331050400/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-nhs-uk-doctors-gagged-england-a9433171.html|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Tests==\nTesting shortage is a key element preventing authorities from measuring the true extend of current epidemic spread.<ref name=20200402com/2020/04/02/us/politics/cia-coronavirus-china>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/02/us/politics/cia-coronavirus-china.html|title=C.I.A. Hunts for Authentic Virus Totals in China, Dismissing Government Tallies|first=Julian E.|last=Barnes|date=2 April 2020|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n===Diagnostic tests===\n\n====Reagents====\nIn Ireland and the UK, in late March and early April, reagent shortages limited the number of tests.<ref name=20200401reuters>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-ireland-reagent-idUSL8N2BP2DQ|title=Ireland says reagent shortage to slow COVID-19 tests rollout for 7\u201310 days|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref> By March, insufficient amounts of [[reagent]] has become a [[Bottleneck (production)|bottleneck]] for mass testing in the EU and UK<ref name=20200325eu/sites/default/files/documents/RRA-seventh-update-Outbreak-of-coronavirus-disease-COVID-19>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) pandemic: increased transmission in the EU/EEA and the UK \u2013seventh update |url=https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/sites/default/files/documents/RRA-seventh-update-Outbreak-of-coronavirus-disease-COVID-19.pdf |publisher=[[European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control]] |accessdate=29 March 2020 |pages=15\u201316 |date=25 March 2020 |quote=the current shortages of laboratory consumables and reagents affect diagnostic capacity and hamper the epidemic response at the national and local levels. The laboratories have experienced delayed or missing deliveries of swabbing material, plastic consumables, RNA extraction and RT-PCR reagents, and PPE. This is affecting laboratories in all EU/EEA countries. |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326192834/https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/sites/default/files/documents/RRA-seventh-update-Outbreak-of-coronavirus-disease-COVID-19.pdf |archive-date=26 March 2020 }}</ref> and the US.<ref name=20200324newyorker>{{cite web |last1=Baird |first1=Robert P. |title=Why Widespread Coronavirus Testing Isn't Coming Anytime Soon |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/why-widespread-coronavirus-testing-isnt-coming-anytime-soon |website=[[The New Yorker]] |accessdate=29 March 2020 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200328133105/https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/why-widespread-coronavirus-testing-isnt-coming-anytime-soon |archivedate=28 March 2020  |date=24 March 2020 |quote=South Dakota, said that her state\u2019s public-health laboratory\u2014the only lab doing COVID-19 testing in the state\u2014had so much trouble securing reagents that it was forced to temporarily stop testing altogether. also noted critical shortages of extraction kits, reagents, and test kits |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=qz1822596>{{cite web |last1=Ossola |first1=Alexandra |title=Here are the coronavirus testing materials that are in short supply in the US |url=https://qz.com/1822596/all-the-coronavirus-test-materials-in-short-supply-in-the-us/ |website=Quartz |accessdate=29 March 2020 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200326174135/https://qz.com/1822596/all-the-coronavirus-test-materials-in-short-supply-in-the-us/ |archivedate=26 March 2020  |date=25 March 2020 |quote=extract the virus\u2019s genetic material\u2014in this case, RNA\u2014using a set of chemicals that usually come in pre-assembled kits. \u201cThe big shortage is extraction kits\u201d There are no easy replacements here: \u201cThese reagents that are used in extraction are fairly complex chemicals. They have to be very pure, and they have to be in pure solution\u201d |url-status=live}}</ref> This has led some authors to explore sample preparation protocols that involve heating samples at {{cvt|98|C|F}} for 5 minutes to release [[RNA genome]]s for further testing.<ref name=ssi-boil>{{cite web |last1=Fomsgaard |first1=Anders |title=Statens Serum Institut (SSI) solves essential COVID-19 testing deficiency problem |url=https://en.ssi.dk/news/news/2020/03-ssi--solves-essential-covid19-testing-deficiency-problem |website=en.ssi.dk |publisher=[[Statens Serum Institut]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200329085152/https://en.ssi.dk/news/news/2020/03-ssi--solves-essential-covid19-testing-deficiency-problem |archivedate=29 March 2020  |date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live |quote=several countries are in lack of the chemical reagents necessary to test their citizens for the disease. }}</ref><ref name=cphpost112522>{{cite web |title=Danish researchers behind simple&nbsp;coronavirus test method |work=[[The Copenhagen Post]]|url=http://cphpost.dk/?p=112522 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328130357/http://cphpost.dk/?p=112522 |archivedate=28 March 2020 |date=28 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn UK, on 1 April the government confirmed that a total of 2,000 NHS staff had been tested for coronavirus since the outbreak began, but Cabinet Office Minister Michael Gove said a shortage of chemicals needed for the test meant it was not possible to screen the NHS's 1.2&nbsp;million workforce.<ref name=\"BBC52122761\"/> Gove's statement was contradicted by the [[Chemical Industries Association]], which said there was not a shortage of the relevant chemicals and that at a meeting with a business minister the week before the government had not tried to find out about potential supply problems.<ref name=20200331itv>{{cite news |last1=Preston |first1=Robert |authorlink1=Robert Peston |title=Robert Peston: Is Michael Gove right that there is a shortage of coronavirus test kit ingredients? |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-31/robert-peston-is-gove-right-that-there-is-a-shortage-of-test-kit-ingredients/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[ITV News]] |date=31 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401160117/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-31/robert-peston-is-gove-right-that-there-is-a-shortage-of-test-kit-ingredients/ |archivedate=1 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====Swabs====\nA feared shortage of swabs in [[Iceland]] was averted when stocks were found to bridge the gap until more arrived from China.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.icelandreview.com/news/plenty-of-swabs-for-covid-19-testing/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=3 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331023517/https://www.icelandreview.com/news/plenty-of-swabs-for-covid-19-testing/ |archive-date=31 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Shortages arose in the US, though one manufacturer increased production to 1 million swabs per day.<ref name=npr825499508>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/01/825499508/one-of-the-few-manufacturers-of-the-special-swab-for-coronavirus-tests-speaks|title=Swab Manufacturer Works To Meet 'Overwhelming' Demand|publisher=NPR}}</ref> Shortages also arose in the UK, but were resolve by 2 April.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2020-04-02/uk-has-fixed-swab-shortage-problem-for-coronavirus-testing-minister-says</ref>\n\n===Antibody tests===\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Personal protective equipment ==\nMasks, gloves, closes, and sanitising products have been in shortage. A survey of medical personnel pointed out at the lack of proper equipment as the main issue in their current efforts, with 90% claiming they went to work without the proper equipment.<ref name=20200325com/2020/03/25/business/media/coronavirus-nurses-stories-anonymous>{{Cite news|last=Lee|first=Edmund|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/business/media/coronavirus-nurses-stories-anonymous.html|title=Nurses Share Coronavirus Stories Anonymously in an Online Document|date=25 March 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=25 March 2020|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325205951/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/business/media/coronavirus-nurses-stories-anonymous.html|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGiven that the global supply of [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE) is insufficient, the [[World Health Organization]] recommends minimising the need for PPE through [[telemedicine]], physical barriers such as clear windows, allowing only those involved in direct care to enter a room with a COVID-19 patient, using only the PPE necessary for the specific task, continuing use of the same respirator without removing it while caring for multiple patients with the same diagnosis, monitoring and coordinating the PPE supply chain, and discouraging the use of masks for asymptomatic individuals.<ref name=\":32\">{{cite web|url=https://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/331215/WHO-2019-nCov-IPCPPE_use-2020.1-eng.pdf|title=Rational use of personal protective equipment for coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19)|date=27 February 2020|website=World Health Organization|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303000654/https://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/331215/WHO-2019-nCov-IPCPPE_use-2020.1-eng.pdf|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Sanitising products ===\n[[Hand sanitizer|Hand sanitiser]] was largely out of stocks in many areas, causing price gouging.<ref name=20200316com/2020/03/16/learning/is-it-immoral-to-increase-the-price-of-goods-during-a-crisis>{{Cite news|last=Doyne|first=Shannon|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/learning/is-it-immoral-to-increase-the-price-of-goods-during-a-crisis.html|title=Is It Immoral to Increase the Price of Goods During a Crisis?|date=16 March 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=26 March 2020|last2=Gonchar|first2=Michael|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326130830/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/learning/is-it-immoral-to-increase-the-price-of-goods-during-a-crisis.html|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Protective gear ===\nIn the United States, some nurses at one New York City hospital have been reported as wearing garbage bags as an alternative to unavailable protective clothing.<ref name=20200325nypost>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/25/worker-at-nyc-hospital-where-nurses-wear-trash-bags-as-protection-dies-from-coronavirus/|title=Worker at NYC hospital where nurses wear trash bags as protection dies from coronavirus|last=Bowden|first=Ebony|last2=Campanile|first2=Carl|date=25 March 2020|website=New York Post|access-date=26 March 2020|last3=Golding|first3=Bruce|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326131114/https://nypost.com/2020/03/25/worker-at-nyc-hospital-where-nurses-wear-trash-bags-as-protection-dies-from-coronavirus/|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Facial masks ===\n==== Early epidemic in China ====\n[[File:Citizens of Wuhan lining up outside of a drug store to buy masks during the Wuhan coronavirus outbreak.jpg|thumb|People in Wuhan lining up in front of a drug store to buy [[surgical masks]]]]\n[[File:Surgical mask and 84 disinfectant liquid purchase limit notice at a CSF Market (20200202155633).jpg|thumb|A notice at a supermarket in Beijing, which says each person can only buy one pack of surgical masks and one bottle of 84 disinfectant liquid a day]]\n\nAs the epidemic accelerated, the mainland market saw a shortage of [[Surgical mask|face masks]] due to the increased need from the public.<ref name=sohu161795>{{cite news|author=\u8c22\u658c \u5f20\u7eaf|url=http://www.sohu.com/a/368299105_161795|title=\u4e00\u7f69\u96be\u6c42\uff1a\u5357\u90fd\u6c11\u8c03\u5b9e\u6d4b\u8d70\u8bbf\u53d1\u73b0\uff0c\u7ebf\u4e0a\u7ebf\u4e0b\u53e3\u7f69\u57fa\u672c\u5356\u8131\u9500|date=21 January 2020|accessdate=21 January 2020|agency=\u5357\u65b9\u90fd\u5e02\u62a5}}</ref> It was reported that Shanghai customers had to queue for nearly an hour to buy a pack of face masks which was sold out in another half an hour.<ref name=udn4304194>{{cite news|author1=\u5f90\u6986\u6db5|url=https://money.udn.com/money/story/5648/4304194|title=\u5168\u7403\u5404\u5730\u760b\u6436\u53e3\u7f69 \u5c08\u5bb6\uff1a\u4e0d\u5fc5\u8cb7N95|date=23 January 2020|accessdate=25 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125103023/https://money.udn.com/money/story/5648/4304194|archive-date=25 January 2020|publisher=\u806f\u5408\u5831|url-status=live}}</ref> Some stores are hoarding, driving up prices and other acts, so the market regulator said it will crack down on such acts.<ref name=southcn190111854>{{cite news|author=\u5218\u704f|url=http://economy.southcn.com/e/2020-01/21/content_190111854.htm|title=\u5e7f\u4e1c\u5e02\u573a\u76d1\u7ba1\u90e8\u95e8\uff1a\u5c06\u575a\u51b3\u6253\u51fb\u56e4\u79ef\u5c45\u5947\u3001\u54c4\u62ac\u4ef7\u683c\u7b49\u884c\u4e3a|date=21 January 2020|accessdate=21 January 2020|agency=\u5357\u65b9\u7f51}}</ref><ref name=gov1620613>{{cite web|url=http://scjgj.beijing.gov.cn/zwxx/ttgg/202001/t20200122_1620613.html|title=\u5e02\u573a\u4ef7\u683c\u884c\u4e3a\u63d0\u9192\u4e66|date=n.d.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127080911/http://scjgj.beijing.gov.cn/zwxx/ttgg/202001/t20200122_1620613.html|archive-date=27 January 2020|accessdate=|url-status=live}}</ref> The shortage will not be relieved until late February when most workers return from the New Year vacation according to Lei Limin, an expert in the industry.<ref name=chinanews9074410>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinanews.com/sh/2020/01-31/9074410.shtml|title=\u4e13\u5bb6\uff1a\u53e3\u7f69\u77ed\u7f3a2\u6708\u5e95\u6216\u7f13\u89e3|last=Liu|first=Yuying|date=31 January 2020|website=\u4e2d\u65b0\u7f51|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202154104/http://www.chinanews.com/sh/2020/01-31/9074410.shtml|archive-date=2 February 2020|access-date=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 January 2020, [[Taobao]], China's largest e-commerce platform owned by [[Alibaba Group]], said that all face masks on [[Taobao]] and [[Tmall]] would not be allowed to increase in price. Special subsidies would be provided to the retailers. Also, Alibaba Health's \"urgent drug delivery\" service would not be closed during the Spring Festival.<ref name=ycwb30486944>{{cite news|author=\u9648\u6cfd\u4e91|url=http://news.ycwb.com/2020-01/22/content_30486944.htm|title=\u53e3\u7f69\u4e70\u4e0d\u5230\u600e\u4e48\u529e\uff1f\u8fd9\u4e9b\u836f\u5e97\u5e73\u53f0\u6625\u8282\u671f\u95f4\u6301\u7eed\u4f9b\u5e94|date=22 January 2020|accessdate=22 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122102833/http://news.ycwb.com/2020-01/22/content_30486944.htm|archive-date=22 January 2020|agency=\u91d1\u7f8a\u7f51|url-status=live}}</ref> [[JD.com|JD]], another leading Chinese e-commerce platform, said, \"We are actively working to ensure supply and price stability from sources, storage and distribution, platform control and so on\" and \"while fully ensuring price stability for JD's own commodities, JD.com has also exercised strict control over the commodities on JD's platform. Third-party vendors selling face masks are prohibited from raising prices. Once it is confirmed that the prices of third-party vendors have increased abnormally, JD will immediately remove the offending commodities from shelves and deal with the offending vendors accordingly.\"<ref name=bjnews677805>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjnews.com.cn/finance/2020/01/22/677805.html|title=\u4eac\u4e1c\uff1a\u7981\u6b62\u7b2c\u4e09\u65b9\u5546\u5bb6\u53e3\u7f69\u6da8\u4ef7|author=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5|date=22 January 2020|website=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127082917/http://www.bjnews.com.cn/finance/2020/01/22/677805.html|archive-date=27 January 2020|access-date=22 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Other major e-commerce platforms including Sunning.com and [[Pinduoduo]] also promised to keep the prices of health products stable.<ref name=bjnews677744>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjnews.com.cn/finance/2020/01/22/677744.html|title=\u62fc\u591a\u591a\uff1a\u5bf9\u53e3\u7f69\u7b49\u4ea7\u54c1\u8fdb\u884c\u76d1\u6d4b\uff0c\u6076\u610f\u6da8\u4ef7\u8005\u5c06\u4e0b\u67b6|author=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5|date=22 January 2020|website=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122023043/http://www.bjnews.com.cn/finance/2020/01/22/677744.html|archive-date=22 January 2020|access-date=22 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=bjnews677740>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjnews.com.cn/finance/2020/01/22/677740.html|title=\u82cf\u5b81\u6613\u8d2d\uff1a\u53e3\u7f69\u7b49\u5065\u5eb7\u7c7b\u5546\u54c1\u7981\u6da8\u4ef7\uff0c\u5e76\u5f00\u5c55\u767e\u4ebf\u8865\u8d34|author=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5|date=22 January 2020|website=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122023040/http://www.bjnews.com.cn/finance/2020/01/22/677740.html|archive-date=22 January 2020|access-date=22 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFigures from China Customs show that some 2.46&nbsp;billion pieces of epidemic prevention and control materials had been imported between 24 January and 29 February, including 2.02&nbsp;billion masks and 25.38&nbsp;million items of protective clothing valued at 8.2&nbsp;billion yuan ($1&nbsp;billion). Press reported that the [[China Poly Group]], together with other Chinese companies and state-owned enterprises, had an important role in scouring markets abroad to procure essential medical supplies and equipment for China.<ref name=smh20200402>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/billions-of-face-masks-sent-to-china-during-australian-bushfire-crisis-20200402-p54gjh.html|title=Billions of face masks sent to China during bushfire crisis|first=Kate McClymont, Royce|last=Millar|date=2 April 2020|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> [[Risland]] (formerly Country Garden)  sourced 82 tonnes of supplies, which were subsequently airlifted to Wuhan.<ref name=20200326smh>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/second-developer-flies-82-tonnes-of-medical-supplies-to-china-20200326-p54e8n.html  |title=Second developer flew 82 tonnes of medical supplies to China |author=McClymont, Kate|date=27 March 2020|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Rest of the world ====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"float:right; font-size:0.9em;\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"7\" | Can facial masks be disinfected for re-use?<ref name=\":7\" />\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Cleaning method\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" | Meltblown fiber filtration media\n! colspan=\"2\" | Static-charged cotton\n! rowspan=\"2\" | ''E. Coli.''\nDisinfection\n|-\n!Min.\n!Filtration (%)\n!Pressure drop (Pa)\n!Filtration (%)\n!Pressure drop (Pa)\n|-\n|Masks before treatment\n|(null)\n|style=\"background:#60ff60aa;\"| 96.76\n|style=\"background:#60ff60aa;\"| 8.33\n|style=\"background:#60ff60aa;\"| 78.01\n|style=\"background:#60ff60aa;\"| 5.33\n|style=\"background:#60ff60aa;\"| (no E.Coli.)\n|-\n|70&nbsp;\u00b0C hot air in oven\n|30\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 96.60\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 8.00\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 70.16\n|4.67\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| >99%\n|-\n|Ultraviolet light\n|30\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 95.50\n|7.00\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 77.72\n|6.00\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| >99%\n|-\n| 5% alcohol soaking, drying\n|n.a.\n|style=\"background:#ff606088;\"| 56.33\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 7.67\n|style=\"background:#ff606088;\"| 29.24\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 5.33\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| >99%\n|-\n|Chlorine-based\n|5\n|style=\"background:#ff606088;\"| 73.11\n|9.00\n|style=\"background:#ff606088;\"| 57.33\n|7.00\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| >99%\n|-\n|Vapor from boiling water\n|10\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 94.74\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 8.00\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| 77.65\n|7.00\n|style=\"background:#60ff6088;\"| >99%\n|}\n\nShortage in single-use medical mask and field reports of reuse lead to the question of which process could properly sanitise these PPE without altering their filtering capacity.<ref name=\":7\" /> In 2006, 156 million masks were added to the US [[Strategic National Stockpile]] in prevision of a flu pandemic.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|last=Manjoo|first=Farhad|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/opinion/coronavirus-face-mask.html|title=Opinion {{!}} How the World's Richest Country Ran Out of a 75-Cent Face Mask|date=25 March 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=25 March 2020|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325205952/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/opinion/coronavirus-face-mask.html|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> After they were used against the [[2009 flu pandemic]], neither the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] nor the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump administration]] renewed the stocks.<ref name=\":8\"/>\n\n[[FFP2]] masks can be sanitised by 70&nbsp;\u00b0C vapor allowing reuses.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://stanfordmedicine.app.box.com/v/covid19-PPE-1-1|title=Addressing COVID-19 Face Mask Shortages [v1.1] : Can Facial Masks be Disinfected for Re-use?|last1=Price|first1=Amy|last2=Chu|first2=Larry|date=22 March 2020|website=stanfordmedicine.app.box.com|publisher=[[Stanford University]] Anesthesia Informatics and Media Lab, [[COVID-19]] Evidence Service Report|page=5|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323234628/https://stanfordmedicine.app.box.com/v/covid19-PPE-1-1|archive-date=23 March 2020|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> Use of alcohol is discouraged since it alters [[N95 mask]] microfibers' static charge which helps filtration.<ref name=\":7\" /> Chlorine is also discouraged since its fumes may be harmful.<ref name=\":7\" /> Authors are warning against reuses by non-professionals, pointing out that even the best scored methods can degrade the mask if not performed properly.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=sciencesetavenir142836>{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencesetavenir.fr/sante/covid-19-des-medecins-decontaminent-leur-masque-ffp2-en-les-passant-au-four_142836|title=Covid-19: des chercheurs tentent de d\u00e9contaminer les masques \u2013 Sciences et Avenir|date=27 March 2020|website=sciencesetavenir.fr|language=fr|access-date=28 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328045554/https://www.sciencesetavenir.fr/sante/covid-19-des-medecins-decontaminent-leur-masque-ffp2-en-les-passant-au-four_142836|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing [[N95 masks]] shortages, volunteers created 3D printed \"NanoHack\" alternative.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/societe/coronavirus-quand-les-inventeurs-viennent-a-la-rescousse-des-hopitaux-23-03-2020-8286186.php|title=Coronavirus : quand les inventeurs viennent \u00e0 la rescousse des h\u00f4pitaux|last=Opoczynski|first=David|date=23 March 2020|website=Le Parisien|language=fr-FR|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324220615/http://www.leparisien.fr/societe/coronavirus-quand-les-inventeurs-viennent-a-la-rescousse-des-hopitaux-23-03-2020-8286186.php|archive-date=24 March 2020|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> This printed mask allows to use hand-cut [[surgical mask]] as fine-particle filters.<ref name=\":4\" /> Vacuum bags can be sewn into masks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/kevin-drum/2020/03/how-to-make-a-homemade-mask-if-you-absolutely-have-to/|title=How to make a homemade mask if you absolutely have to|last=Drum|first=Kevin|website=Mother Jones|access-date=26 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326004750/https://www.motherjones.com/kevin-drum/2020/03/how-to-make-a-homemade-mask-if-you-absolutely-have-to/|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA Singaporean study found no contamination on mask after brief care to COVID19 patients, suggesting masks could be reuse for multiple patients cares.<ref name=cambridge900526>{{cite journal |author=Institution login |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/infection-control-and-hospital-epidemiology/article/absence-of-contamination-of-personal-protective-equipment-ppe-by-severe-acute-respiratory-syndrome-coronavirus-2-sarscov2/EA37207FECDD23BE900526CEE5BA9430 |title=Absence of contamination of personal protective equipment (PPE) by Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) &#124; Infection Control & Hospital Epidemiology &#124; Cambridge Core |journal=Infection Control & Hospital Epidemiology |doi=10.1017/ice.2020.91 |publisher=Cambridge.org |date=26 March 2020 |pages=1\u20136 |pmid=32213231 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328233703/https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/infection-control-and-hospital-epidemiology/article/absence-of-contamination-of-personal-protective-equipment-ppe-by-severe-acute-respiratory-syndrome-coronavirus-2-sarscov2/EA37207FECDD23BE900526CEE5BA9430 |archive-date=28 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April, US's [[Strategic National Stockpile]] was nearly emptied.<ref name=washingtonpost7148009252>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/coronavirus-protective-gear-stockpile-depleted/2020/04/01/44d6592a-741f-11ea-ae50-7148009252e3_story.html|title=Protective gear in national stockpile is nearly depleted, DHS officials say|last=enforcement|first=Nick Miroff closeNick MiroffReporter covering immigration|last2=Homel|first2=the Department of|website=The Washington Post|access-date=1 April 2020|last3=SecurityEmailEmailBioBioFollowFollow|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401225900/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/coronavirus-protective-gear-stockpile-depleted/2020/04/01/44d6592a-741f-11ea-ae50-7148009252e3_story.html|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>{{clarify|date=April 2020}} French regional representative complained that the United States, in their aggressive search for stocks, had been making tarmac bids for stocks of masks ordered, paying 3 times the price.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfmtv.com/mediaplayer/video/valerie-pecresse-sur-les-masques-nous-avons-ete-confrontes-a-cette-situation-ou-des-americains-ont-surencheri-1235950.html|title=Val\u00e9rie P\u00e9cresse sur les masques: \u00ab Des Am\u00e9ricains ont surench\u00e9ri \u00bb|via=bfmtv.com}}</ref>\n\nIn late-March/early-April 2020, as Western countries were in turn dependent on China for supplies of masks and other equipment, China was seen as making soft-power play to influence world opinion.<ref name=bbc52092395/><ref name=20200402businessinsider/> However, some of the supplies sent to Spain, Turkey and the Netherlands was reportedly rejected as being sub-standard. Dutch health ministry issued a recall of 600,000 face masks from a Chinese supplier on 21 March did not fit properly and whose filters did not work as intended despite them having a quality certificate;<ref name=bbc52092395>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-52092395|title=Countries reject Chinese-made equipment|date=30 March 2020|via=bbc.com}}</ref><ref name=\"20200402businessinsider\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.fr/us/china-face-mask-defective-double-check-instructions-2020-4|title=Chinese government rejects allegations that its face masks were defective, tells countries to 'double check' instructions|first=David|last=Choi|date=2 April 2020|website=Business Insider France}}</ref><ref name=\"20200402businessinsider\"/> The Spanish government alleged that 60,000 out of 340,000 test kits from a Chinese manufacturer did not accurately test for COVID-19.<ref name=20200402businessinsider/> The Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs responded that the customer should \"double-check the instructions to make sure that you ordered, paid for and distributed the right ones. Do not use non-surgical masks for surgical purposes\".<ref name=20200402businessinsider/>\n\n====Do it yourself masks====\nGiven the scarecity of masks and ambiguity on their efficiency, individuals and volunteers have started to produce masks for themselves or for others.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite news|last=Sindya|first=Bhanoo|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/wellness/masks-diy-coronavirus/2020/04/01/20830f5e-7420-11ea-85cb-8670579b863d_story.html|title=Which DIY mask pattern should you use? Even experts can't pick one to recommend.|date=1 April 2020|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401220027/https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/wellness/masks-diy-coronavirus/2020/04/01/20830f5e-7420-11ea-85cb-8670579b863d_story.html|archive-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> Various designs are shared online to ease creation.<ref name=\":15\" />{{Explain|reason=|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== Medical face shield ===\n[[File:Visor frame v10.stl|thumb|right|A 3d printable face shield frame.]]\nReacting to shortage of face shield, volunteers from the [[Maker culture|maker community]] with [[3D printing]] abilities initiated an effort to produce face-shields for hospitals' staff.<ref name=\":4\" /> On 24 March, while the epidemic was expanding, popular French 3D maker and YouTuber Heliox announced her willingness to produce face-shields for free building upon another maker's design.<ref name=\":13\">{{cite web|url=https://www.lci.fr/high-tech/l-imprimante-3d-au-secours-des-hopitaux-pour-lutter-contre-le-coronavirus-2149112.html|title=L'imprimante 3D au secours des h\u00f4pitaux pour lutter contre le coronavirus|website=LCI|language=fr|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329153244/https://www.lci.fr/high-tech/l-imprimante-3d-au-secours-des-hopitaux-pour-lutter-contre-le-coronavirus-2149112.html|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She was quickly contacted by local hospitals, health centres and other medical professionals asking for rapid delivery of face shield.<ref name=\":13\" /> The visible popularity of her initiative caused other 3D makers to join the effort and offer their help in other regions to connect health facilities with nearby makers.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nOn 30 March, the [[The New York Times]] published a video on COVID-19-related shortages and healthcare workers' DIY solutions.<ref name=\":14\" />{{Clarify|reason=|date=March 2020}}\n\n'''3D printed [[Face shield#Medical|medical face shield]] created in response to COVID19's medical shortage'''\n<gallery>\nFile:3D-printed visor-Heliox Lab-01.jpg\nFile:3D-printed visor-Heliox Lab-02.jpg\nFile:3D-printed visor-Heliox Lab-03.jpg\nFile:3D-printed visor-Heliox Lab-04.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n== Medical care devices ==\nThe availability of critical care beds or ICU beds,<ref name=20200316theguardian>{{cite news|last=Srivastava|first=Ranjana|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/mar/17/now-more-than-ever-we-have-to-be-honest-about-intensive-care-beds|title=Now more than ever, we have to be honest about intensive care beds|date=16 March 2020|work=The Guardian|accessdate=17 March 2020|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323151959/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/mar/17/now-more-than-ever-we-have-to-be-honest-about-intensive-care-beds|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[mechanical ventilation]]<ref name=20200318com/2020/03/18/business/ventilator-shortage-coronavirus>{{Cite news|last=Kliff|first=Sarah|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/business/ventilator-shortage-coronavirus.html|title=There Aren't Enough Ventilators to Cope With the Coronavirus|date=18 March 2020|work=The New York Times|accessdate=18 March 2020|last2=Satariano|first2=Adam|issn=0362-4331|last3=Silver-Greenberg|first3=Jessica|last4=Kulish|first4=Nicholas|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318190318/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/business/ventilator-shortage-coronavirus.html|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Daugherty Biddison 848\u2013854\">{{Cite journal|last=Daugherty Biddison|first=E. Lee|last2=Faden|first2=Ruth|last3=Gwon|first3=Howard S.|last4=Mareiniss|first4=Darren P.|last5=Regenberg|first5=Alan C.|last6=Schoch-Spana|first6=Monica|last7=Schwartz|first7=Jack|last8=Toner|first8=Eric S.|date=1 April 2019|title=Too Many Patients\u2026A Framework to Guide Statewide Allocation of Scarce Mechanical Ventilation During Disasters|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0012369218325650|journal=Chest|volume=155|issue=4|pages=848\u2013854|doi=10.1016/j.chest.2018.09.025|pmid=30316913|issn=0012-3692}}</ref> and [[Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation|ECMO]] devices<ref name=\"Ronco 240\u2013241\">{{Cite journal|last=Ronco|first=Claudio|last2=Navalesi|first2=Paolo|last3=Vincent|first3=Jean Louis|date=1 March 2020|title=Coronavirus epidemic: preparing for extracorporeal organ support in intensive care|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lanres/article/PIIS2213-2600(20)30060-6/abstract|journal=The Lancet Respiratory Medicine|volume=8|issue=3|pages=240\u2013241|doi=10.1016/S2213-2600(20)30060-6|issn=2213-2600|pmid=32035509}}</ref> generally closely associated with [[List of countries by hospital beds|hospital beds]] has been described as a critical bottleneck in responding to the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. The lack of such devices dramatically raises the mortality rate of COVID-19.\n\n=== Oxygenation mask ===\n[[File:Decathlon_Easybreath_snorkel_mask.jpg|thumb|Common snorkeling masks have been adapted into oxygenation masks via minor changes and 3D-printed adapters.]]\nPopular [[Snorkeling]] masks have been adapted into oxygen dispensing emergency respiratory masks via the usage of 3D printed adapters and minimal modifications to the original mask.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w4Csqdxkrfw|title=Video: Emergency mask for hospital ventilators|date=n.d.|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325193405/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w4Csqdxkrfw|archive-date=25 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.isinnova.it/easy-covid19-eng/|title=Easy \u2013 Covid19 : Emergency mask for hospital ventilators|last=Isinnova|date=n.d.|website=Isinnova|language=it-IT|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324231946/https://www.isinnova.it/easy-covid19-eng/|archive-date=24 March 2020|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> According to Italian laws relative to medical cares where the project has occurs, usage by the patient requires a signed declaration of acceptance of use of an uncertified biomedical device.<ref name=\":5\" /> The project provides the 3D files for free, as well as 2 forms to register hospitals in need and 3D makers willing to produces adapters.<ref name=\":5\" />\nFrance main sportwear and snorkeling masks producer [[Decathlon]] has locked down is mask sales to redirect them toward medical staff, patients and 3D makers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uZ5Vtf69cAA |title=Pourquoi ne pas distribuer des masques de plong\u00e9e D\u00e9cathlon? BFMTV r\u00e9pond \u00e0 vos questions |via=YouTube |date=n.d.|accessdate=1 April 2020|language=French}}</ref>\n\n=== Intensive care beds ===\n{{See also|List of countries by hospital beds}}\nBoth rich countries and [[developing countries]] have or will face [[intensive care beds]] shortages, but the situation is expected to be more intense in developing countries due to lower equipment levels.<ref name=scmp3077552>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/opinion/article/3077552/why-coronavirus-lockdowns-will-not-be-easy-developing-countries |title=Why coronavirus lockdowns will not be easy for developing countries, and what they can learn |work=South China Morning Post |date=n.d.|accessdate=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330120606/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/opinion/article/3077552/why-coronavirus-lockdowns-will-not-be-easy-developing-countries |archive-date=30 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn early March, the UK government supported a strategy to develop natural [[herd immunity]], drawing sharp criticism from medical personnel and researchers.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/u-k-realized-its-coronavirus-plan-could-kill-over-100-000.html|title=U.K. Only Grasped in the 'Last Few Days' It Had the Exact Wrong Coronavirus Plan|last=Stieb|first=Matt|date=16 March 2020|website=Intelligencer|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317215047/https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/u-k-realized-its-coronavirus-plan-could-kill-over-100-000.html|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Various forecasts by [[Imperial College COVID-19 Response Team]], made public on 16 March, suggested that the peak number of cases in the UK would require between 100 and 225 CCBs / 100,000 inhabitants,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-COVID19-NPI-modelling-16-03-2020.pdf|title=Impact of non-pharmaceutical interventions (NPIs) to reduce COVID19 mortality and healthcare demand|last=Imperial College COVID-19 Response Team|date=16 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316223332/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-COVID19-NPI-modelling-16-03-2020.pdf|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> if proper mitigation or no mitigation strategies are put into force, respectively. These requirements would both exceed the UK's current capacities of 6.6<ref name=\"Rhodes2012a2\">{{cite journal|last=Rhodes|first=A.|last2=Ferdinande|first2=P.|last3=Flaatten|first3=H.|last4=Guidet|first4=B.|last5=Metnitz|first5=P. G.|last6=Moreno|first6=R. P.|date=1 October 2012|title=The variability of critical care bed numbers in Europe|journal=Intensive Care Medicine|volume=38|issue=10|pages=1647\u20131653|doi=10.1007/s00134-012-2627-8|pmid=22777516|issn=1432-1238}}</ref>\u201314<ref name=\":0\" /> CCB / 100,000 inhabitants. In the best case scenario, the peak caseload would require 7.5 times the current number of available ICU beds.<ref name=20200315co>{{Cite news|last=Batchelor|first=George|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/hospitals-could-need-75-times-number-critical-care-beds-treat/|title=Hospitals could need 7.5 times the number of critical care beds to treat virus patients|date=15 March 2020|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=17 March 2020|issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323151959/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/hospitals-could-need-75-times-number-critical-care-beds-treat/|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Around 16 March, the UK government changed trajectory toward a more standard mitigation/suppression strategy.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|France]], around 15 March, the [[Grand Est]] region was the first to express the scarcity of CCB limiting its handling of the crisis.<ref name=europe13955371>{{cite web|url=https://www.europe1.fr/sante/coronavirus-dans-le-grand-est-pratiquement-tous-les-lits-de-reanimation-sont-occupes-3955371|title=Coronavirus : dans le Grand Est, \"pratiquement tous les lits de r\u00e9animation sont occup\u00e9s\"|website=Europe 1|access-date=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317174350/https://www.europe1.fr/sante/coronavirus-dans-le-grand-est-pratiquement-tous-les-lits-de-reanimation-sont-occupes-3955371|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Assistance Publique \u2013 H\u00f4pitaux de Paris|Assistance-publique H\u00f4pitaux de Paris]] (AP-HP), which manages most hospitals in the French capital area (~10&nbsp;million inhabitants), reported the need for 3,000\u20134,000 ICUs.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2020/03/17/covid-19-des-milliers-de-lits-de-reanimation-necessaires-dans-les-hopitaux-parisiens_6033380_3244.html|title=Covid-19 : l'AP-HP s'attend \u00e0 faire face \u00e0 une vague d'hospitalisation bien plus haute que pr\u00e9vu|date=17 March 2020|work=Le Monde.fr|accessdate=17 March 2020|language=fr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323151957/https://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2020/03/17/covid-19-des-milliers-de-lits-de-reanimation-necessaires-dans-les-hopitaux-parisiens_6033380_3244.html|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Current capacity is reported to be between 1500<ref name=\":1\" /> and 350,<ref>See [[:fr:Assistance Publique \u2013 H\u00f4pitaux de Paris|Assistance Publique \u2013 H\u00f4pitaux de Paris]].</ref> depending on the source.\n\nIn France, given shortages of ICU hospital beds in [[Grand Est]] and [[Ile-de-France]] regions, severe but stable patients with ARS and breathing assistance have been moved toward other regional medical centers within France, Germany, Austria, Luxembourg or Switzerland.<ref name=bfmtv1235967>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfmtv.com/mediaplayer/video/les-transferts-de-malades-du-coronavirus-se-poursuivent-pour-desengorger-les-regions-saturees-1235967.html|title=Les transferts de malades du coronavirus se poursuivent pour d\u00e9sengorger les r\u00e9gions satur\u00e9es|via=bfmtv.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Mechanical ventilation ===\n[[Mechanical ventilation]] have been called ''\"the device that becomes the decider between life and death\"''<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90477940/these-good-samaritans-with-a-3d-printer-are-saving-lives-by-making-new-respirator-valves-for-free|title=These Good Samaritans with a 3D printer are saving lives by making new respirator valves for free|last=Toussaint|first=Kristin|date=16 March 2020|publisher=Fast Company|access-date=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326042513/https://www.fastcompany.com/90477940/these-good-samaritans-with-a-3d-printer-are-saving-lives-by-making-new-respirator-valves-for-free|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> for COVID-19 patients, due to COVID19 being a respiratory disease sending all about 5% of detected cases to rely on the device now in shortage.<ref name=\":6\" /> Ventilators shortage is endemic in the [[Developing country|developing world]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Krishnamoorthy|first=Vijay|last2=Vavilala|first2=Monica S.|last3=Mock|first3=Charles N.|year=2014|title=The need for ventilators in the developing world: An opportunity to improve care and save lives|journal=Journal of Global Health|volume=4|issue=1|page=010303|doi=10.7189/jogh.04.010303|issn=2047-2978|pmc=4073242|pmid=24976958}}</ref> In case of shortage, some triage strategies have been previously discussed. One strategy is to grade the patient on dimensions such as : prospects for short-term survival ; prospects for long-term survival ; stage of life-related considerations ; pregnancy and fair chance.<ref name=\"Daugherty Biddison 848\u2013854\" /> The frequent 15 to 20 days duration of the intubation to recover is an important factor in the ventilator's shortage.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Facing Covid-19 in Italy \u2013 Ethics, Logistics, and Therapeutics on the Epidemic's Front Line|first=Lisa|last=Rosenbaum|date=18 March 2020|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=0|doi=10.1056/NEJMp2005492|pmid = 32187459}}</ref>\n\nAn important way of reducing demand for ventilators is the use of CPAP devices as a first resort.  For this reason CPAP devices themselves have become a scarce item.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==== Officials assessments ====\nIn the 2000s, the US CDC estimated a shortage of 40~70,000 ventilators in case of pandemic influenza.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|last=Kulish|first=Nicholas|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/29/business/coronavirus-us-ventilator-shortage.html|title=The U.S. Tried to Build a New Fleet of Ventilators. The Mission Failed.|date=29 March 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=29 March 2020|last2=Kliff|first2=Sarah|issn=0362-4331|last3=Silver-Greenberg|first3=Jessica|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329151242/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/29/business/coronavirus-us-ventilator-shortage.html|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> From this assessment resulted ''Project Aura'', a public-private initiative to design a frugal, 3,000 US$ mechanical ventilator, simple to mass-produce, and able to supply the [[Strategic National Stockpile]].<ref name=\":12\" /> [[Newport Medical Instruments]] was granted the contract, designing and prototyping (2011) the frugal ventilators to CDC officials, and expecting to later profit from the product by moving into the private market were other competing devices were sold for 10,000US$.<ref name=\":12\" /> On April 2012, [[United States Department of Health and Human Services|US Health and Human Services]] officials confirmed to the [[United States Congress|US Congress]] that the project was on schedule to file for market approval in late 2013, after which the device would go into mass-production.<ref name=\":12\" /> In May 2012, US$12&nbsp;billion-worth medical conglomerate [[Covidien]], a top actor of the mechanical ventilation market, acquired Newport for 100 million US$.<ref name=\":12\" /> Covidien soon asked to cancel the ''Project Aura'' contract since it wasn't profitable enough.<ref name=\":12\" /> Former Newport executives, government officials and executives at rival ventilator companies suspect Covidien acquired Newport to prevent the frugal 3,000 ventilator design from disturbing its profitable ventilation operation.<ref name=\":12\" /> Covidien has merged in 2015 into [[Medtronic]].<ref name=\":12\" />  ''Project Aura'' looked for and then signed a new contract with [[Philips healthcare]]. In July 2019, the [[Food and Drug Administration|FDA]] signed for 10,000 units of their [[Trilogy Evo]] portable ventilator, to be delivered to the SNS by mid-2020.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nOn 25 March, Andrew Cuomo made a detailed 1-hour COVID-19 press conference,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pscp.tv/NYGovCuomo/1DXxyeovOoYxM|title=Andrew Cuomo @NYGovCuomo|last=Inc|first=Twitter|website=Periscope|access-date=26 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327001048/https://www.pscp.tv/NYGovCuomo/1DXxyeovOoYxM|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=20200325youtube>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wjGq1SsuPwU|title=New York Gov. Cuomo holds briefing on the coronavirus pandemic|date=25 March 2020|website=|publisher=CNBC|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331205742/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wjGq1SsuPwU|archive-date=31 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref> emphasising an expectation of a severe shortage of ventilators, and their importance in sustaining life in severe COVID-19 cases.<ref name=\":11\">{{cite web|url=https://www.governor.ny.gov/news/video-audio-photos-rush-transcript-amid-ongoing-covid-19-pandemic-governor-cuomo-announces-2|title=Video, Audio, Photos & Rush Transcript: Amid Ongoing COVID-19 Pandemic, Governor Cuomo Announces 40,000 Health Professionals Have Signed Up to Volunteer as Part of The State's Surge Healthcare Force|date=25 March 2020|website=Governor Andrew M. Cuomo|access-date=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327001059/https://www.governor.ny.gov/news/video-audio-photos-rush-transcript-amid-ongoing-covid-19-pandemic-governor-cuomo-announces-2|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Cuomo said New York state would ultimately need about 30,000 ventilators to handle the influx, while having only 4,000 as of 25 March; on the 27th, President Trump expressed doubt about the need, saying \"I don't believe you need 40,000 or 30,000 ventilators,\" and resisting calls to force businesses to produce them.<ref name=20200327theguardian>{{Cite news|last=Evelyn|first=Kenya|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/27/trump-ventilators-coronavirus-cuomo-new-york|title=Trump on urgent requests for ventilators: 'I don't believe you need 30,000'|date=27 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=28 March 2020|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328152527/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/27/trump-ventilators-coronavirus-cuomo-new-york|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":11\" /> Later on the 27th, the President acceded to calls to assist states in ventilator procurement, using the [[Defense Production Act of 1950|Defense Production Act]]; fears remain that procurement will not happen in time to prevent severe shortages.<ref name=20200327com/2020/03/27/us/politics/coronavirus-trump-ventilators-gm-ventec>{{Cite news|last=Sanger|first=David E.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/27/us/politics/coronavirus-trump-ventilators-gm-ventec.html|title=Under Intense Criticism, Trump Says Government Will Buy More Ventilators|date=27 March 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=28 March 2020|last2=Haberman|first2=Maggie|issn=0362-4331|last3=Karni|first3=Annie|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328151652/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/27/us/politics/coronavirus-trump-ventilators-gm-ventec.html|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Industrial suppliers ====\nIn Europe, the company [[L\u00f6wenstein Medical]] producing 1500 ICU-level ventilators and 20,000 home-level ventilator per year for France alone, pointed out of the current high demand and production shortage.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/replay-radio/l-interview-eco/coronavirus-la-demande-en-ventilateurs-et-respirateurs-artificiels-est-devenue-colossale-explique-un-specialiste-dans-le-materiel-medical_3849549.html|title=Coronavirus : la demande en ventilateurs et respirateurs artificiels est devenue \"colossale\", explique un sp\u00e9cialiste dans le mat\u00e9riel m\u00e9dical|date=17 March 2020|website=Franceinfo|language=fr|access-date=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319185356/https://www.francetvinfo.fr/replay-radio/l-interview-eco/coronavirus-la-demande-en-ventilateurs-et-respirateurs-artificiels-est-devenue-colossale-explique-un-specialiste-dans-le-materiel-medical_3849549.html|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Based in Europe, all their components are European and not relying on Chinese's supply chain.<ref name=\":3\" /> As for production ramp up, it was suggested to increase the production of home-level ventilators, more basic and which can be assembled in half an hour yet able to support patients through [[acute respiratory distress syndrome]].<ref name=\":3\" /> The current bottleneck is mainly a question of qualified human resources.<ref name=\":3\" /> In business as usual, ICU-level ventilators are to be renewed every 10 to 15 years.<ref name=\":3\" /> Due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], Germany and other European countries have started to take control over the company's supply.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn China, local manufacturers are racing to answer the demand.<ref name=scmp3076657>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/business/companies/article/3076657/chinas-factories-work-24/7-build-medical-ventilators-milan-new|title=China's factories work 24/7 to build ventilators for Milan, New York|date=24 March 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=25 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325225951/https://www.scmp.com/business/companies/article/3076657/chinas-factories-work-24/7-build-medical-ventilators-milan-new|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Medtronic]] made ventilator design specifications publicly available.<ref>{{cite news |title=Medtronic is sharing its portable ventilator design specifications and code for free to all |url=https://techcrunch.com/2020/03/30/medtronic-is-sharing-its-portable-ventilator-design-specifications-and-code-for-free-to-all/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=TechCrunch |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401182148/https://techcrunch.com/2020/03/30/medtronic-is-sharing-its-portable-ventilator-design-specifications-and-code-for-free-to-all/ |archive-date=1 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== Hackers ====\n{{See also|Open-source ventilator}}\n[[File:Open_source_ventilator-OpenLung-01-design.png|thumb|500px|The Open Source Ventilator's OpenLung project, an open source, low resource, quick deployment [[:en:mechanical ventilator|mechanical ventilator]] design uses a [[:bag valve mask|bag valve mask]] (BVM or Ambu-bag) as a core component.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gitlab.com/open-source-ventilator/OpenLung|title=Open Source Ventilator / OpenLung BVM Ventilator|website=GitLab|access-date=28 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327173607/https://gitlab.com/open-source-ventilator/OpenLung|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>]]\n3D makers have been working on various low-cost alternative ventilation devices or adaptations.\n\nAnaesthetist Dr. Alan Gauthier from [[Ontario]], Canada, turned one single-patient ventilator into a nine-patient device thanks to a 2006 YouTube video by 2 doctors from Detroit.<ref name=\":4\" /> The method uses T-shaped tubes to split airflow and multiply the number of patients provided with respiratory support.\n\nIn Ireland, volunteers started the ''Open Source Ventilator Project'' in collaboration with medical staff.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn Italy, local journalist and journal director Nunzia Vallini of the ''[[Giornale di Brescia]] (Brescia Daily)'' was informed that nearby [[Chiari, Lombardy|Chiani]] hospital was running out of valves which mix oxygen with air and are therefore a critical part of reanimation devices.<ref name=\":6\" /> The valves supplier was itself out of stock leading to patient deaths.<ref name=\":6\" /> Vallini contacted [[Fab lab|FabLab]] founder Massimo Temporelli, which invited Michele Faini, an expert in 3D print manufacturing and a research and development designer at Lonati SpA to join a 3D printing effort.<ref name=\":6\" /> When the supplier didn't wish to share the design's specifics, they reverse-engineered the valves and produced a limited not-for-profit series for local hospitals.<ref name=\":6\" /> To satisfy biomedical requirements that can withstand periodic sanitation, Lonati SpA used their SLS 3D printers to print about 100 valves in [[Nylon 12|Nylon PA12]].<ref name=\":6\" /> Faini and Temporelli still acknowledge the limitations of their production: 3D printing not being able to reach the quality and sterilised context of the original valves and manufacturing process.<ref name=\":6\" /> Contrary to rumors online, the valves don't cost {{usd|10,000}} each and the original manufacturer did not threaten to sue the 3D printers team.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nHackers of the ''Ventilator Project'' have brainstormed to propose to re-purposing [[CPAP machine]]s (sleep-apnea masks) as ventilators, hacking single ventilators to split air-flow and treat multiple patients, and using grounded airplanes as treatment facilities to leverage their one-oxygen-mask-per-seat infrastructure.<ref name=\"nyMCGuyvers\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/04/06/the-macgyvers-taking-on-the-ventilator-shortage|title=The MacGyvers Taking on the Ventilator Shortage|first=Tyler|last=Foggatt|website=The New Yorker|access-date=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327203202/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/04/06/the-macgyvers-taking-on-the-ventilator-shortage|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Engineers familiar with devices design and production, medical professionals familiar existing respiratory devices and lawyers able to navigate FDA regulations if the needs arise are key participants among the 350 volunteers involved.<ref name=\"nyMCGuyvers\" /> The central avenue of exploration is to ditch away the most advances features of modern mechanical ventilation, which includes layers of electronics and patients monitoring systems, to focus solely on assisted respiration by pressured airflow. The group is, by example, looking for an old [[Harry Diamond Labs]] \"emergency army respirator\" model to study.<ref name=\"nyMCGuyvers\" /> While hopeful they will be able to submit viable and mass-producible design, several questions linger at this later levels: mass production line, FDA approval, personnel training, personnel availability, and eventually actual needs on the battlegrounds to come.<ref name=\"nyMCGuyvers\" />\n\nAn MIT team has designed an emergency ventilator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.mit.edu/2020/ventilator-covid-deployment-open-source-low-cost-0326|title=MIT-based team works on rapid deployment of open-source, low-cost ventilator|website=MIT News|access-date=28 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328084324/http://news.mit.edu/2020/ventilator-covid-deployment-open-source-low-cost-0326|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== ECMOs ===\n[[Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation]] are devices able to replace both the lungs and the patient's heart. As of 6 February 2020, the medical community was encouraged to set up criteria for ECMO patients triage.<ref name=\"Ronco 240\u2013241\"/>\n\n== Facilities ==\nAs Wuhan's situation worsened and to assist the overwhelmed [[Central Hospital of Wuhan]] and [[Dabie Mountain Regional Medical Centre]], China built two emergency field hospital within a few days: the [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] and [[Leishenshan Hospital]]. The hospitals were progressively phased out in March 2020.<ref name=channelnewsasia12490222>{{cite web |title=Wuhan closes makeshift hospital as new COVID-19 cases in China drop sharply |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/coronavirus-wuhan-closes-makeshift-hospital-china-cases-drop-12490222 |website=CNA |accessdate=3 March 2020 |date=2 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"aisachanews\">{{cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/coronavirus-china-wuhan-hubei-makeshift-hospitals-closed-12517390 |title=China closes makeshift hospitals as COVID-19 cases plunge |website=CNA  |access-date=27 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327122456/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/coronavirus-china-wuhan-hubei-makeshift-hospitals-closed-12517390 |archive-date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, Lieutenant General [[Todd T. Semonite]], Chief of the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]], signaled an ongoing effort to lease existing facilities such as hostels, [[College dormitory|college dormitories]], and a larger hall to temporarily convert them into medical facilities.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 16 March, French President [[Emmanuel Macron]] announced a military hospital would be set up in the Grand-Est region, to provide up to 30 ICU beds.<ref name=liberation1782133>{{cite news|url=https://www.liberation.fr/france/2020/03/17/aide-de-l-armee-la-france-dans-les-bras-de-morphee_1782133|title=Aide de l'arm\u00e9e : la France dans les bras de \"Morph\u00e9e\"|date=17 March 2020|work=Lib\u00e9ration|access-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live|language=French|trans-title=Aid from the Army: France in the arms of \"Morpheus\"|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324094601/https://www.liberation.fr/france/2020/03/17/aide-de-l-armee-la-france-dans-les-bras-de-morphee_1782133|archive-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> The hospital was being tested 7 days later.<ref name=lemonde6034110>{{cite news|last=S\u00e9bastien|first=Bozon|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2020/03/23/coronavirus-voici-a-quoi-ressemble-l-hopital-militaire-installe-a-mulhouse_6034110_3244.html|title=Coronavirus : voici \u00e0 quoi ressemble l'h\u00f4pital militaire install\u00e9 \u00e0 Mulhouse|date=23 March 2020|work=Le Monde|access-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live|language=French|trans-title=Coronavirus: this is what the military hospital in Mulhouse looks like|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323203541/https://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2020/03/23/coronavirus-voici-a-quoi-ressemble-l-hopital-militaire-installe-a-mulhouse_6034110_3244.html|archive-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy 8 March, [[Lombardy]] had created 482 new I.C.U beds answers to the initial shortage.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|last=Marcolini|first=Barbara|url=https://www.nytimes.com/video/world/europe/100000007045579/coronavirus-italy-doctors-lombardy-hospitals-video.html|title='Brace Yourself': How Doctors in Italy Responded to Coronavirus|date=23 March 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live|last2=Stein|first2=Robin|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326121523/https://www.nytimes.com/video/world/europe/100000007045579/coronavirus-italy-doctors-lombardy-hospitals-video.html|archive-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> [[Lodi, Lombardy|Lodi]]'s ICU director reported that every single square metre, every single aisle of the hospital had been repurposed for severe COVID-19 patients, increasing ICU beds from 7 to 24.<ref name=\":9\" /> In [[Monza]], 3 new wards of 50 beds each were opened on 17 March.<ref name=\":9\" /> In [[Bergamo]], gastrology, internal medicine, neurology services have been repurposed.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nIn the UK almost the entire private health stock of beds was requisitioned, providing an additional 8,000 beds.<ref name=co7027196>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/policy-and-regulation/nhs-block-books-almost-all-private-hospital-sector-capacity-to-fight-covid-19/7027196.article|title=NHS block books almost all private hospital sector capacity to fight covid-19|first=James|last=Illman|website=Health Service Journal|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> Three [[NHS Nightingale Hospitals|Nightingale hospitals]] were created by [[NHS England]], with the military, to provide an additional 10\u201311,000 critical care beds, another 1,000 bed hospital created in Scotland, and a 3,000 bed hospital at the [[Principality Stadium]] in Cardiff.  Temporary wards were constructed in hospital car parks, and existing wards re-organised to free up 33,000 beds in England and 3,000 in Scotland for COVID-19 patients.<ref name=\"Look inside\"/> A hanger at [[Birmingham International Airport]] was converted into a 12,000 body mortuary.<ref name=\"Look inside\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2020/03/look-inside-london-nightingale-temporary-hospitals-coronavirus/|title=Take a look inside NHS Nightingale, London's new coronavirus hospital|website=World Economic Forum|accessdate=2 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403004905/https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2020/03/look-inside-london-nightingale-temporary-hospitals-coronavirus/|archive-date=3 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Health workers ==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\nThe factors in health worker shortage are several.  First, the excess demand due to the pandemic.  Second, the specialised nature of care of the critically ill and the time taken to train for new methods of working to prevent cross-contamination, in some cases with new types of protective equipment (PPE).  The third factor is the loss of staff to the pandemic, mostly because they are self-isolating with symptoms (which may be unrelated) or because a household member has symptoms, but also because of long term effects of the disease, or death.  This last case applies across the health system and makes it harder to draw staff from non-COVID health workers.\n\nMitigations being used include recruiting military and sports medics, final-year doctors in training, private sector staff, and re-recruiting retired staff and those who have moved from the medical sector.\n\nFor non-medical roles staff have been recruited from other sectors.\n\n=== Patients overload===\nMayor De Blasio made a call for medical staffs.<ref name=20200403com/2020/04/03/opinion/coronavirus-deblasio-nyc>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/03/opinion/coronavirus-deblasio-nyc.html|title=Opinion: We Need All Medical Workers on the Front Lines|first=Bill|last=de Blasio|date=3 April 2020|work=The New York Times}}</ref>{{explain|date=March 2020}}\n\n=== Isolation and trauma ===\n{{See also|Mental health during the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n====China====\nAs for China, medical staff are self isolating from families and under high emotional pressure.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nPsychological trauma is expected among medical professionals.<ref name=\"nytSick0329\">{{cite news |author=Jennifer Senior |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/29/opinion/coronavirus-ventilators-rationing-triage.html |title=Opinion &#124; Doctors Must Ration Ventilators as Coronavirus Rages. The Decisions Are Painful. |work=The New York Times |date=n.d.|accessdate=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330133854/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/29/opinion/coronavirus-ventilators-rationing-triage.html |archive-date=30 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{clarify|date=March 2020}}\n\n=== Sickness and death ===\nAt least 50 Chinese doctors died.<ref name=20200324com/2020/03/30/nyregion/ny-coronavirus-doctors-sick>{{cite news |author=Michael Schwirtz |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/nyregion/ny-coronavirus-doctors-sick.html |title=Nurses Die, Doctors Fall Sick and Panic Rises on Virus Front Lines|work=The New York Times |date=24 March 2020 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330101607/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/nyregion/ny-coronavirus-doctors-sick.html |archive-date=30 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn [[Lombardy]], Italy, with the mid-March 2020 outbreak, medical staff reported high level of sick staff.<ref name=\":9\" /> In Lodi, doctors from other services have been called to attend Covid patients.<ref name=\":9\" /> In [[Cremona]], the number of patients entries was three times the usual while services were running with 50% of their staff.<ref name=\":9\" /> On 12 March 8% of Italy's 13,382 cases were health workers.<ref name=\":9\" /> It was also reported that between 5 and 10% of deaths were medical staff.<ref name=\":9\" /> On 17 March, one of the largest hospital of the [[Bergamo]] region ran out of [[Intensive care unit|ICU beds]], patients were flown to other regions by helicopter.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nAbout 14% of Spanish cases are medical staff.<ref name=\"nytSick0329\" />\n\n== Groceries ==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:2020-03-14 Desabastiment a Consum Rafelbunyol per compra compulsiva pel COVID-19 02.jpg|thumb|Almost empty shelves in a [[Consum supermarkets|Consum]] supermarket on 14 March, though plenty of produce can be seen in the next bay an in the background.]]\nSome daily goods have seen shortages, mainly due to [[panic buying]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n<!-- Vitamin C also if citation can be found -->\n\n===Soap===\n\n\n===Hand sanitiser===\n\n\n===Toilet paper===\n\n\n===Paracetemol===\n\n\n===Pasta===\n\n\n===Condoms===\nThe shortage of condoms is possible.<ref name=20200327theguardian2>{{cite web |author=Reuters in Kuala Lumpur |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/27/global-condom-shortage-coronavirus-shuts-down-production |title=Global condom shortage looms as coronavirus shuts down production  |work=The Guardian |date=n.d.|accessdate=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327180211/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/27/global-condom-shortage-coronavirus-shuts-down-production |archive-date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Others ==\nIn France, due to closed borders and the impossibility for foreign seasonal worker to come over,<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bfmtv.com/economie/coronavirus-la-cueillette-des-fraises-menacee-par-le-manque-de-main-d-oeuvre-et-de-debouches-1881783.html|title=Coronavirus: la cueillette des fraises menac\u00e9e par le manque de main d'oeuvre et de d\u00e9bouch\u00e9s|last=BFMTV|publisher=BFMTV|language=fr|access-date=26 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326150948/https://www.bfmtv.com/economie/coronavirus-la-cueillette-des-fraises-menacee-par-le-manque-de-main-d-oeuvre-et-de-debouches-1881783.html|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the government's [[Didier Guillaume|Minister of Agriculture]] called for jobless volunteers to contact [[Strawberry|strawberries farms]] and help collect the harvest for the usual [[Minimum wage|minimal wage]].<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nLaboratory mice are being culled, and some strains are at risk of shortage due to lockdowns.<ref name=20200323sciencemag>{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/it-s-heartbreaking-labs-are-euthanizing-thousands-mice-response-coronavirus-pandemic|title='It's heartbreaking.' Labs are euthanizing thousands of mice in response to coronavirus pandemic|last=Grimm |first=David|date=23 March 2020|website=Science {{!}} AAAS|access-date=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328234927/https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/it-s-heartbreaking-labs-are-euthanizing-thousands-mice-response-coronavirus-pandemic|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{annotated link|List of countries by hospital beds}}\n* {{annotated link|Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation}}\n* {{annotated link|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n==References==\n{{clear}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|data}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Socio-economic impact of the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Shortages]]\n[[Category:2020 in international relations]]\n[[Category:Market (economics)]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "unneeded bolding, alpha see also", "url_page": "//en.wi